{"title_page": "The Terror State", "text_new": "{{Infobox album|\n| name       = The Terror State\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Anti-Flag]]\n| cover      = The Terror State.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = October 21, 2003\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Punk rock]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.phoenixnewtimes.com/music/10-best-political-punk-rock-albums-of-all-time-7388653|title=10 Best Political Punk Albums|work=Phoenix New Times|author=Chesler, Josh|date=June 8, 2015|accessdate=June 12, 2016}}</ref>\n| length     = 36:48\n| label      = [[Fat Wreck Chords]]\n| producer   = [[Tom Morello]], Nick DiDia\n| prev_title = [[BYO Split Series, Vol. 4]]\n| prev_year  = 2002\n| next_title = [[Death of a Nation (video album)|Death of a Nation]]\n| next_year  = 2004\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n|rev1 = [[AllMusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>[{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r662900|pure_url=yes}} Allmusic review]</ref>\n|rev2 = Punknews.org\n|rev2score = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref>[http://www.punknews.org/review/2371 Punknews.org review]</ref>\n}}<!-- Automatically generated by DASHBot-->\n\n'''''The Terror State''''' is the fifth studio album by Pittsburgh [[punk rock]] band [[Anti-Flag]], released on October 21, 2003, on [[Fat Wreck Chords]].  The album's artwork was regarded as somewhat controversial (picturing lead vocalist Justin Sane's niece, Rachel, amongst rubble and holding an automatic handgun), and the band was forced to create an alternate version (which was simply all black with the Terror State logo centered) for sale in some larger chain stores, such as [[Wal-Mart]].<ref>{Sounds Like A Revolution Documentary}</ref>\n\nProduced by [[Tom Morello]], ''The Terror State'' was hailed as Anti-Flag's most polished album to date.  The album made #1 on [[KTUH]]'s charts on the week of January 19, 2004.<ref>[http://ktuh.fm/charts/2004/01/19 ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081031132633/http://ktuh.fm/charts/2004/01/19 |date=October 31, 2008 }}</ref> As of April 3, 2008, the album had sold 106,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08094/870050-42.stm |title=Anti-Flag: Frequently Asked Questions |publisher=Post-gazette.com |date=2008-04-03 |accessdate=2012-03-11}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{tracklist\n|title1 =Turncoat\n|length1 =2:10\n|title2 =Rank-N-File\n|length2 =3:46\n|title3 =Post-War Breakout ([[Woody Guthrie]])\n|length3 =3:11\n|title4 =Sold as Freedom\n|length4 =2:16\n|title5 =Power to the Peaceful\n|length5 =2:57\n|title6 =Mind the [[General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade|G.A.T.T.]]\n|length6 =3:14\n|title7 =You Can Kill the Protester, But You Can't Kill the Protest\n|length7 =2:33\n|title8 =When You Don't Control Your Government People Want to Kill You\n|length8 =2:47\n|title9 =Wake Up!\n|length9 =2:35\n|title10 =Tearing Down the Borders\n|length10 =3:07\n|title11 =Death of a Nation\n|length11 =1:55\n|title12 =[[Operation Iraqi Liberation]]\n|length12 =2:21\n|title13 =One People, One Struggle\n|length13 =3:01\n|title14 =Fuck the Flag\n|note14 = bonus track (Only available on the LP or the first 15,000 pressings of the CD)\n|length14 =0:52\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n* [[Justin Sane]] - guitar, lead vocals on tracks 1, 2, 4, 6, 8, 10, 12, 14\n* Chris Head - guitar, backing vocals\n* Chris #2 - bass guitar, lead vocals on tracks 3, 5, 7, 9, 11, 13, 14\n* [[Pat Thetic]] - drums\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Anti-Flag}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Terror State, The}}\n[[Category:2003 albums]]\n[[Category:Anti-Flag albums]]\n[[Category:Fat Wreck Chords albums]]\n\n\n{{2000s-punk-album-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox album|\n| name       = The Terror State\n| type       = studio\n| artist     = [[Anti-Flag]]\n| cover      = The Terror State.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = October 21, 2003\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     =\n| genre      = [[Punk rock]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.phoenixnewtimes.com/music/10-best-political-punk-rock-albums-of-all-time-7388653|title=10 Best Political Punk Albums|work=Phoenix New Times|author=Chesler, Josh|date=June 8, 2015|accessdate=June 12, 2016}}</ref>\n| length     = 36:48\n| label      = [[Fat Wreck Chords]]\n| producer   = [[Tom Morello]], Nick DiDia\n| prev_title = [[BYO Split Series, Vol. 4]]\n| prev_year  = 2002\n| next_title = [[Death of a Nation (video album)|Death of a Nation]]\n| next_year  = 2004\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n|rev1 = [[Allmusic]]\n|rev1score = {{Rating|4|5}}<ref>[{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r662900|pure_url=yes}} Allmusic review]</ref>\n|rev2 = Punknews.org\n|rev2score = {{Rating|4.5|5}}<ref>[http://www.punknews.org/review/2371 Punknews.org review]</ref>\n}}<!-- Automatically generated by DASHBot-->\n\n'''''The Terror State''''' is the fifth studio album by Pittsburgh [[punk rock]] band [[Anti-Flag]]; released October 21, 2003 on the independent label [[Fat Wreck Chords]].  The album's artwork was regarded as somewhat controversial (picturing lead vocalist Justin Sane's niece, Rachel, amongst rubble holding an automatic handgun), and the band was forced to create an alternate version (which was simply all black with the Terror State logo centered) for sale in some larger chain stores, such as [[Wal-Mart]].<ref>{Sounds Like A Revolution Documentary}</ref>\n\nProduced by [[Rage Against the Machine]] guitarist [[Tom Morello]], ''The Terror State'' was hailed as Anti-Flag's most polished album to date.  The album made #1 on [[KTUH]]'s charts on the week of January 19, 2004.<ref>[http://ktuh.fm/charts/2004/01/19 ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20081031132633/http://ktuh.fm/charts/2004/01/19 |date=October 31, 2008 }}</ref> As of April 3, 2008, the album has sold 106,000 copies.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.post-gazette.com/pg/08094/870050-42.stm |title=Anti-Flag: Frequently Asked Questions |publisher=Post-gazette.com |date=2008-04-03 |accessdate=2012-03-11}}</ref>\n\n==Track listing==\n{{tracklist\n|title1 =Turncoat\n|length1 =2:10\n|title2 =Rank-N-File\n|length2 =3:46\n|title3 =Post-War Breakout ([[Woody Guthrie]])\n|length3 =3:11\n|title4 =Sold as Freedom\n|length4 =2:16\n|title5 =Power to the Peaceful\n|length5 =2:57\n|title6 =Mind the [[General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade|G.A.T.T.]]\n|length6 =3:14\n|title7 =You Can Kill the Protester, But You Can't Kill the Protest\n|length7 =2:33\n|title8 =When You Don't Control Your Government People Want to Kill You\n|length8 =2:47\n|title9 =Wake Up!\n|length9 =2:35\n|title10 =Tearing Down the Borders\n|length10 =3:07\n|title11 =Death of a Nation\n|length11 =1:55\n|title12 =[[Operation Iraqi Liberation]]\n|length12 =2:21\n|title13 =One People, One Struggle\n|length13 =3:01\n|title14 =Fuck the Flag\n|note14 = bonus track (Only available on the LP or the first 15,000 pressings of the CD)\n|length14 =0:52\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\n* [[Justin Sane]] - guitar, lead vocals on tracks 1, 2, 4, 6, 8, 10, 12, 14\n* Chris Head - guitar, backing vocals\n* Chris #2 - bass guitar, lead vocals on tracks 3, 5, 7, 9, 11, 13, 14\n* [[Pat Thetic]] - drums\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Anti-Flag}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Terror State, The}}\n[[Category:2003 albums]]\n[[Category:Anti-Flag albums]]\n[[Category:Fat Wreck Chords albums]]\n\n\n{{2000s-punk-album-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Caro7200", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/The_Terror_State"}
