{"title_page": "Sprotbrough", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country =                  England\n|official_name =            Sprotbrough\n|static_image =             \n|coordinates = {{coord|53.5119763|-1.1881056|display=inline,title}}\n|population =               \n|map_type =                 South Yorkshire\n|metropolitan_borough =     [[Metropolitan Borough of Doncaster|Doncaster]]\n|civil_parish =             [[Sprotbrough and Cusworth]]\n|metropolitan_county =      [[South Yorkshire]]\n|region =                   Yorkshire and the Humber\n|constituency_westminster = [[Doncaster North (UK Parliament constituency)|Doncaster North]]\n|post_town =                DONCASTER\n|postcode_district =        DN5\n|postcode_area =            DN\n|dial_code =                01302\n|os_grid_reference =        SE544050\n|london_distance_mi =       145 <!-- straight line per MOS \u2013 constant and comparable with other place distances -->\n|london_direction =         SSE\n|static_image_name =        River Don lock at Sprotbrough, South Yorkshire.jpg\n|static_image_width =        240px\n|static_image_caption =\n|website =                  [http://www.sc-pc.co.uk/ Parish Council]\n}}\n'''Sprotbrough''' is a large village in [[Doncaster]], [[South Yorkshire]], England. Bounded by Cusworth (N), Warmsworth (S), Cadeby (W) and Newton (E), Sprotbrough, together with [[Cusworth]], forms the [[civil parish]] of [[Sprotbrough and Cusworth]] (sometimes Sprotbrough with Cusworth).\nHome to many sad people who sit on Facebook all day\nSprotbrough Village harbours the Grade I listed St Mary's Church and The Old Rectory \u2013 the childhood home of Second World War flying ace [[Douglas Bader]].\n\nThe place-name 'Sprotbrough' is first attested in the [[Domesday Book]] of 1086, where it appears as ''Sproteburg''. The name is thought to mean 'Sprot's borough'.<ref>[[Eilert Ekwall]], ''The Concise Oxford Dictionary of English Place-names'', p.435.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Sprotbrough and Cusworth]]\n*[[Cusworth]]\n*[[Bentley, South Yorkshire|Bentley]]\n*[[Scawsby]]\n*[[St George's Minster, Doncaster]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Doncaster]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country =                  England\n|official_name =            Sprotbrough\n|static_image =             \n|coordinates = {{coord|53.5119763|-1.1881056|display=inline,title}}\n|population =               \n|map_type =                 South Yorkshire\n|metropolitan_borough =     [[Metropolitan Borough of Doncaster|Doncaster]]\n|civil_parish =             [[Sprotbrough and Cusworth]]\n|metropolitan_county =      [[South Yorkshire]]\n|region =                   Yorkshire and the Humber\n|constituency_westminster = [[Doncaster North (UK Parliament constituency)|Doncaster North]]\n|post_town =                DONCASTER\n|postcode_district =        DN5\n|postcode_area =            DN\n|dial_code =                01302\n|os_grid_reference =        SE544050\n|london_distance_mi =       145 <!-- straight line per MOS \u2013 constant and comparable with other place distances -->\n|london_direction =         SSE\n|static_image_name =        River Don lock at Sprotbrough, South Yorkshire.jpg\n|static_image_width =        240px\n|static_image_caption =\n|website =                  [http://www.sc-pc.co.uk/ Parish Council]\n}}\n'''Sprotbrough''' is a large village in [[Doncaster]], [[South Yorkshire]], England. Bounded by Cusworth (N), Warmsworth (S), Cadeby (W) and Newton (E), Sprotbrough, together with [[Cusworth]], forms the [[civil parish]] of [[Sprotbrough and Cusworth]] (sometimes Sprotbrough with Cusworth).\n\nSprotbrough Village harbours the Grade I listed St Mary's Church and The Old Rectory \u2013 the childhood home of Second World War flying ace [[Douglas Bader]].\n\nThe place-name 'Sprotbrough' is first attested in the [[Domesday Book]] of 1086, where it appears as ''Sproteburg''. The name is thought to mean 'Sprot's borough'.<ref>[[Eilert Ekwall]], ''The Concise Oxford Dictionary of English Place-names'', p.435.</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[Sprotbrough and Cusworth]]\n*[[Cusworth]]\n*[[Bentley, South Yorkshire|Bentley]]\n*[[Scawsby]]\n*[[St George's Minster, Doncaster]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n[[Category:Villages in Doncaster]]\n", "name_user": "2a01:4c8:c62:516:adf9:543c:e1eb:f043", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sprotbrough"}
{"title_page": "Ruby", "text_new": "{{short description|Variety of corundum, mineral, gemstone}}\n{{about|the mineral or gem}}\n{{Infobox mineral\n| name        = Ruby\n| image       = File:Corundum-winza-17d.jpg\n| imagesize   = 260px\n| alt         =\n| caption     = Natural ruby crystals from [[Winza]], [[Tanzania]]\n| category    = [[Oxide mineral]] variety\n| formula     = [[aluminium oxide]] with [[chromium]], Al<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3</sub>:Cr\n| molweight   =\n| strunz      = hi Ruby ryr\n| dana        =\n| system      = [[Trigonal]] \n| class       = Hexagonal scalenohedral ({{overline|3}}m) <br/>[[H-M symbol]]: ({{overline|3}} 2/m)\n| symmetry    = ''R''{{overline|3}}c<ref>[http://webmineral.com/data/Corundum.shtml Corundum data on Webmineral] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001144657/http://webmineral.com/data/Corundum.shtml |date=October 1, 2007 }}</ref>\n| unit cell   =\n| color       = Near colorless through pink through all shades of red to a deep crimson\n| colour      =\n| habit       = Terminated tabular hexagonal prisms\n| twinning    =\n| cleavage    = No true cleavage\n| fracture    = Conchoidal, splintery\n| tenacity    = Brittle\n| mohs        = 9.0\n| luster      = Subadamantine, vitreous, pearly (on partings)\n| streak      = White\n| diaphaneity = Transparent, translucent\n| gravity     = 3.97\u20134.05\n| density     =\n| polish      =\n| opticalprop = Uniaxial/\u2212\n| refractive  = n<sub>\u03c9</sub>=1.768\u20131.772 <br/>n<sub>\u03b5</sub>=1.760\u20131.763\n| birefringence =0.008\n| pleochroism = Strong: purplish-red \u2013 orangy-red\n| 2V          =\n| dispersion  = 0.018\n| extinction  =\n| length fast/slow =\n| fluorescence = Red under longwave\n| absorption  =\n| melt        = \n| fusibility  =\n| diagnostic  =\n| solubility  = \n| impurities  =\n| alteration  =\n| other       =\n| prop1       =\n| prop1text   =\n| references  =<ref>[http://www.gemdat.org/gem-3473.html Ruby on Gemdat.org] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150317144325/http://www.gemdat.org/gem-3473.html |date=March 17, 2015 }}</ref>\n}}\n\nA '''ruby''' is a pink to blood-red colored [[gemstone]], a variety of the [[mineral]] [[corundum]] ([[aluminium oxide]]). Other varieties of gem-quality corundum are called [[sapphire]]s. Ruby is one of the traditional [[cardinal gem]]s, together with [[amethyst]], [[sapphire]], [[emerald]], and [[diamond]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=crc7ZtRHItgC&pg=PA1 ''Precious Stones''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171218182752/https://books.google.com/books?id=crc7ZtRHItgC&pg=PA1 |date=December 18, 2017 }}, Max Bauer, p. 2</ref> The word ''ruby'' comes from ''ruber'', [[Latin]] for red. The color of a ruby is due to the element [[chromium]].\n\nSome gemstones that are popularly or historically called rubies, such as the [[Black Prince's Ruby]] in the British [[Imperial State Crown]], are actually [[spinel]]s. These were once known as \"Balas rubies\".\n\nThe quality of a ruby is determined by its color, cut, and clarity, which, along with [[carat (mass)|carat]] weight, affect its value. The brightest and most valuable shade of red called blood-red or pigeon blood, commands a large premium over other rubies of similar quality. After color follows clarity: similar to diamonds, a clear stone will command a premium, but a ruby without any needle-like [[rutile]] [[Inclusion (mineral)|inclusions]] may indicate that the stone has been treated. Ruby is the traditional [[birthstone]] for July and is usually [[pink]]er than [[garnet]], although some [[rhodolite]] garnets have a similar pinkish hue to most rubies. The world's most valuable ruby is the [[Sunrise Ruby]].\n\n==Physical properties==\n[[Image:Corundum.png|thumb|left|Crystal structure of rubies]]\nRubies have a [[hardness]] of 9.0 on the [[Mohs scale of mineral hardness]]. Among the natural gems only [[moissanite]] and [[diamond]] are harder, with diamond having a Mohs hardness of 10.0 and moissanite falling somewhere in between corundum (ruby) and diamond in hardness. Sapphire, ruby, and pure corundum are \u03b1-alumina, the most stable form of Al<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3</sub>, in which 3 electrons leave each aluminium [[ion]] to join the regular octahedral group of six nearby O<sup>2\u2212</sup> ions; in pure corundum this leaves all of the aluminium ions with a very stable configuration of no unpaired electrons or unfilled energy levels, and the crystal is perfectly colorless.\n\n[[Image: Ruby model.jpg|thumb|left|Crystal structure of ruby showing the substitution of Al<sup>3+</sup> ions (blue) with Cr<sup>3+</sup> (red).  The substitution density of Cr<sup>3+</sup> ions in this model is approximately 2%, approximating the maximum doping normally encountered.<ref>[https://www.miramodus.com/images.shtml Images of molecular models from Miramodus]</ref>]]\n\nWhen a chromium atom replaces an occasional aluminium atom, it too loses 3 electrons to become a chromium<sup>3+</sup> ion to maintain the charge balance of the Al<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3</sub> crystal.  However, the Cr<sup>3+</sup> ions are larger and have [[Electron configuration#Ionization of the transition metals|electron orbitals]] in different directions than aluminium. The octahedral arrangement of the O<sup>2\u2212</sup> ions is distorted, and the energy levels of the different orbitals of those Cr<sup>3+</sup> ions are slightly altered because of the directions to the O<sup>2\u2212</sup> ions.<ref name=causes>{{cite web | url= http://www.webexhibits.org/causesofcolor/6AA.html | title= Ruby: causes of color | accessdate= 28 Mar 2016 | url-status= live | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160321193313/http://www.webexhibits.org/causesofcolor/6AA.html | archivedate= March 21, 2016 | df= mdy-all }}</ref> Those energy differences correspond to absorption in the ultraviolet, violet, and yellow-green regions of the spectrum.\n\n[[Image:Ruby transmittance.svg |thumb|Transmittance of ruby in optical and near-IR spectra. Note the two broad violet and yellow-green absorption bands and one narrow absorption band at the wavelength of 694 nm, which is the wavelength of the ruby laser.]]\n\nIf one percent of the aluminium ions are replaced by chromium in ruby, the yellow-green absorption results in a red color for the gem.<ref name=causes/>  Additionally, absorption at any of the above wavelengths stimulates [[fluorescence|fluorescent]] emission of 694-nanometer-wavelength red light, which adds to its red color and perceived [[Lustre (mineralogy)|luster]].\n\nAfter absorbing short-wavelength light, there is a short interval of time when the crystal lattice of ruby is in an excited state before fluorescence occurs. If 694-nanometer photons pass through the crystal during that time, they can stimulate more fluorescent photons to be emitted in-phase with them, thus strengthening the intensity of that red light. By arranging mirrors or other means to pass  emitted light repeatedly through the crystal, a [[ruby laser]] in this way produces a very high intensity of [[Coherence (physics)|coherent]] red light.\n\nAll natural rubies have imperfections in them, including color impurities and inclusions of [[rutile]] needles known as \"silk\". Gemologists use these needle inclusions found in natural rubies to distinguish them from synthetics, simulants, or substitutes. Usually, the rough stone is heated before cutting. These days, almost all rubies are treated in some form, with heat treatment being the most common practice. Untreated rubies of high quality command a large premium.\n\nSome rubies show a three-point or six-point [[asterism (gemmology)|asterism]] or \"star\". These rubies are cut into [[cabochons]] to display the effect properly. Asterisms are best visible with a single-light source and move across the stone as the light moves or the stone is rotated. Such effects occur when light is reflected off the \"silk\" (the structurally oriented [[rutile]] needle inclusions) in a certain way. This is one example where inclusions increase the value of a gemstone. Furthermore, rubies can show color changes\u2014though this occurs very rarely\u2014as well as [[chatoyancy]] or the \"cat's eye\" effect.\n\n===Ruby vs. pink sapphire===\nGenerally, gemstone-quality corundum in all shades of red, including pink, are called rubies.<ref name=\"matlins\">{{cite book|last=Matlins|first=Antoinette Leonard|title=Colored Gemstones|year=2010|publisher=Gemstone Press|isbn=0-943763-72-X|page=203|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4UANp6MCTSQC|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160502140108/https://books.google.com/books?id=4UANp6MCTSQC|archivedate=May 2, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Reed|first=Peter|title=Gemmology|year=1991|publisher=Butterworth-Heinemann|isbn=0-7506-6449-5|page=337|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t-OQO3Wk-JsC|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170102012607/https://books.google.com/books?id=t-OQO3Wk-JsC|archivedate=January 2, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>  However, in the United States, a minimum color saturation must be met to be called a ruby; otherwise, the stone will be called a [[sapphire|pink sapphire]].<ref name=\"matlins\" />  Drawing a distinction between rubies and pink sapphires is relatively new, having arisen sometime in the 20th century. Often, the distinction between ruby and pink sapphire is not clear and can be debated.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wise|first=Richard G|title=Gemstone Connoisseurship; The Finer Points, Part II|url=http://www.secretsofthegemtrade.com/articles_5_2.htm|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426082627/http://www.secretsofthegemtrade.com/articles_5_2.htm|archivedate=April 26, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>  As a result of the difficulty and subjectiveness of such distinctions, trade organizations such as the [[International Colored Gemstone Association]] (ICGA) have adopted the broader definition for ruby which encompasses its lighter shades, including pink.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hughes|first=Richard W.|title=Walking the line in ruby & sapphire|url=http://www.ruby-sapphire.com/ruby_sapphire_borders.htm|publisher=ruby-sapphire.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120113084826/http://www.ruby-sapphire.com/ruby_sapphire_borders.htm|archivedate=January 13, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Federman|first=David|title=Pink Sapphire|url=http://www.modernjeweler.com/web/online/Colored-Gemstone-Gem-Profiles/Pink-Sapphire/1$530|publisher=Modern Jeweler|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120131101220/http://www.modernjeweler.com/web/online/Colored-Gemstone-Gem-Profiles/Pink-Sapphire/1$530|archivedate=January 31, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Occurrence and mining==\nHistorically, rubies have also been mined in Thailand, in the [[Pailin]] and [[Samlout District]] of Cambodia, as well as in Afghanistan, Australia, Brazil, Colombia, India,  Namibia, Japan, and Scotland; after the [[Second World War]] ruby deposits were found in Madagascar, Nepal, Pakistan, Tajikistan, Tanzania, and Vietnam.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gemsociety.org/article/ruby-sapphire-identifying-origin-understanding-value-rarity-gem-corundum/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-12-23 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141230213525/http://www.gemsociety.org/article/ruby-sapphire-identifying-origin-understanding-value-rarity-gem-corundum/ |archivedate=December 30, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> \n\nThe Republic of North Macedonia is the only country in mainland Europe to have naturally occurring rubies. They can mainly be found around the city of [[Prilep]]. Macedonian rubies have a unique raspberry color. The ruby is also included on the Macedonian coat of arms.<ref>{{cite news|title=This is the New Coat of Arms of Republic of Macedonia |url=http://www.independent.mk/articles/12107/This+is+the+New+Coat+of+Arms+of+Republic+of+Macedonia|accessdate=30 March 2017|work=Independent.mk|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170330175849/http://www.independent.mk/articles/12107/This+is+the+New+Coat+of+Arms+of+Republic+of+Macedonia|archivedate=March 30, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> A few rubies have been found in the U.S. states of [[Montana]], [[North Carolina]], [[South Carolina]] and [[Wyoming]].\n\n[[Spinel]], another red gemstone, is sometimes found along with rubies in the same gem gravel or marble. Red spinels may be mistaken for rubies by those lacking experience with gems. However, the finest red spinels can have values approaching that of an average ruby.<ref>{{Cite book|author1=Wenk, Hans-Rudolf |author2=Bulakh, A. G. |title=Minerals: their constitution and origin|year=2004 |publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge, U.K. |isbn=0-521-52958-1 |pages=539\u2013541 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=0GAvKQJ2JuwC&pg=RA1-PA541}}</ref>\n\n===South Asia===\nThe [[Mogok]] Valley in Upper [[Myanmar]] (Burma) was for centuries the world's main source for rubies. That region has produced some exceptional rubies, however in recent years few good rubies have been found. In central Myanmar, the area of Mong Hsu began producing rubies during the 1990s and rapidly became the world's main ruby mining area. The most recently found ruby deposit in Myanmar is in Namya (Namyazeik) located in the northern state of [[Kachin State|Kachin]].\n\nRubies are also mined in [[Afghanistan]] and [[Pakistan]]. In [[Azad Kashmir|Pakistani Kashmir]] there are vast proven reserves of millions of rubies, worth up to half a billion dollars.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rubies, the buried treasures of Pakistani Kashmir |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20171015-rubies-buried-treasures-pakistani-kashmir|publisher=[[France24]]}}</ref> However, as of 2017 there was only one mine (at Chitta Katha) due to lack of investment.<ref>{{cite news|author=Caroline Nelly Perrot|title=Rubies, the buried treasures of Pakistani Kashmir |url=https://phys.org/news/2017-10-rubies-treasures-pakistani-kashmir.html}}</ref> In Afghanistan, rubies are mined at Jegdalek.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=The dangerous world of Pakistan\u2019s gem trade |url=https://www.macleans.ca/news/world/pakistans-blood-stones/|magazine=[[Maclean's]]}}</ref>\n\nIn Sri Lanka, lighter shades of rubies (often \"pink sapphires\") are more commonly found.\n\n==Factors affecting value==\nRubies, as with other gemstones, are graded using criteria known as the four Cs, namely color, cut, clarity and carat weight. Rubies are also evaluated on the basis of their geographic origin.\n\n'''Color:''' In the evaluation of colored gemstones, color is the most important factor. Color divides into three components: ''hue'', ''saturation'' and ''tone''. Hue refers to color as we normally use the term. Transparent gemstones occur in the ''pure spectral hues'' of red, orange, yellow, green, blue, violet.<ref name=wise>{{cite book|author=Wise, Richard W. |title=Secrets Of The Gem Trade, The Connoisseur's Guide To Precious Gemstones |pages=18\u201322 |isbn=0-9728223-8-0 |year=2006|publisher=Brunswick House Press}}</ref> In nature, there are rarely pure hues, so when speaking of the hue of a gemstone, we speak of primary and secondary and sometimes tertiary hues. Ruby is defined to be red. All other hues of the gem species corundum are called sapphire. Ruby may exhibit a range of secondary hues, including orange, purple, violet, and pink.\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"160\">\nImage:Ruby cristal.jpg|A naturally occurring ruby crystal\nImage:Ruby gem.JPG|Natural ruby with inclusions\nImage:Cut Ruby.jpg|A cut pink ruby\nImage:Rubis, calcite 14.jpg|Purple rubies\n</gallery>\n\n==Treatments and enhancements==\nImproving the quality of gemstones by treating them is common practice. Some treatments are used in almost all cases and are therefore considered acceptable. During the late 1990s, a large supply of low-cost materials caused a sudden surge in supply of heat-treated rubies, leading to a downward pressure on ruby prices.\n\nImprovements used include color alteration, improving transparency by dissolving rutile inclusions, healing of fractures (cracks) or even completely filling them.\n\nThe most common treatment is the application of heat. Most rubies at the lower end of the market are heat treated to improve color, remove ''purple tinge'', blue patches, and silk. These heat treatments typically occur around temperatures of 1800&nbsp;\u00b0C (3300&nbsp;\u00b0F).<ref name=\"ThemelisRubyHeat\">{{cite book|isbn=0940965100|title=The Heat Treatment of Ruby and Sapphire|publisher=Gemlab Inc.|place=Bangkok, Thailand|year=1992}}</ref> Some rubies undergo a process of low tube heat, when the stone is heated over charcoal of a temperature of about 1300&nbsp;\u00b0C (2400&nbsp;\u00b0F) for 20 to 30 minutes. The silk is partially broken, and the color is improved.\n\nAnother treatment, which has become more frequent in recent years, is <!-- to avoid false positives for 'is led/lead' typo-->[[lead glass]] filling. Filling the fractures inside the ruby with lead glass (or a similar material) dramatically improves the transparency of the stone, making previously unsuitable rubies fit for applications in jewelry.<ref>Vincent Pardieu [http://www.fieldgemology.org/Ruby_lead_glass_treatment.pdf Lead Glass Filled/Repaired Rubies] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110831062843/http://www.fieldgemology.org/Ruby_lead_glass_treatment.pdf |date=August 31, 2011 }}. Asian Institute of Gemological Sciences Gem Testing Laboratory. February 2005</ref> The process is done in four steps:\n\n# The rough stones are pre-polished to eradicate all surface impurities that may affect the process\n# The rough is cleaned with [[hydrogen fluoride]]\n# The first heating process during which no fillers are added. The heating process eradicates impurities inside the fractures. Although this can be done at temperatures up to 1400&nbsp;\u00b0C (2500&nbsp;\u00b0F) it most likely occurs at a temperature of around 900&nbsp;\u00b0C (1600&nbsp;\u00b0F) since the rutile silk is still intact.\n# The second heating process in an electrical oven with different chemical additives. Different solutions and mixes have shown to be successful, however mostly lead-containing glass-powder is used at present. The ruby is dipped into oils, then covered with powder, embedded on a tile and placed in the oven where it is heated at around 900&nbsp;\u00b0C (1600&nbsp;\u00b0F) for one hour in an oxidizing atmosphere. The orange colored powder transforms upon heating into a transparent to yellow-colored paste, which fills all fractures. After cooling the color of the paste is fully transparent and dramatically improves the overall transparency of the ruby.<ref>Richard W. Hughes (1997), ''Ruby & Sapphire'', Boulder, CO, RWH Publishing, {{ISBN|978-0-9645097-6-4}}</ref>\n\nIf a color needs to be added, the glass powder can be \"enhanced\" with copper or other metal oxides as well as elements such as sodium, calcium, potassium etc.\n\nThe second heating process can be repeated three to four times, even applying different mixtures.<ref>{{cite journal| last = Milisenda| first=C C| title=Rubine mit bleihaltigen Glasern gefullt| journal=Zeitschrift der Deutschen Gemmologischen Gesellschaft| volume=54 |issue=1| pages=35\u201341|publisher=Deutschen Gemmologischen Gesellschaft|year=2005|language=German}}</ref> When jewelry containing rubies is heated (for repairs) it should not be coated with boracic acid or any other substance, as this can etch the surface; it does not have to be \"protected\" like a diamond.\n\nThe treatment can identified by noting bubbles in cavities and fractures using a 10\u00d7 loupe.<ref>{{cite news |work= GIA Global Dispatch |publisher= Gemological Institute of America |date=16 February 2012 |url= http://www.gia.edu/research-resources/news-from-research/gia-global-dispatch/index.html |title= Lead Glass-Filled Rubies |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120614070635/http://www.gia.edu/research-resources/news-from-research/gia-global-dispatch/index.html |archive-date= June 14, 2012 |access-date=22 January 2020|df= mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Synthetic and imitation rubies==\n{{multiple image |direction=vertical\n|image1=Artificial ruby hemisphere under a normal light.jpg\n|image2=Artificial ruby hemisphere under a monochromatic light.jpg\n||caption2=Artificial ruby under a normal light (top) and under a green laser light (bottom). Red light is emitted}}\nIn 1837, Gaudin made the first synthetic rubies by fusing potash [[potassium alum|alum]] at a high temperature with a little chromium as a pigment. In 1847, [[Jacques-Joseph Ebelmen|Ebelmen]] made white sapphire by fusing [[alumina]] in boric acid. In 1877, Frenic and Freil made crystal [[corundum]] from which small stones could be cut. Frimy and [[Auguste Verneuil]] manufactured artificial ruby by fusing BaF<sub>2</sub> and Al<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3</sub> with a little chromium at [[Incandescence|red heat]]. In 1903, Verneuil announced he could produce synthetic rubies on a commercial scale using this [[flame fusion]] process.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.farlang.com/gemstones/bahadur_handbook_of_precious_stones/page_067|title = Bahadur: a Handbook of Precious Stones|year = 1943|accessdate = 2007-08-19|url-status = live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070927020704/http://www.farlang.com/gemstones/bahadur_handbook_of_precious_stones/page_067|archivedate = September 27, 2007|df = mdy-all}}</ref> By 1910, Verneuil's laboratory had expanded into a 30 furnace production facility, with annual gemstone production having reached {{convert|1000|kg|lb|-3}} in 1907.\n\n[[Edmond Fr\u00e9my]] would later improve the crystallisation of ruby from a solution to grow larger crystals: first alongside the industrial glass-maker Charles Feil, and latterly alongside his student [[Auguste Victor Louis Verneuil|Auguste Verneuil]]. By this point Verneuil was already developing the process of [[Verneuil process|flame fusion]] that would later bear his name. Verneuil published details of his new method in 1902, at which point the industrial production of synthetic ruby could begin. By 1910, Verneuil's laboratory had expanded into a 30 furnace production facility, with annual gemstone production having reached {{convert|1000|kg|lb|-3}} in 1907.\n\nOther processes in which synthetic rubies can be produced are through Czochralski's [[Czochralski process|pulling process]], flux process, and the [[hydrothermal synthesis|hydrothermal process]]. Most synthetic rubies originate from flame fusion, due to the low costs involved. Synthetic rubies may have no imperfections visible to the naked eye but magnification may reveal curved [[striae]] and gas bubbles. The fewer the number and the less obvious the imperfections, the more valuable the ruby is; unless there are no imperfections (i.e., a perfect ruby), in which case it will be suspected of being artificial. [[Dopant]]s are added to some manufactured rubies so they can be identified as synthetic, but most need [[gemology|gemological]] testing to determine their origin.\n\nSynthetic rubies have technological uses as well as gemological ones. Rods of synthetic ruby are used to make [[ruby laser]]s and [[maser]]s. The first working laser was made by [[Theodore Maiman|Theodore H. Maiman]] in 1960.<ref name=\"maiman\">{{cite journal |last=Maiman |first=T.H. |authorlink=Theodore Harold Maiman |year=1960 |title=Stimulated optical radiation in ruby |journal=Nature|volume=187 |issue=4736 |pages=493\u2013494 |doi=10.1038/187493a0 |bibcode=1960Natur.187..493M}}</ref> Maiman used a solid-state light-pumped synthetic ruby to produce red laser light at a wavelength of 694 nanometers (nm). Ruby lasers are still in use. Rubies are also used in applications where high hardness is required such as at wear-exposed locations in modern mechanical clockworks, or as scanning probe tips in a [[coordinate measuring machine]].\n\n[[Imitation]] rubies are also marketed. Red [[spinel]]s, red [[garnet]]s, and colored glass have been falsely claimed to be rubies. Imitations go back to Roman times and already in the 17th century techniques were developed to color foil red\u2014by burning scarlet wool in the bottom part of the furnace\u2014which was then placed under the imitation stone.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.farlang.com/gemstones/nicols-history-gemstones/page_036|title = Thomas Nicols: A Lapidary or History of Gemstones|year = 1652|accessdate = 2007-08-19|url-status = live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070819165714/http://www.farlang.com/gemstones/nicols-history-gemstones/page_036|archivedate = August 19, 2007|df = mdy-all}}</ref> Trade terms such as [[balas ruby]] for red spinel and [[rubellite]] for red [[tourmaline]] can mislead unsuspecting buyers. Such terms are therefore discouraged from use by many gemological associations such as the Laboratory Manual Harmonisation Committee (LMHC).\n\n==Records and famous rubies==\n[[Image:NMNH-Rubies-CroppedRotated.png|thumb|Rubies at the [[National Museum of Natural History]], [[Washington, D.C.]], USA]]\n* The Smithsonian's [[National Museum of Natural History]] in Washington, D.C. has some of the world's largest and finest ruby gemstones. The {{convert|23.1|carat|g|adj=on}} Burmese ruby, set in a platinum ring with diamonds, was donated by businessman and philanthropist [[Peter Buck (restaurateur)|Peter Buck]] in memory of his late wife Carmen L\u00facia. This gemstone displays a richly saturated red color combined with an exceptional transparency. The finely proportioned cut provides vivid red reflections. The stone was mined from the [[Mogok]] region of [[Burma]] (now [[Myanmar]]) in the 1930s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mnh.si.edu/exhibits/ruby/index.htm |title=The Carmen L\u00facia Ruby |accessdate=2008-02-28 |work=Exhibitions |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080309050010/http://www.mnh.si.edu/exhibits/ruby/index.htm |archivedate=March 9, 2008 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* In 2007 the London jeweler [[Garrard & Co]] featured on their website a heart-shaped 40.63-carat ruby.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.garrard.com/treasures/ |title=Garrards \u2013 Treasures (large and important jewelry pieces) |accessdate=2010-11-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120729020054/http://www.garrard.com/treasures/ |archivedate=July 29, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* On December 13/14, 2011 [[Elizabeth Taylor]]'s complete jewellery collection was auctioned by [[Christie's]]. Several ruby-set pieces were included in the sale, notably a ring set with an 8.24 ct gem that broke the 'price-per-carat' record for rubies ($512,925 per carat, i.e. over $4.2 million in total),<ref>[http://www.christies.com/about/press-center/releases/pressrelease.aspx?pressreleaseid=5294 The Legendary Jewels, Evening Sale & Jewelry (Sessions II and III) | Press Release | Christie's] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120129030559/http://www.christies.com/about/press-center/releases/pressrelease.aspx?pressreleaseid=5294 |date=January 29, 2012 }}. Christies.com (2011-12-14). Retrieved on 2012-07-11.</ref> and a necklace<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/photos/elizabeth-taylors-ruby-diamond-necklace-gift-mike-todd-photo-101745840.html Elizabeth Taylor's ruby and diamond necklace] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305041651/http://news.yahoo.com/photos/elizabeth-taylors-ruby-diamond-necklace-gift-mike-todd-photo-101745840.html |date=March 5, 2016 }}. News.yahoo.com (2011-09-07). Retrieved on 2012-07-11.</ref> that sold for over $3.7 million.\n* The [[Liberty Bell Ruby]] is the largest mined ruby in the world. It was stolen in a heist in 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://philadelphia.cbslocal.com/2012/01/09/irreplaceable-2-million-ruby-stolen-in-wilmington-jewelry-heist/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-03-17 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161229181248/http://philadelphia.cbslocal.com/2012/01/09/irreplaceable-2-million-ruby-stolen-in-wilmington-jewelry-heist/ |archivedate=December 29, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* The [[Sunrise Ruby]] is the world's most expensive ruby, most expensive coloured gemstone, and most expensive gemstone other than a diamond. In May 2015, it sold at auction in Switzerland to an anonymous buyer for US$30 million.<ref name=BBC>{{cite news|title=World's most expensive coloured gem sells for $30m|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-32717029|accessdate=13 May 2015|work=BBC|date=13 May 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150513063509/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-32717029|archivedate=May 13, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* A synthetic ruby crystal became the gain medium in the world's first optical laser, conceived, designed and constructed by [[Theodore Maiman|Theodore H. \"Ted\" Maiman]], on 16 May 1961 at [[Hughes Research Laboratories]].<ref name=\"maiman\" /><ref>\n {{cite web\n |title       = Laser inventor Maiman dies; tribute to be held on anniversary of first laser\n |publisher   = Laser Focus World\n |date        = 2007-05-09\n |url         = http://www.laserfocusworld.com/display_article/292149/12/none/none/INDUS/Laser-inventor-Maiman-dies;-tribute-to-be-held-on-anniversary-of-first-lase,\n |accessdate  = 2007-05-14\n |url-status     = live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070927174042/http://www.laserfocusworld.com/display_article/292149/12/none/none/INDUS/Laser-inventor-Maiman-dies;-tribute-to-be-held-on-anniversary-of-first-lase,\n |archivedate = September 27, 2007\n |df          = mdy-all\n}}</ref> The concept of electromagnetic radiation amplification through the mechanism of [[stimulated emission]] had already been successfully demonstrated in the laboratory by way of the [[maser]], using other materials such as ammonia and, later, ruby, but the [[ruby laser]] was the first device to work at optical (694.3&nbsp;nm) wavelengths. Maiman's prototype laser is still in working order.\n\n==Historical and cultural references==\n[[File:Ruby Eye Pendant.jpg|thumb|right|The Ruby Eye Amulet from Mesopotamia, Adilnor Collection, Sweden.]]\n* An early recorded  transport and trading of rubies arises in the literature on the [[North Silk Road]] of China, wherein about 200 [[Before Christ|BC]] rubies were carried along this ancient [[trackway]] moving westward from China.<ref>C. Michael Hogan, [http://www.megalithic.co.uk/article.php?sid=18006 Silk Road, North China] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002140921/http://www.megalithic.co.uk/article.php?sid=18006 |date=October 2, 2013 }}, The Megalithic Portal. 19 November 2007</ref>\n* Rubies have always been held in high esteem in Asian countries. They were used to ornament armor, scabbards, and harnesses of noblemen in India and China. Rubies were laid beneath the foundation of buildings to secure good fortune to the structure.\n*Some other sources explain that the Indian culture worships rubies to be the \"gemstone of the sun\", leader of the nine planets. <ref name=\"smith\">{{cite book|last = Smith|first = Henry G.|title = Gems and Precious Stones|publisher = Charles Potter Government Printer, Australia|year = 1896|url = http://www.farlang.com/gemstones/smith-gems-prec-stones/page_028|chapter = Chapter 2, Sapphires, Rubies|url-status = live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070929090904/http://www.farlang.com/gemstones/smith-gems-prec-stones/page_028|archivedate = September 29, 2007|df = mdy-all}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikipedia books|Gemstones}}\n{{Portal|Minerals}}\n*[[Anyolite]]\n*[[List of individual gemstones]]\n*[[List of minerals]]\n*[[Shelby Gem Factory]]\n*[[Verneuil process]]\n*[[Emerald]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.gemstone.org/gem-by-gem/english/ruby.html International Colored Stone Association's ruby overview page]\n* [http://webmineral.com/data/Corundum.shtml  Webmineral crystallographic and mineral info]\n\n{{Jewellery}}\n{{Gemstone}}\n{{Use American English|date=August 2015}}  \n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2015}}\n\n[[Category:Aluminium minerals]]\n[[Category:Oxide minerals]]\n[[Category:Superhard materials]]\n[[Category:Trigonal minerals]]\n[[Category:Luminescent minerals]]\n[[Category:Corundum gemstones]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Variety of corundum, mineral, gemstone}}\n{{about|the mineral or gem}}\n{{Infobox mineral\n| name        = Ruby\n| image       = File:Corundum-winza-17d.jpg\n| imagesize   = 260px\n| alt         =\n| caption     = Natural ruby crystals from [[Winza]], [[Tanzania]]\n| category    = [[Oxide mineral]] variety\n| formula     = [[aluminium oxide]] with [[chromium]], Al<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3</sub>:Cr\n| molweight   =\n| strunz      =\n| dana        =\n| system      = [[Trigonal]] \n| class       = Hexagonal scalenohedral ({{overline|3}}m) <br/>[[H-M symbol]]: ({{overline|3}} 2/m)\n| symmetry    = ''R''{{overline|3}}c<ref>[http://webmineral.com/data/Corundum.shtml Corundum data on Webmineral] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20071001144657/http://webmineral.com/data/Corundum.shtml |date=October 1, 2007 }}</ref>\n| unit cell   =\n| color       = Near colorless through pink through all shades of red to a deep crimson\n| colour      =\n| habit       = Terminated tabular hexagonal prisms\n| twinning    =\n| cleavage    = No true cleavage\n| fracture    = Conchoidal, splintery\n| tenacity    = Brittle\n| mohs        = 9.0\n| luster      = Subadamantine, vitreous, pearly (on partings)\n| streak      = White\n| diaphaneity = Transparent, translucent\n| gravity     = 3.97\u20134.05\n| density     =\n| polish      =\n| opticalprop = Uniaxial/\u2212\n| refractive  = n<sub>\u03c9</sub>=1.768\u20131.772 <br/>n<sub>\u03b5</sub>=1.760\u20131.763\n| birefringence =0.008\n| pleochroism = Strong: purplish-red \u2013 orangy-red\n| 2V          =\n| dispersion  = 0.018\n| extinction  =\n| length fast/slow =\n| fluorescence = Red under longwave\n| absorption  =\n| melt        = \n| fusibility  =\n| diagnostic  =\n| solubility  = \n| impurities  =\n| alteration  =\n| other       =\n| prop1       =\n| prop1text   =\n| references  =<ref>[http://www.gemdat.org/gem-3473.html Ruby on Gemdat.org] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150317144325/http://www.gemdat.org/gem-3473.html |date=March 17, 2015 }}</ref>\n}}\n\nA '''ruby''' is a pink to blood-red colored [[gemstone]], a variety of the [[mineral]] [[corundum]] ([[aluminium oxide]]). Other varieties of gem-quality corundum are called [[sapphire]]s. Ruby is one of the traditional [[cardinal gem]]s, together with [[amethyst]], [[sapphire]], [[emerald]], and [[diamond]].<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=crc7ZtRHItgC&pg=PA1 ''Precious Stones''] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171218182752/https://books.google.com/books?id=crc7ZtRHItgC&pg=PA1 |date=December 18, 2017 }}, Max Bauer, p. 2</ref> The word ''ruby'' comes from ''ruber'', [[Latin]] for red. The color of a ruby is due to the element [[chromium]].\n\nSome gemstones that are popularly or historically called rubies, such as the [[Black Prince's Ruby]] in the British [[Imperial State Crown]], are actually [[spinel]]s. These were once known as \"Balas rubies\".\n\nThe quality of a ruby is determined by its color, cut, and clarity, which, along with [[carat (mass)|carat]] weight, affect its value. The brightest and most valuable shade of red called blood-red or pigeon blood, commands a large premium over other rubies of similar quality. After color follows clarity: similar to diamonds, a clear stone will command a premium, but a ruby without any needle-like [[rutile]] [[Inclusion (mineral)|inclusions]] may indicate that the stone has been treated. Ruby is the traditional [[birthstone]] for July and is usually [[pink]]er than [[garnet]], although some [[rhodolite]] garnets have a similar pinkish hue to most rubies. The world's most valuable ruby is the [[Sunrise Ruby]].\n\n==Physical properties==\n[[Image:Corundum.png|thumb|left|Crystal structure of rubies]]\nRubies have a [[hardness]] of 9.0 on the [[Mohs scale of mineral hardness]]. Among the natural gems only [[moissanite]] and [[diamond]] are harder, with diamond having a Mohs hardness of 10.0 and moissanite falling somewhere in between corundum (ruby) and diamond in hardness. Sapphire, ruby, and pure corundum are \u03b1-alumina, the most stable form of Al<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3</sub>, in which 3 electrons leave each aluminium [[ion]] to join the regular octahedral group of six nearby O<sup>2\u2212</sup> ions; in pure corundum this leaves all of the aluminium ions with a very stable configuration of no unpaired electrons or unfilled energy levels, and the crystal is perfectly colorless.\n\n[[Image: Ruby model.jpg|thumb|left|Crystal structure of ruby showing the substitution of Al<sup>3+</sup> ions (blue) with Cr<sup>3+</sup> (red).  The substitution density of Cr<sup>3+</sup> ions in this model is approximately 2%, approximating the maximum doping normally encountered.<ref>[https://www.miramodus.com/images.shtml Images of molecular models from Miramodus]</ref>]]\n\nWhen a chromium atom replaces an occasional aluminium atom, it too loses 3 electrons to become a chromium<sup>3+</sup> ion to maintain the charge balance of the Al<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3</sub> crystal.  However, the Cr<sup>3+</sup> ions are larger and have [[Electron configuration#Ionization of the transition metals|electron orbitals]] in different directions than aluminium. The octahedral arrangement of the O<sup>2\u2212</sup> ions is distorted, and the energy levels of the different orbitals of those Cr<sup>3+</sup> ions are slightly altered because of the directions to the O<sup>2\u2212</sup> ions.<ref name=causes>{{cite web | url= http://www.webexhibits.org/causesofcolor/6AA.html | title= Ruby: causes of color | accessdate= 28 Mar 2016 | url-status= live | archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20160321193313/http://www.webexhibits.org/causesofcolor/6AA.html | archivedate= March 21, 2016 | df= mdy-all }}</ref> Those energy differences correspond to absorption in the ultraviolet, violet, and yellow-green regions of the spectrum.\n\n[[Image:Ruby transmittance.svg |thumb|Transmittance of ruby in optical and near-IR spectra. Note the two broad violet and yellow-green absorption bands and one narrow absorption band at the wavelength of 694 nm, which is the wavelength of the ruby laser.]]\n\nIf one percent of the aluminium ions are replaced by chromium in ruby, the yellow-green absorption results in a red color for the gem.<ref name=causes/>  Additionally, absorption at any of the above wavelengths stimulates [[fluorescence|fluorescent]] emission of 694-nanometer-wavelength red light, which adds to its red color and perceived [[Lustre (mineralogy)|luster]].\n\nAfter absorbing short-wavelength light, there is a short interval of time when the crystal lattice of ruby is in an excited state before fluorescence occurs. If 694-nanometer photons pass through the crystal during that time, they can stimulate more fluorescent photons to be emitted in-phase with them, thus strengthening the intensity of that red light. By arranging mirrors or other means to pass  emitted light repeatedly through the crystal, a [[ruby laser]] in this way produces a very high intensity of [[Coherence (physics)|coherent]] red light.\n\nAll natural rubies have imperfections in them, including color impurities and inclusions of [[rutile]] needles known as \"silk\". Gemologists use these needle inclusions found in natural rubies to distinguish them from synthetics, simulants, or substitutes. Usually, the rough stone is heated before cutting. These days, almost all rubies are treated in some form, with heat treatment being the most common practice. Untreated rubies of high quality command a large premium.\n\nSome rubies show a three-point or six-point [[asterism (gemmology)|asterism]] or \"star\". These rubies are cut into [[cabochons]] to display the effect properly. Asterisms are best visible with a single-light source and move across the stone as the light moves or the stone is rotated. Such effects occur when light is reflected off the \"silk\" (the structurally oriented [[rutile]] needle inclusions) in a certain way. This is one example where inclusions increase the value of a gemstone. Furthermore, rubies can show color changes\u2014though this occurs very rarely\u2014as well as [[chatoyancy]] or the \"cat's eye\" effect.\n\n===Ruby vs. pink sapphire===\nGenerally, gemstone-quality corundum in all shades of red, including pink, are called rubies.<ref name=\"matlins\">{{cite book|last=Matlins|first=Antoinette Leonard|title=Colored Gemstones|year=2010|publisher=Gemstone Press|isbn=0-943763-72-X|page=203|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=4UANp6MCTSQC|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160502140108/https://books.google.com/books?id=4UANp6MCTSQC|archivedate=May 2, 2016|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite book|last=Reed|first=Peter|title=Gemmology|year=1991|publisher=Butterworth-Heinemann|isbn=0-7506-6449-5|page=337|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=t-OQO3Wk-JsC|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170102012607/https://books.google.com/books?id=t-OQO3Wk-JsC|archivedate=January 2, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref>  However, in the United States, a minimum color saturation must be met to be called a ruby; otherwise, the stone will be called a [[sapphire|pink sapphire]].<ref name=\"matlins\" />  Drawing a distinction between rubies and pink sapphires is relatively new, having arisen sometime in the 20th century. Often, the distinction between ruby and pink sapphire is not clear and can be debated.<ref>{{cite web|last=Wise|first=Richard G|title=Gemstone Connoisseurship; The Finer Points, Part II|url=http://www.secretsofthegemtrade.com/articles_5_2.htm|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120426082627/http://www.secretsofthegemtrade.com/articles_5_2.htm|archivedate=April 26, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>  As a result of the difficulty and subjectiveness of such distinctions, trade organizations such as the [[International Colored Gemstone Association]] (ICGA) have adopted the broader definition for ruby which encompasses its lighter shades, including pink.<ref>{{cite web|last=Hughes|first=Richard W.|title=Walking the line in ruby & sapphire|url=http://www.ruby-sapphire.com/ruby_sapphire_borders.htm|publisher=ruby-sapphire.com|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120113084826/http://www.ruby-sapphire.com/ruby_sapphire_borders.htm|archivedate=January 13, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Federman|first=David|title=Pink Sapphire|url=http://www.modernjeweler.com/web/online/Colored-Gemstone-Gem-Profiles/Pink-Sapphire/1$530|publisher=Modern Jeweler|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120131101220/http://www.modernjeweler.com/web/online/Colored-Gemstone-Gem-Profiles/Pink-Sapphire/1$530|archivedate=January 31, 2012|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n\n==Occurrence and mining==\nHistorically, rubies have also been mined in Thailand, in the [[Pailin]] and [[Samlout District]] of Cambodia, as well as in Afghanistan, Australia, Brazil, Colombia, India,  Namibia, Japan, and Scotland; after the [[Second World War]] ruby deposits were found in Madagascar, Nepal, Pakistan, Tajikistan, Tanzania, and Vietnam.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.gemsociety.org/article/ruby-sapphire-identifying-origin-understanding-value-rarity-gem-corundum/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2014-12-23 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141230213525/http://www.gemsociety.org/article/ruby-sapphire-identifying-origin-understanding-value-rarity-gem-corundum/ |archivedate=December 30, 2014 |df=mdy-all }}</ref> \n\nThe Republic of North Macedonia is the only country in mainland Europe to have naturally occurring rubies. They can mainly be found around the city of [[Prilep]]. Macedonian rubies have a unique raspberry color. The ruby is also included on the Macedonian coat of arms.<ref>{{cite news|title=This is the New Coat of Arms of Republic of Macedonia |url=http://www.independent.mk/articles/12107/This+is+the+New+Coat+of+Arms+of+Republic+of+Macedonia|accessdate=30 March 2017|work=Independent.mk|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170330175849/http://www.independent.mk/articles/12107/This+is+the+New+Coat+of+Arms+of+Republic+of+Macedonia|archivedate=March 30, 2017|df=mdy-all}}</ref> A few rubies have been found in the U.S. states of [[Montana]], [[North Carolina]], [[South Carolina]] and [[Wyoming]].\n\n[[Spinel]], another red gemstone, is sometimes found along with rubies in the same gem gravel or marble. Red spinels may be mistaken for rubies by those lacking experience with gems. However, the finest red spinels can have values approaching that of an average ruby.<ref>{{Cite book|author1=Wenk, Hans-Rudolf |author2=Bulakh, A. G. |title=Minerals: their constitution and origin|year=2004 |publisher=Cambridge University Press|location=Cambridge, U.K. |isbn=0-521-52958-1 |pages=539\u2013541 |url=https://books.google.com/?id=0GAvKQJ2JuwC&pg=RA1-PA541}}</ref>\n\n===South Asia===\nThe [[Mogok]] Valley in Upper [[Myanmar]] (Burma) was for centuries the world's main source for rubies. That region has produced some exceptional rubies, however in recent years few good rubies have been found. In central Myanmar, the area of Mong Hsu began producing rubies during the 1990s and rapidly became the world's main ruby mining area. The most recently found ruby deposit in Myanmar is in Namya (Namyazeik) located in the northern state of [[Kachin State|Kachin]].\n\nRubies are also mined in [[Afghanistan]] and [[Pakistan]]. In [[Azad Kashmir|Pakistani Kashmir]] there are vast proven reserves of millions of rubies, worth up to half a billion dollars.<ref>{{cite news|title=Rubies, the buried treasures of Pakistani Kashmir |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20171015-rubies-buried-treasures-pakistani-kashmir|publisher=[[France24]]}}</ref> However, as of 2017 there was only one mine (at Chitta Katha) due to lack of investment.<ref>{{cite news|author=Caroline Nelly Perrot|title=Rubies, the buried treasures of Pakistani Kashmir |url=https://phys.org/news/2017-10-rubies-treasures-pakistani-kashmir.html}}</ref> In Afghanistan, rubies are mined at Jegdalek.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=The dangerous world of Pakistan\u2019s gem trade |url=https://www.macleans.ca/news/world/pakistans-blood-stones/|magazine=[[Maclean's]]}}</ref>\n\nIn Sri Lanka, lighter shades of rubies (often \"pink sapphires\") are more commonly found.\n\n==Factors affecting value==\nRubies, as with other gemstones, are graded using criteria known as the four Cs, namely color, cut, clarity and carat weight. Rubies are also evaluated on the basis of their geographic origin.\n\n'''Color:''' In the evaluation of colored gemstones, color is the most important factor. Color divides into three components: ''hue'', ''saturation'' and ''tone''. Hue refers to color as we normally use the term. Transparent gemstones occur in the ''pure spectral hues'' of red, orange, yellow, green, blue, violet.<ref name=wise>{{cite book|author=Wise, Richard W. |title=Secrets Of The Gem Trade, The Connoisseur's Guide To Precious Gemstones |pages=18\u201322 |isbn=0-9728223-8-0 |year=2006|publisher=Brunswick House Press}}</ref> In nature, there are rarely pure hues, so when speaking of the hue of a gemstone, we speak of primary and secondary and sometimes tertiary hues. Ruby is defined to be red. All other hues of the gem species corundum are called sapphire. Ruby may exhibit a range of secondary hues, including orange, purple, violet, and pink.\n\n<gallery mode=\"packed\" heights=\"160\">\nImage:Ruby cristal.jpg|A naturally occurring ruby crystal\nImage:Ruby gem.JPG|Natural ruby with inclusions\nImage:Cut Ruby.jpg|A cut pink ruby\nImage:Rubis, calcite 14.jpg|Purple rubies\n</gallery>\n\n==Treatments and enhancements==\nImproving the quality of gemstones by treating them is common practice. Some treatments are used in almost all cases and are therefore considered acceptable. During the late 1990s, a large supply of low-cost materials caused a sudden surge in supply of heat-treated rubies, leading to a downward pressure on ruby prices.\n\nImprovements used include color alteration, improving transparency by dissolving rutile inclusions, healing of fractures (cracks) or even completely filling them.\n\nThe most common treatment is the application of heat. Most rubies at the lower end of the market are heat treated to improve color, remove ''purple tinge'', blue patches, and silk. These heat treatments typically occur around temperatures of 1800&nbsp;\u00b0C (3300&nbsp;\u00b0F).<ref name=\"ThemelisRubyHeat\">{{cite book|isbn=0940965100|title=The Heat Treatment of Ruby and Sapphire|publisher=Gemlab Inc.|place=Bangkok, Thailand|year=1992}}</ref> Some rubies undergo a process of low tube heat, when the stone is heated over charcoal of a temperature of about 1300&nbsp;\u00b0C (2400&nbsp;\u00b0F) for 20 to 30 minutes. The silk is partially broken, and the color is improved.\n\nAnother treatment, which has become more frequent in recent years, is <!-- to avoid false positives for 'is led/lead' typo-->[[lead glass]] filling. Filling the fractures inside the ruby with lead glass (or a similar material) dramatically improves the transparency of the stone, making previously unsuitable rubies fit for applications in jewelry.<ref>Vincent Pardieu [http://www.fieldgemology.org/Ruby_lead_glass_treatment.pdf Lead Glass Filled/Repaired Rubies] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110831062843/http://www.fieldgemology.org/Ruby_lead_glass_treatment.pdf |date=August 31, 2011 }}. Asian Institute of Gemological Sciences Gem Testing Laboratory. February 2005</ref> The process is done in four steps:\n\n# The rough stones are pre-polished to eradicate all surface impurities that may affect the process\n# The rough is cleaned with [[hydrogen fluoride]]\n# The first heating process during which no fillers are added. The heating process eradicates impurities inside the fractures. Although this can be done at temperatures up to 1400&nbsp;\u00b0C (2500&nbsp;\u00b0F) it most likely occurs at a temperature of around 900&nbsp;\u00b0C (1600&nbsp;\u00b0F) since the rutile silk is still intact.\n# The second heating process in an electrical oven with different chemical additives. Different solutions and mixes have shown to be successful, however mostly lead-containing glass-powder is used at present. The ruby is dipped into oils, then covered with powder, embedded on a tile and placed in the oven where it is heated at around 900&nbsp;\u00b0C (1600&nbsp;\u00b0F) for one hour in an oxidizing atmosphere. The orange colored powder transforms upon heating into a transparent to yellow-colored paste, which fills all fractures. After cooling the color of the paste is fully transparent and dramatically improves the overall transparency of the ruby.<ref>Richard W. Hughes (1997), ''Ruby & Sapphire'', Boulder, CO, RWH Publishing, {{ISBN|978-0-9645097-6-4}}</ref>\n\nIf a color needs to be added, the glass powder can be \"enhanced\" with copper or other metal oxides as well as elements such as sodium, calcium, potassium etc.\n\nThe second heating process can be repeated three to four times, even applying different mixtures.<ref>{{cite journal| last = Milisenda| first=C C| title=Rubine mit bleihaltigen Glasern gefullt| journal=Zeitschrift der Deutschen Gemmologischen Gesellschaft| volume=54 |issue=1| pages=35\u201341|publisher=Deutschen Gemmologischen Gesellschaft|year=2005|language=German}}</ref> When jewelry containing rubies is heated (for repairs) it should not be coated with boracic acid or any other substance, as this can etch the surface; it does not have to be \"protected\" like a diamond.\n\nThe treatment can identified by noting bubbles in cavities and fractures using a 10\u00d7 loupe.<ref>{{cite news |work= GIA Global Dispatch |publisher= Gemological Institute of America |date=16 February 2012 |url= http://www.gia.edu/research-resources/news-from-research/gia-global-dispatch/index.html |title= Lead Glass-Filled Rubies |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120614070635/http://www.gia.edu/research-resources/news-from-research/gia-global-dispatch/index.html |archive-date= June 14, 2012 |access-date=22 January 2020|df= mdy-all }}</ref>\n\n==Synthetic and imitation rubies==\n{{multiple image |direction=vertical\n|image1=Artificial ruby hemisphere under a normal light.jpg\n|image2=Artificial ruby hemisphere under a monochromatic light.jpg\n||caption2=Artificial ruby under a normal light (top) and under a green laser light (bottom). Red light is emitted}}\nIn 1837, Gaudin made the first synthetic rubies by fusing potash [[potassium alum|alum]] at a high temperature with a little chromium as a pigment. In 1847, [[Jacques-Joseph Ebelmen|Ebelmen]] made white sapphire by fusing [[alumina]] in boric acid. In 1877, Frenic and Freil made crystal [[corundum]] from which small stones could be cut. Frimy and [[Auguste Verneuil]] manufactured artificial ruby by fusing BaF<sub>2</sub> and Al<sub>2</sub>O<sub>3</sub> with a little chromium at [[Incandescence|red heat]]. In 1903, Verneuil announced he could produce synthetic rubies on a commercial scale using this [[flame fusion]] process.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.farlang.com/gemstones/bahadur_handbook_of_precious_stones/page_067|title = Bahadur: a Handbook of Precious Stones|year = 1943|accessdate = 2007-08-19|url-status = live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070927020704/http://www.farlang.com/gemstones/bahadur_handbook_of_precious_stones/page_067|archivedate = September 27, 2007|df = mdy-all}}</ref> By 1910, Verneuil's laboratory had expanded into a 30 furnace production facility, with annual gemstone production having reached {{convert|1000|kg|lb|-3}} in 1907.\n\n[[Edmond Fr\u00e9my]] would later improve the crystallisation of ruby from a solution to grow larger crystals: first alongside the industrial glass-maker Charles Feil, and latterly alongside his student [[Auguste Victor Louis Verneuil|Auguste Verneuil]]. By this point Verneuil was already developing the process of [[Verneuil process|flame fusion]] that would later bear his name. Verneuil published details of his new method in 1902, at which point the industrial production of synthetic ruby could begin. By 1910, Verneuil's laboratory had expanded into a 30 furnace production facility, with annual gemstone production having reached {{convert|1000|kg|lb|-3}} in 1907.\n\nOther processes in which synthetic rubies can be produced are through Czochralski's [[Czochralski process|pulling process]], flux process, and the [[hydrothermal synthesis|hydrothermal process]]. Most synthetic rubies originate from flame fusion, due to the low costs involved. Synthetic rubies may have no imperfections visible to the naked eye but magnification may reveal curved [[striae]] and gas bubbles. The fewer the number and the less obvious the imperfections, the more valuable the ruby is; unless there are no imperfections (i.e., a perfect ruby), in which case it will be suspected of being artificial. [[Dopant]]s are added to some manufactured rubies so they can be identified as synthetic, but most need [[gemology|gemological]] testing to determine their origin.\n\nSynthetic rubies have technological uses as well as gemological ones. Rods of synthetic ruby are used to make [[ruby laser]]s and [[maser]]s. The first working laser was made by [[Theodore Maiman|Theodore H. Maiman]] in 1960.<ref name=\"maiman\">{{cite journal |last=Maiman |first=T.H. |authorlink=Theodore Harold Maiman |year=1960 |title=Stimulated optical radiation in ruby |journal=Nature|volume=187 |issue=4736 |pages=493\u2013494 |doi=10.1038/187493a0 |bibcode=1960Natur.187..493M}}</ref> Maiman used a solid-state light-pumped synthetic ruby to produce red laser light at a wavelength of 694 nanometers (nm). Ruby lasers are still in use. Rubies are also used in applications where high hardness is required such as at wear-exposed locations in modern mechanical clockworks, or as scanning probe tips in a [[coordinate measuring machine]].\n\n[[Imitation]] rubies are also marketed. Red [[spinel]]s, red [[garnet]]s, and colored glass have been falsely claimed to be rubies. Imitations go back to Roman times and already in the 17th century techniques were developed to color foil red\u2014by burning scarlet wool in the bottom part of the furnace\u2014which was then placed under the imitation stone.<ref>{{cite web|url = http://www.farlang.com/gemstones/nicols-history-gemstones/page_036|title = Thomas Nicols: A Lapidary or History of Gemstones|year = 1652|accessdate = 2007-08-19|url-status = live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070819165714/http://www.farlang.com/gemstones/nicols-history-gemstones/page_036|archivedate = August 19, 2007|df = mdy-all}}</ref> Trade terms such as [[balas ruby]] for red spinel and [[rubellite]] for red [[tourmaline]] can mislead unsuspecting buyers. Such terms are therefore discouraged from use by many gemological associations such as the Laboratory Manual Harmonisation Committee (LMHC).\n\n==Records and famous rubies==\n[[Image:NMNH-Rubies-CroppedRotated.png|thumb|Rubies at the [[National Museum of Natural History]], [[Washington, D.C.]], USA]]\n* The Smithsonian's [[National Museum of Natural History]] in Washington, D.C. has some of the world's largest and finest ruby gemstones. The {{convert|23.1|carat|g|adj=on}} Burmese ruby, set in a platinum ring with diamonds, was donated by businessman and philanthropist [[Peter Buck (restaurateur)|Peter Buck]] in memory of his late wife Carmen L\u00facia. This gemstone displays a richly saturated red color combined with an exceptional transparency. The finely proportioned cut provides vivid red reflections. The stone was mined from the [[Mogok]] region of [[Burma]] (now [[Myanmar]]) in the 1930s.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.mnh.si.edu/exhibits/ruby/index.htm |title=The Carmen L\u00facia Ruby |accessdate=2008-02-28 |work=Exhibitions |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080309050010/http://www.mnh.si.edu/exhibits/ruby/index.htm |archivedate=March 9, 2008 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* In 2007 the London jeweler [[Garrard & Co]] featured on their website a heart-shaped 40.63-carat ruby.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.garrard.com/treasures/ |title=Garrards \u2013 Treasures (large and important jewelry pieces) |accessdate=2010-11-08 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120729020054/http://www.garrard.com/treasures/ |archivedate=July 29, 2012 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* On December 13/14, 2011 [[Elizabeth Taylor]]'s complete jewellery collection was auctioned by [[Christie's]]. Several ruby-set pieces were included in the sale, notably a ring set with an 8.24 ct gem that broke the 'price-per-carat' record for rubies ($512,925 per carat, i.e. over $4.2 million in total),<ref>[http://www.christies.com/about/press-center/releases/pressrelease.aspx?pressreleaseid=5294 The Legendary Jewels, Evening Sale & Jewelry (Sessions II and III) | Press Release | Christie's] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120129030559/http://www.christies.com/about/press-center/releases/pressrelease.aspx?pressreleaseid=5294 |date=January 29, 2012 }}. Christies.com (2011-12-14). Retrieved on 2012-07-11.</ref> and a necklace<ref>[https://news.yahoo.com/photos/elizabeth-taylors-ruby-diamond-necklace-gift-mike-todd-photo-101745840.html Elizabeth Taylor's ruby and diamond necklace] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305041651/http://news.yahoo.com/photos/elizabeth-taylors-ruby-diamond-necklace-gift-mike-todd-photo-101745840.html |date=March 5, 2016 }}. News.yahoo.com (2011-09-07). Retrieved on 2012-07-11.</ref> that sold for over $3.7 million.\n* The [[Liberty Bell Ruby]] is the largest mined ruby in the world. It was stolen in a heist in 2011.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://philadelphia.cbslocal.com/2012/01/09/irreplaceable-2-million-ruby-stolen-in-wilmington-jewelry-heist/ |title=Archived copy |accessdate=2017-03-17 |url-status=live |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20161229181248/http://philadelphia.cbslocal.com/2012/01/09/irreplaceable-2-million-ruby-stolen-in-wilmington-jewelry-heist/ |archivedate=December 29, 2016 |df=mdy-all }}</ref>\n* The [[Sunrise Ruby]] is the world's most expensive ruby, most expensive coloured gemstone, and most expensive gemstone other than a diamond. In May 2015, it sold at auction in Switzerland to an anonymous buyer for US$30 million.<ref name=BBC>{{cite news|title=World's most expensive coloured gem sells for $30m|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-32717029|accessdate=13 May 2015|work=BBC|date=13 May 2015|url-status=live|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20150513063509/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-europe-32717029|archivedate=May 13, 2015|df=mdy-all}}</ref>\n* A synthetic ruby crystal became the gain medium in the world's first optical laser, conceived, designed and constructed by [[Theodore Maiman|Theodore H. \"Ted\" Maiman]], on 16 May 1961 at [[Hughes Research Laboratories]].<ref name=\"maiman\" /><ref>\n {{cite web\n |title       = Laser inventor Maiman dies; tribute to be held on anniversary of first laser\n |publisher   = Laser Focus World\n |date        = 2007-05-09\n |url         = http://www.laserfocusworld.com/display_article/292149/12/none/none/INDUS/Laser-inventor-Maiman-dies;-tribute-to-be-held-on-anniversary-of-first-lase,\n |accessdate  = 2007-05-14\n |url-status     = live\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20070927174042/http://www.laserfocusworld.com/display_article/292149/12/none/none/INDUS/Laser-inventor-Maiman-dies;-tribute-to-be-held-on-anniversary-of-first-lase,\n |archivedate = September 27, 2007\n |df          = mdy-all\n}}</ref> The concept of electromagnetic radiation amplification through the mechanism of [[stimulated emission]] had already been successfully demonstrated in the laboratory by way of the [[maser]], using other materials such as ammonia and, later, ruby, but the [[ruby laser]] was the first device to work at optical (694.3&nbsp;nm) wavelengths. Maiman's prototype laser is still in working order.\n\n==Historical and cultural references==\n[[File:Ruby Eye Pendant.jpg|thumb|right|The Ruby Eye Amulet from Mesopotamia, Adilnor Collection, Sweden.]]\n* An early recorded  transport and trading of rubies arises in the literature on the [[North Silk Road]] of China, wherein about 200 [[Before Christ|BC]] rubies were carried along this ancient [[trackway]] moving westward from China.<ref>C. Michael Hogan, [http://www.megalithic.co.uk/article.php?sid=18006 Silk Road, North China] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20131002140921/http://www.megalithic.co.uk/article.php?sid=18006 |date=October 2, 2013 }}, The Megalithic Portal. 19 November 2007</ref>\n* Rubies have always been held in high esteem in Asian countries. They were used to ornament armor, scabbards, and harnesses of noblemen in India and China. Rubies were laid beneath the foundation of buildings to secure good fortune to the structure.\n*Some other sources explain that the Indian culture worships rubies to be the \"gemstone of the sun\", leader of the nine planets. <ref name=\"smith\">{{cite book|last = Smith|first = Henry G.|title = Gems and Precious Stones|publisher = Charles Potter Government Printer, Australia|year = 1896|url = http://www.farlang.com/gemstones/smith-gems-prec-stones/page_028|chapter = Chapter 2, Sapphires, Rubies|url-status = live|archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20070929090904/http://www.farlang.com/gemstones/smith-gems-prec-stones/page_028|archivedate = September 29, 2007|df = mdy-all}}</ref>\n{{clear}}\n\n==See also==\n{{Wikipedia books|Gemstones}}\n{{Portal|Minerals}}\n*[[Anyolite]]\n*[[List of individual gemstones]]\n*[[List of minerals]]\n*[[Shelby Gem Factory]]\n*[[Verneuil process]]\n*[[Emerald]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category}}\n* [http://www.gemstone.org/gem-by-gem/english/ruby.html International Colored Stone Association's ruby overview page]\n* [http://webmineral.com/data/Corundum.shtml  Webmineral crystallographic and mineral info]\n\n{{Jewellery}}\n{{Gemstone}}\n{{Use American English|date=August 2015}}  \n{{Use mdy dates|date=August 2015}}\n\n[[Category:Aluminium minerals]]\n[[Category:Oxide minerals]]\n[[Category:Superhard materials]]\n[[Category:Trigonal minerals]]\n[[Category:Luminescent minerals]]\n[[Category:Corundum gemstones]]\n", "name_user": "Aquaduct04372 2", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Ruby"}
{"title_page": "Garrett Gilbert", "text_new": "{{short description|American football quarterback}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| image         = Garrett Gilbert browns 2019 preseason (cropped).jpg\n| image_size    = \n| name          = Garrett Gilbert\n| caption       = Gilbert with the Cleveland Browns in 2019\n| current_team  = Cleveland Browns\n| number        = 3\n| position      = [[Quarterback]]\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1991|7|1|mf=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Buffalo, New York]]\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| height_ft     = 6\n| height_in     = 4\n| weight_lbs    = 230\n| high_school   = [[Lake Travis High School|Lake Travis]] ([[Austin, Texas]])\n| college       = [[SMU Mustangs football|SMU]]<br/>[[Texas Longhorns football|Texas]]\n| draftyear     = 2014\n| draftround    = 6\n| draftpick     = 214\n| pastteams     = \n* [[History of the St. Louis Rams|St. Louis Rams]] ({{NFL Year|2014}})*\n* [[New England Patriots]] ({{NFL Year|2014}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2015}})*\n* [[Detroit Lions]] ({{NFL Year|2015}})*\n* [[Oakland Raiders]] ({{NFL Year|2015}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2016}})*\n* [[Carolina Panthers]] ({{NFL Year|2017}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2018}})\n* [[Orlando Apollos]] ({{AAF Year|2019}})\n* [[Cleveland Browns]] ({{NFL Year|2019}}\u2013present)\n| pastteamsnote = yes\n| status        = Active \n| highlights    = \n* [[Mr. Football Award (Texas)|Mr. Texas Football]] (2008)\n* Gatorade Male Athlete of the Year (2008)\n* Gatorade Football Player of the Year (2008)\n* USA Today Offensive Player of the Year (2008)\n* ''[[USA Today]]'' High School All-American ([[2008 USA Today All-USA high school football team|2008]])\n| statleague    = NFL\n| statseason    = 2019\n| statweek      = \n| statlabel1    = Passing completions\n| statvalue1    = 2\n| statlabel2    = Passing attempts\n| statvalue2    = 6\n| statlabel3    = Percentage\n| statvalue3    = 33.3%\n| statlabel4    = [[Touchdowns|TD]]\u2013[[Interceptions|INT]]\n| statvalue4    = 0\u20130\n| statlabel5    = Passing yards\n| statvalue5    = 40\n| statlabel6    = [[Passer rating]]\n| statvalue6    = 57.6\n| nflnew        = garrettgilbert/2549982\n| pfr           = G/GilbGa01\n}}\n'''Garrett Antone Gilbert''' (born July 1, 1991) is an [[American football]] [[quarterback]] for the [[Cleveland Browns]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). Regarded as one of the best high school quarterbacks of his class, he played [[college football]] at [[Texas Longhorns football|Texas]] and [[SMU Mustangs football|SMU]] and was selected by the [[History of the St. Louis Rams|St. Louis Rams]] in the sixth round of the [[2014 NFL Draft]]. He is the son of former NFL quarterback [[Gale Gilbert]].\n\nGilbert initially saw little playing time as a professional and was primarily assigned to the offseason and practice squads of his teams during his first five seasons in the NFL. He came to prominence as the starting quarterback of the [[Orlando Apollos]] of the [[Alliance of American Football]] (AAF) in 2019 where he led the league in yards and passer rating and helped his team obtain a league-best 7-1 record and playoff berth. After the AAF suspended operations before the scheduled conclusion of the season, Gilbert signed with the Browns.\n\n==High school career==\nGilbert made his first high school start during his sophomore year in the 2006 [[Texas Football Classic]], where he led the Cavaliers to a 41\u201334 victory over Texas City. His performance caused Texas gridiron sportswriters to take notice, including Lone Star Gridiron's Chris Doelle who referred to Gilbert as \"the best high school quarterback I have seen EVER.\" <ref name=\"LSG 09-02-96\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.lonestargridiron.com/2006/09/02/bonus-4a-austin-lake-travis-vs-texas-city/ |title=BONUS \u2013 4A Austin Lake Travis vs. Texas City |last=Doelle |first=Chris |date=September 2, 2006 |publisher=Lone Star Gridiron}}</ref>\n\nGilbert guided Lake Travis to the 2007 Texas [[University Interscholastic League|UIL]] Class 4A Division II State Championship. Upon completing the 2007 season, he broke state records for completions (359), pass attempts (555) and yards (4,827).<ref name=\"AAS 12-28-08\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.statesman.com/sports/content/sports/stories/highschool/12/28/1228gilbert.html |title=A truly Fabulous year for Lake Travis' Gilbert |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090204121625/http://www.statesman.com/sports/content/sports/stories/highschool/12/28/1228gilbert.html |archive-date=February 4, 2009}}</ref>\n\nAfter Lake Travis won the 2007 championship, the team's head coach, Jeff Dicus, resigned to take the head coaching position at Class 5A [[Duncanville High School]]. [[Chad Morris]], then the head coach at [[Stephenville High School]], became the new coach. Prior to his senior season, Gilbert learned Morris' offense.<ref name=\"AAS 12-28-08\" />\n\nOn top of the coaching change, Gilbert had to undergo minor [[shoulder]] surgery, which took five months to recover. He was not able to lift weights during the five-month period, and instead performed rehabilitation exercises. Gilbert recovered in time to play the first game of the 2008 season.<ref name=\"AAS 12-28-08\" />\n\nIn the 2008 season, Gilbert led Lake Travis to a perfect 16\u20130 record<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.news-journal.com/sports/content/sports/stories/2008/12/21/12212008_lobomain.html?imw=Y |title=Title eludes Lobos: Lake Travis' Gilbert lives up to billing in 48\u201323 win}}</ref> and its second straight state title. He finished the season with 4,851 passing yards for 55 [[touchdown]]s.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.wacotrib.com/highschools/content/sports/highschools/stories/2008/12/21/12212008wacUILplayoffs.html |title=HIGH SCHOOL STATE TITLE GAMES: Lake Travis claims 2nd straight 4A state crown}}</ref>\n\nGilbert completed his high school career setting a state record of 12,534<ref name=\"Texas High School Football Records\">{{Cite news |url=http://lonestargridiron.com/history-records/all-time-individual-team-records/passing-career-yardage-leaders/ |title=Texas High School Football Passing Career Yardage Leaders |publisher=Lone Star Gridiron}}</ref> passing yards, breaking the previous mark set by [[Graham Harrell]] by two-yards. Gilbert initially was indifferent to breaking the record when he had the chance during the 2008 state title game; he only did so after his coach insisted.<ref name=\"SA 1-17-09\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.mysanantonio.com/sports/high_school_football/37779869.html |title=UT recruit looks like can't-miss kid }}{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Gilbert finished second to Harrell for career touchdowns, completions and attempts.<ref name=\"AAS 12-28-08\" /> He led his Cavaliers to a 39\u20134 combined record as a starter from his sophomore through senior seasons.<ref name=\"SA 1-17-09\" />\n\n===Football events===\n[[File:Garrett Gilbert High School.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Gilbert playing for his high school in 2008.]]\nGilbert participated in [[ESPN]] RISE's 10th anniversary [[Elite 11]] quarterback event from July 21\u201324. He was one of the 11 high school quarterbacks selected out of a pool of more than a thousand. The Elite 11 played against each other and received coaching from current standout college quarterbacks.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncaa/recruiting/football/news/story?id=3490003 |title=ESPN RISE Announces 2008 ELITE 11 Quarterback Field}}</ref> An [[ESPN]] columnist pointed out that Gilbert was the most likely player from the camp to win the college football national championship.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncaa/recruiting/football/news/story?id=3504655 |title=Murray garners Elite 11 MVP honors}}</ref>\n\nAlong with 79 other high school [[Twelfth grade|seniors]], Gilbert played in the 2009 [[Under Armour All-America Game]] on January 4, 2009.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://insider.espn.go.com/ncf/recruiting/tracker/underarmourgame?&action=login&appRedirect=http%3a%2f%2finsider.espn.go.com%2fncf%2frecruiting%2ftracker%2funderarmourgame |title=Under Armour All-Americans |publisher=ESPN}}</ref> In the nationally televised matchup,<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.espnmediazone.com/press_releases/2008_04_apr/20080401_UnderArmourAll-AmericaHighSchoolFootballGametobePlayedJan.42009onESPN.htm |title=Under Armour All-America High School Football Game to be Played Jan. 4, 2009, and will be televised on ESPN at 8 p.m. ET |date=April 1, 2008 |access-date=December 28, 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080718025339/http://www.espnmediazone.com/press_releases/2008_04_apr/20080401_UnderArmourAll-AmericaHighSchoolFootballGametobePlayedJan.42009onESPN.htm |archive-date=July 18, 2008 |publisher=ESPN}}</ref> Gilbert completed 11-of-22 passes for 161 yards and an [[interception]] as he guided the Black team in its 27\u201316 loss to the White team.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://recruiting.scout.com/2/827398.html |title=Team White Tops Team Black, 26\u201317 |access-date=January 5, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090118165839/http://recruiting.scout.com/2/827398.html |archive-date=January 18, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2009, a [[Scouts Inc.]] reporter predicted that Gilbert would win the [[Heisman Trophy]] before his collegiate senior season.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncaa/recruiting/football/columns/story?columnist=luginbill_tom&page=predictions09/recruiting |title=Future holds national titles and Heismans for Class of '09}}</ref>\n\n===College recruitment===\nGilbert verbally committed to play [[college football]] for the [[University of Texas at Austin|Texas]] [[Texas Longhorns football|Longhorns]] on February 7, 2008, the day after he received the offer in the mail.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/headline/sports/5524460.html |title=Lake Travis\u2019 Gilbert commits to Texas for 2009 |last=Duarte |first=Joseph |date=February 8, 2008 |work=[[Houston Chronicle]] |access-date=February 23, 2008}}</ref> He always had aspirations to play for Texas since he was a child. During his youth, he pretended to play football for the Longhorns, passing the football to himself in his living room and diving onto the couch to catch it. When he was eight, he had the chance to play catch with then-Texas quarterback [[Major Applewhite]], whom he considered to be his idol growing up. His family members were also season ticket holders.<ref name=\"AAS 12-28-08\" />\n\nGilbert was rated as a five-star prospect by ''[[Rivals.com]]''.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.statesman.com/blogs/content/shared-gen/blogs/austin/longhorns/entries/2008/01/30/gilbert_earns_f.html |title=Quarterback recruit Gilbert earns fifth star |last=Trubow |first=Alan |date=January 30, 2008 |work=[[Austin American-Statesman]] |access-date=February 23, 2008}}</ref> Alongside [[Matt Barkley]] of [[Mater Dei High School (Santa Ana, California)|Mater Dei High School]] in [[California]], Gilbert was the premier quarterback prospect of the class of 2009. Former college head coach [[Jackie Sherrill]] called Gilbert the best quarterback he has seen since [[Dan Marino]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.statesman.com/sports/content/sports/stories/highschool/08/10/0810fabside.html |title=Gilbert or McFarland? For Fab 55, give me the QB}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and honors===\n* 2007, 2008 ''[[Austin American-Statesman]]'' Player of the Year (became the first player to win the honor outright twice)<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.statesman.com/blogs/content/shared-gen/blogs/austin/varsitynews/entries/2008/12/26/and_the_winners.html |title=Gilbert, Stony Point Septuplets on CenTex team}}</ref>\n* 2008 [[Mr. Football Award (Texas)|Mr. Texas Football]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.texasfootball.com/mr-texas-football/?ref=subnav |title=Mr. Texas Football Player of the Year \u2013 Dave Campbell's Texas Football |website=www.texasfootball.com |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref>\n* 2008 [[Gatorade Player of the Year awards|Gatorade National Football Player of the Year]] award; became the first Texas player to receive the honor.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://newsblaze.com/story/2008120907030300016.pnw/topstory.html |title=Gatorade National Football Player of the Year: Garrett Gilbert}}</ref>\n* 2008 Texas [[Associated Press]] Sports Editors Class 4A all-state team<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.tdtnews.com/story/2008/12/19/54495 |title=Killeen's Scales highlights The AP Sports Editors Class 4A all-state team}}</ref>\n* 2008 Texas Associated Press Sports Editors Class 4A Player of the Year<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/APStories/stories/D95645V00.html |title=Lake Travis QB named Texas APSE player of year}}</ref>\n* 2008 ''[[USA Today]]'' Offensive Player of the Year<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/preps/football/2008-all-usa.htm |title=All-USA honors split between Florida, Texas and Hawaii |date=January 1, 2009 |work=USA Today |access-date=May 3, 2010}}</ref>\n* 2009 ''[[Parade (magazine)|Parade]]'' All-American and Player of the Year<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.parade.com/news/2009/01/parade-all-america-high-school-football-team.html |title=Meet PARADE's All-America High School Football Team}}</ref>\n* 2008 [[EA Sports]] Mr. Football USA<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://proxy.espn.go.com/highschool/rise/football/news/story?id=3851921 |title=Gilbert takes home top football award}}</ref>\n* 2008 Built Ford Tough Class 4A Texas High School Player of the Year<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.tylerpaper.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20090210/SPORTS05/902100310 |title=Tucker Named 3A Top Player}}</ref>\n* 2008\u20132009 MaxPreps Male Athlete of the Year<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.maxpreps.com/news/tmVzrl0lEd6pcwAcxJTdpg/maxpreps-male-athlete-of-the-year--garrett-gilbert.htm |title=MaxPreps Male Athlete of the Year: Garrett Gilbert}}</ref>\n* 2009 Gatorade Male High School Athlete of the Year<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.maxpreps.com/news/FVC6fHFSEd6OEwAcxJTdpg/gatorade-aoys--diggins,-gilbert-take-top-honors.htm |title=Gatorade AOYs: Diggins, Gilbert Take Top Honors \u2013 MaxPreps |date=July 15, 2009 |website=MaxPreps.com |language=en |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\n\n===2009 season===\n[[File:Gilbert BCS Game.jpg|right|thumb|Gilbert drops back for a pass in the BCS National Championship game.|275px]]\n{{see also|2009 Texas Longhorns football team}}\nIt was at first thought that Gilbert would likely redshirt in 2009 and compete for the starting job in 2010. However, since former backup quarterback [[John Chiles]] was moved to [[wide receiver]], Gilbert competed with Sherrod Harris for the backup job during the off-season. On August 23, 2009, Gilbert became the second-string quarterback as a true freshman, in front of the junior Harris.\n\nIn the 2009 season opener against [[2009 Louisiana\u2013Monroe Warhawks football team|Louisiana-Monroe]], Gilbert lined up behind center during the fourth quarter and drove the Longhorns down the field, completing four-of-five passes for 46 yards, before scoring a twelve-yard rushing [[touchdown]] on a quarterback draw play to end the drive.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://ulmwarhawks.com/news/2009/9/6/204788729 |title=No. 2 Texas Defeats ULM 59\u201320 |website=University of Louisiana Monroe Athletics |language=en |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn January 7, 2010, in the [[2010 BCS National Championship Game|BCS National Championship Game]], Gilbert replaced the injured [[Colt McCoy]]. Gilbert completed 15-of-40 passes for 186 yards, two touchdowns, and four [[interception]]s. One analyst took the position that his stat line did not reflect how well he actually played (even though he was responsible for five turnovers \u2013 the four interceptions and a lost [[fumble]]), and that several of his passes that should have been caught were dropped.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/bowls09/news/story?id=4807359 |title=ESPN: Title Game a \"Humbling\" Experience}}</ref> Gilbert led the Longhorns to two scoring drives in the second half to spark a comeback, bringing the score to 24\u201321 [[2009 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]]. However, the comeback ultimately fell short late in the game with a turnover inside the Texas five\u2013yard line. The Longhorns lost the game 37\u201321.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=300070333 |title=Texas Longhorns vs. Alabama Crimson Tide}}</ref>\n\n===2010 season===\n{{see also|2010 Texas Longhorns football team}}\nGilbert was the starting quarterback during 2010 season. He led the team to a 5\u20137 record, Texas' first losing season since [[1997 Texas Longhorns football team|1997]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/texas/index.html |title=Texas Longhorns Football Record By Year |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref> Against Kansas State, he threw for 5 interceptions as the Longhorns lost by a score of 39\u201314. In that game, Kansas State also only attempted four passes.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/boxscore?gameId=303102306 |title=Texas vs. Kansas State \u2013 Box Score \u2013 November 6, 2010 \u2013 ESPN |website=ESPN.com}}</ref> Soon after that year's bowl season, [[Mack Brown]] announced that every job was up for grabs, leaving Gilbert to compete with sophomores [[Case McCoy]] and Conner Wood, as well as freshman [[David Ash (American football)|David Ash]].\n\n===2011 season===\nOn August 29, it was announced that Gilbert would retain the starting position in the season opener against [[2011 Rice Owls football team|Rice]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.crimsonandcreammachine.com/2011/8/29/2391332/texas-longhorns-name-starting-qb-garrett-gilbert |title=Texas Longhorns Name Starting QB: Garrett Gilbert |last=DeCray |first=Rich |date=August 29, 2011 |website=Crimson And Cream Machine |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref> However, on September 12, it was announced that he was being demoted to the second-string quarterback behind McCoy and Ash, who would share the starting position. On September 20, it was announced that Gilbert underwent successful surgery on his [[shoulder]] and was ruled out the remainder of the season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/6996396 |title=Texas QB Gilbert has surgery, out for season |date=September 20, 2011 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nGilbert was granted his unconditional release from Texas on October 5, allowing him the opportunity to seek a transfer.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/dallas/colleges/post/_/id/4674129/garrett-gilbert-to-transfer-from-texas |title=Garrett Gilbert to transfer from Texas |date=October 5, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |access-date=October 5, 2011}}</ref> Later that day, he was seen at [[Southern Methodist University]] (SMU), watching the [[SMU Mustangs football|football team]] practice.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://collegefootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2011/10/05/garrett-gilbert-reportedly-at-smu-practice/ |title=Updated: Garrett Gilbert given unconditional release from UT |last=Kercheval |first=Ben |date=October 5, 2011 |work=NBC Sports |access-date=October 5, 2011}}</ref> He completed his [[Academic degree|degree]] at Texas and transferred to SMU for the 2012 season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/dallas/ncf/story/_/id/7178558 |title=Source: Ex-Texas QB Gilbert to transfer to SMU |date=November 1, 2011 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2012 season===\nGilbert won the starting job at SMU, where he ran [[June Jones]]'s [[run and shoot offense]]. He began the season with an inconsistent performance at [[2012 Baylor Bears football team|Baylor]], throwing two interceptions in the 59\u201324 loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2012-09-02-baylor.html |title=SMU at Baylor Box Score, September 2, 2012 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs the season progressed, Gilbert gained confidence, completing four touchdown passes against [[2012 Houston Cougars football team|Houston]] en route to a 72\u201342 win, a game which set the SMU record for points in a game.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2012-10-18-southern-methodist.html |title=Houston at SMU Box Score, October 18, 2012 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref> He had his best game of the season the following week against [[2012 Memphis Tigers football team|Memphis]], throwing for 353 yards with one passing touchdown and two rushing touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2012-10-27-southern-methodist.html |title=Memphis at SMU Box Score, October 27, 2012 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref> Overall, he finished the 2012 season with 2,932 passing yards, 15 touchdowns, and 15 interceptions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/garrett-gilbert-1/gamelog/2012 |title=Garrett Gilbert 2012 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2013 season===\nGilbert passed for 3,528 yards and 21 touchdowns in [[2013 SMU Mustangs football team|2013]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/garrett-gilbert-1/gamelog/2013 |title=Garrett Gilbert 2013 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref> He missed two games due to injury. He finished his college career with 9,761 yards and 49 touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.smumustangs.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/garrett_gilbert_810610.html |title=Garrett Gilbert |website=SMUMustangs.com |access-date=June 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year \n! rowspan=\"2\"| Team \n! colspan=\"2\"| Games\n! colspan=\"8\"| Passing \n! colspan=\"4\"| Rushing \n|-\n! G !! GS !! {{tooltip|Cmp|Passes completed}} !! {{tooltip|Att|Passes attempted}} !! {{tooltip|Pct|Completion percentage}} !! {{tooltip|Yds|Passing yards}} !! {{tooltip|Y/A|Yards per passing attempt}} !! {{tooltip|TD|Passing touchdowns}} !! {{tooltip|Int|Interceptions}} !! {{tooltip|Rtg|Passer rating}} !! {{tooltip|Att|Rushing attempts}} !! {{tooltip|Yds|Rushing yards}} !! {{tooltip|Avg|Yards per rushing attempt}} !! {{tooltip|TD|Rushing touchdowns}}\n|-\n! [[2009 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2009]] !! [[2009 Texas Longhorns football team|TEX]]\n| 10 || 0 || 30 || 66 || 45.5 || 310 || 4.7 || 2 || 4 || 82.8 || 11 || 5 || 0.5 || 1\n|-\n! [[2010 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2010]] !! [[2010 Texas Longhorns football team|TEX]]\n| 12 || 12 || 260 || 441 || 59.0 || 2,744 || 6.2 || 10 || 17 || 111.0 || 100 || 380 || 3.8 || 5\n|-\n! [[2011 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2011]] !! [[2011 Texas Longhorns football team|TEX]] \n| 2 || 2 || 15 || 31 || 48.4 || 247 || 8.0 || 1 || 2 || 113.1 || 7 || 15 || 2.1 || 0\n|-\n! [[2012 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2012]] !! [[2012 SMU Mustangs football team|SMU]]\n| 13 || 13 || 268 || 506 || 53.0 || 2,932 || 5.8 || 15 || 15 || 105.5 || 94 || 346 || 3.7 || 8\n|-\n! [[2013 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2013]] !! [[2013 SMU Mustangs football team|SMU]]\n| 10 || 10 || 335 || 504 || 66.5 || 3,528 || 7.0 || 21 || 7 || 136.2 || 83 || 267 || 3.2 || 6 \n|- \n! colspan=\"2\"| Career !! 47 !! 37 !! 908 !! 1,548 !! 58.7 !! 9,761 !! 6.3 !! 49 !! 45 !! 116.3 !! 295 !! 1,013 !! 3.4 !! 20\n|}\n\n===Records===\n* UT Record \u2013 Attempts, Game (59)\n* UT Record \u2013 Total Plays, Game (68)\n* SMU Record \u2013 Passing Yards, Game (538)\n* SMU Record \u2013 Passing Yards, three consecutive games (1,343)\n* SMU Record \u2013 Completions, Game (45)\n* SMU Record \u2013 Attempts, Game (70)\n* SMU Record \u2013 Total Plays, Game (81)\n* SMU Record \u2013 Touchdowns, Game (7)\n* SMU Record \u2013 Total Offense, Game (635)\n* SMU Record \u2013 Total Offense, Consecutive Games (941)\n* SMU Record \u2013 300 Yard Passing Games, Career (9)\n* SMU Record \u2013 300 Yard Passing Games, Consecutive (5)\n\n==Professional career==\n\n===St. Louis Rams===\nGilbert was selected in the sixth round (214th overall) of the [[2014 NFL Draft]], by the [[St. Louis Rams]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2014/draft.htm |title=2014 NFL Draft Listing |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref> He was released during final cuts on August 29, 2014. He was signed to the Rams' [[practice squad]] on September 1, 2014. He was cut from the practice squad on October 30, 2014.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://collegesportsblog.dallasnews.com/2014/10/rams-waive-former-smu-quarterback-garrett-gilbert.html/ |title=Rams waive former SMU quarterback Garrett Gilbert |last=Holland |first=E |date=October 30, 2014 |access-date=December 8, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141204200012/http://collegesportsblog.dallasnews.com/2014/10/rams-waive-former-smu-quarterback-garrett-gilbert.html/ |archive-date=December 4, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===New England Patriots===\nOn December 17, 2014, the [[New England Patriots]] signed Gilbert to their practice squad.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.patriots.com/news/2014/12/17/patriots-place-dl-dominique-easley-injured-reserve-sign-te-steve-maneri |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151006104859/http://www.patriots.com/news/2014/12/17/patriots-place-dl-dominique-easley-injured-reserve-sign-te-steve-maneri |url-status=dead |archive-date=October 6, 2015 |title=Patriots place DL Dominique Easley on injured reserve; Sign TE Steve Maneri |date=December 17, 2014 |website=Patriots.com}}</ref> He remained on the practice squad when the Patriots defeated the [[2014 Seattle Seahawks season|Seattle Seahawks]] 28\u201324 in [[Super Bowl XLIX]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/super/2015/02/01/super-bowl-xlix-patriots-seahawks/22704073/ |title=Patriots hold off late Seahawks drive to win Super Bowl |website=USA TODAY |language=en |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn June 11, 2015, the Patriots [[Waivers (American football)|waived]] Gilbert.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2015/06/11/report-patriots-waive-garrett-gilbert/ |title=Report: Patriots waive Garrett Gilbert |date=June 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Detroit Lions===\nOne day after being waived by the Patriots, Gilbert was claimed off waivers by the [[Detroit Lions]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2015/06/13/lions-make-a-spot-for-former-patriots-qb-garrett-gilbert/ |title=Lions make a spot for former Patriots QB Garrett Gilbert |last=Gantt |first=Darin |date=June 13, 2015 |website=NBCSports.com |access-date=August 20, 2015}}</ref> He was waived on September 1, 2015.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/detroit-lions/post/_/id/18636/ryan-broyles-among-cuts-as-lions-trim-roster-to-75 |title=Ryan Broyles among cuts as Lions trim roster to 75 |last=Rothstein |first=Michael |date=September 1, 2015 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=January 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Oakland Raiders===\nOn September 6, 2015, Gilbert was signed to the practice squad of the [[Oakland Raiders]]. He was waived on May 24, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.raiders.com/news/article-1/Oakland-Raiders-Sign-Wide-Receivers-Robert-Herron-and-Nathan-Palmer/8015d0fc-6235-4456-bb26-438237535a42 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201044149/http://www.raiders.com/news/article-1/Oakland-Raiders-Sign-Wide-Receivers-Robert-Herron-and-Nathan-Palmer/8015d0fc-6235-4456-bb26-438237535a42 |url-status=dead |archive-date=December 1, 2017 |title=Oakland Raiders Sign Wide Receivers Robert Herron and Nathan Palmer |website=Raiders.com |access-date=June 17, 2016}}</ref> On January 2, 2017, he was signed to the Raiders' practice squad after [[Matt McGloin]] suffered an injury in the final game of the regular season. Gilbert was to serve as the backup in case McGloin was unable to play in the Wild Card Round. McGloin ended up being active as [[Connor Cook]]'s backup for the playoff game. Gilbert was released at the end of the season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000768175/article/raiders-sign-qb-garrett-gilbert-to-practice-squad |title=Raiders sign QB Garrett Gilbert to practice squad |last=Patra, Kevin |date=January 2, 2017 |publisher=nfl.com |access-date=January 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Carolina Panthers===\nAfter working out with the Dallas Cowboys in January,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.star-telegram.com/sports/nfl/dallas-cowboys/article129854289.html |title=Cowboys work out former SMU QB Gilbert, sign 2 receivers to reserve/future list |last=Hill Jr. |first=Clarence E. |website=Star-Teletram |access-date=November 26, 2017}}</ref> Gilbert signed with the [[Carolina Panthers]] on March 24, 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2017/03/24/panthers-sign-quarterback-garrett-gilbert/ |title=Panthers sign quarterback Garrett Gilbert |last=Gantt |first=Darin |date=March 24, 2017 |website=ProFootballTalk.NBCSports.com |access-date=December 12, 2019}}</ref> He was waived on September 2, 2017, and was signed to the Panthers' practice squad the next day.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.panthers.com/news/article-2/Panthers-trim-roster-to-53/04544b8e-4a01-4568-9141-9ed61d2d4c51 |title=Panthers trim roster to 53 |last=Henson |first=Max |date=September 2, 2017 |website=Panthers.com |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170920201032/https://www.panthers.com/news/article-2/Panthers-trim-roster-to-53/04544b8e-4a01-4568-9141-9ed61d2d4c51 |archive-date=September 20, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.panthers.com/news/article-2/Panthers-sign-10-players-to-practice-squad-/13052ee8-0f44-4700-acdb-b5319bd5aff2 |title=Panthers sign 10 players to practice squad |last=Voth |first=Bill |date=September 3, 2017 |website=Panthers.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180313143038/http://www.panthers.com/news/article-2/Panthers-sign-10-players-to-practice-squad-/13052ee8-0f44-4700-acdb-b5319bd5aff2 |archive-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref> He was promoted to the active roster, for the first time in his career, on October 16, 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2017/10/16/panthers-promote-qb-garrett-gilbert-from-practice-squad/ |title=Panthers promote QB Garrett Gilbert from practice squad |last=Alper |first=Josh |date=October 16, 2017 |website=ProFootballTalk.NBCSports.com |access-date=December 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter losing the back-up [[quarterback]] job to [[Taylor Heinicke]] during training camp he was waived on September 1, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.panthers.com/news/panthers-trim-roster-to-53 |title=Panthers trim roster to 53 |last=Voth |first=Bill |date=September 1, 2018 |website=Panthers.com |access-date=December 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\nGilbert was re-signed by the Panthers on December 26, 2018 after [[Cam Newton]] and Heinicke were both shut down for the season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.abccolumbia.com/2018/12/26/panthers-place-qb-heinicke-on-ir-sign-qb-gilbert/ |title=Panthers place QB Heinicke on IR; sign QB Gilbert |last=Gillespie |first=Mike |date=December 26, 2018 |website=ABC Columbia |language=en-US |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref> He served as the backup to [[Kyle Allen]] in the Panthers last game of the season. He made his NFL debut in relief of the injured Allen. He completed his first career pass to [[Ian Thomas (American football)|Ian Thomas]] for 31 yards. He finished the game with 40 yards passing.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201812300nor.htm |title=Carolina Panthers at New Orleans Saints \u2013 December 30th, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref> On December 31, 2018, Gilbert was waived by the Panthers.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.catscratchreader.com/2018/12/31/18163347/nfl-roster-moves-carolina-panthers-waive-qb-garrett-gilbert-sign-13-players-to-future-contracts |title=Panthers sign 13 players to future contracts and waive Garrett Gilbert |last=Smith |first=Bradley |date=December 31, 2018 |website=Cat Scratch Reader |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Orlando Apollos===\nOn November 27, 2018, Gilbert was drafted by the [[Orlando Apollos]] in the [[Alliance of American Football]]'s [[2019 AAF QB Draft|quarterback draft]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://pantherswire.usatoday.com/2018/11/28/former-panthers-qb-garrett-gilbert-selected-by-aafs-orlando-apollos/ |title=Former Panthers QB Garrett Gilbert selected by AAF's Orlando Apollos |last=Riccette |first=Bill |date=November 28, 2018 |work=[[USA Today]] |access-date=November 28, 2018}}</ref> He played for the team during the inaugural [[2019 AAF season]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.oursportscentral.com/services/releases/orlando-apollos-set-final-roster/n-5442986 |title=Orlando Apollos Set Final Roster |date=January 30, 2019 |website=Our Sports Central |access-date=February 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring the inaugural game of the 2019 season against the [[Atlanta Legends]], Gilbert went 15 for 25 for 227 yards, with two passing touchdowns and a receiving score in the 40\u20136 win. He also threw the first touchdown in both Apollos and Alliance history, with a 26-yard toss to [[Jalin Marshall]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://aaf.com/apollos-shine-in-night-of-firsts-for-the-alliance |title=Apollos shine in night of firsts for the Alliance |date=February 10, 2019 |website=The Alliance |access-date=February 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn week 2 of the 2019 season, Gilbert won Offensive Player of the Week with a 393-yard, two-touchdown performance in the 37\u201329 win over the [[San Antonio Commanders]], and set an early AAF record for passing yards in a single game.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://aaf.com/gilbert-reaser-named-alliance-players-of-the-week |title=Gilbert, Reaser named alliance players of the week |date=February 19, 2019 |website=Tom Alexander/The Alliance |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190220063308/https://aaf.com/gilbert-reaser-named-alliance-players-of-the-week |archive-date=February 20, 2019 |access-date=February 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nWhen the AAF suspended operations after week 8, Gilbert led the league in passing yards (2,152), attempts (259), completions (157), and passer rating (99.1). He was also second in passing touchdowns (13), second-lowest in interceptions (3), lowest in interception percentage (1.2), and second-highest in touchdown percentage (5.0) among all starting quarterbacks.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.footballdb.com/stats/stats.html?mode=P&lg=AAF |title=2019 AAF Passing Statistics |access-date=April 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Cleveland Browns===\n[[File:Garrett Gilbert browns vs redskins 2019.jpg|thumb|225px|right|Gilbert playing against the [[2019 Washington Redskins season|Washington Redskins]] in [[2019 Cleveland Browns season|2019 preseason]].]]\nOn April 5, 2019, following the AAF's suspension of operations, Gilbert signed with the [[Cleveland Browns]] of the NFL.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.clevelandbrowns.com/news/browns-sign-db-morgan-burnett-qb-garrett-gilbert |title=Browns sign DB Morgan Burnett, QB Garrett Gilbert |date=April 5, 2019 |website=ClevelandBrowns.com |access-date=November 22, 2019}}</ref> He made his debut with the Browns in Week 5, relieving [[Baker Mayfield]] in the fourth quarter of a 31-3 loss to the [[2019 San Francisco 49ers|San Francisco 49ers]] on ''[[Monday Night Football]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/chrismanning/2019/10/07/takeaways-from-the-cleveland-browns-31-3-loss-to-the-san-francisco-49ers |title=Takeaways From The Cleveland Browns 31-3 Loss To The San Francisco 49ers |date=October 7, 2019 |website=Forbes |access-date=October 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n====Regular season====\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Team\n! rowspan=\"2\"| League\n! colspan=\"2\"| Games\n! colspan=\"8\"| Passing\n! colspan=\"4\"| Rushing\n! colspan=\"2\"| Fumbles\n|-\n! GP !! GS !! {{Tooltip| Cmp | Completed passes}} !! {{Tooltip|Att|Pass attempts}} !! {{Tooltip|Pct|Completion percentage}} !! {{Tooltip|Yds|Passing yards}} !! {{Tooltip|Avg|Yards per pass attempt}} !! {{Tooltip|TD|Passing touchdowns}} !! {{Tooltip|INT|Interceptions thrown}} !! {{Tooltip| Rate | Passer rating}} !! {{Tooltip|Att|Rushing attempts}} !! {{Tooltip|Yds|Rushing yards}} !! {{Tooltip|Avg|Average yards per rush}} !! {{Tooltip|TD|Rushing touchdowns}} !! {{Tooltip|Fum|Fumbles}} !! {{Tooltip|Lost|Fumbles lost}}\n|-\n| [[2018 NFL season|2018]] || [[2018 Carolina Panthers season|CAR]] || [[NFL]] || 1 || 0 || 2 || 3 || 66.7 || 40 || 13.3 || 0 || 0 || 109.7 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|-\n||[[2019 AAF season|2019]] || [[2019 Orlando Apollos season|ORL]] || [[Alliance of American Football|AAF]] || 8 || 8 || 157 || 259 || 60.6 || 2,152 || 8.3 || 13 || 3 || 99.1 || 24 || 79 || 3.3 || 1 || 4 || 3\n|-\n| [[2020 NFL season|2020]] || [[2020 Cleveland Browns season|CLE]] || [[NFL]] || 5 || 0 || 0 || 3 || 0.0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 0 || 39.6 || 3 || -3 || -1 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|- class=\"sortbottom\" style=\"background:#eee;\"\n| colspan=\"3\" |'''NFL Totals'''|| 6 || 0 || 2 || 6 || 33.3 || 40 || 6.7 || 0 || 0 || 57.6 || 3 || -3 || 1 || 0 || 0 || 0\n|- class=\"sortbottom\" style=\"background:#eee;\"\n| colspan=\"3\"| '''AAF Totals''' || 8 || 8 || 157 || 259 || 60.6 || 2,152 || 8.3 || 13 || 3 || 99.1 || 24 || 79 || 3.3 || 1 || 4 || 3\n|}\nSources: <ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/players/garrettgilbert/profile?id=GIL072219 |title=Garrett Gilbert |website=NFL.com |language=en |access-date=April 5, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=https://noextrapoints.com/players/garrett-gilbert/ |title=Garrett Gilbert |last=Swanson |first=Matt |website=NoExtraPoints |language=en |access-date=April 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nGilbert is the son of former NFL quarterback [[Gale Gilbert]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.statesman.com/sports/content/sports/stories/highschool/12/07/1207bohls.html |title=Lake Travis' Gilbert is a grounded but premier passer |last=Bohls |first=Kirk |date=December 7, 2007 |work=[[Austin American-Statesman]] |access-date=February 23, 2008 |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120912211033/http://www.statesman.com/sports/content/sports/stories/highschool/12/07/1207bohls.html |archive-date=September 12, 2012}}</ref>\n\nHe was born in [[Buffalo, New York]], where his father played for the [[Buffalo Bills|Bills]] in the early 1990s as part of the infamous squad that [[Four Falls of Buffalo|lost four straight Super Bowls]]. He moved to [[San Diego, California]], at age three, when Gale signed with the [[San Diego Chargers|Chargers]] (who coincidentally played in the Super Bowl that same year, resulting in a record fifth consecutive championship loss for a player). The family later moved to Austin, Texas, in 1996. Garrett has one brother, Griffin, who played football at [[Texas Christian University]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://gofrogs.com/sports/football/roster/griffin-gilbert/1397 |title=Griffin Gilbert - Football |website=TCU Athletics |language=en |access-date=December 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20121211074455/http://www.smumustangs.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/gilbert_garrett00.html SMU Mustangs bio]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090802004544/http://www.mackbrown-texasfootball.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/gilbert_garrett00.html Texas Longhorns bio]\n* {{youtube|EHwBirQRVBc|Highlights from Gilbert's high school sophomore season}}\n\n{{Cleveland Browns roster navbox}}\n{{Navboxes| title = Garrett Gibert\u2014awards, championships, and honors\n|list1 = \n{{Mr. Football USA}}\n{{USA Today OPOY}}\n{{Gatorade Football Player of the Year}}\n{{Gatorade National Athlete of the Year}}\n{{Texas Longhorns quarterback navbox}}\n{{SMU Mustangs quarterback navbox}}\n{{St. Louis Rams 2014 draft navbox}}\n{{Super Bowl XLIX}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Gilbert, Garrett}}\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Austin, Texas]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Texas]]\n[[Category:American football quarterbacks]]\n[[Category:Under Armour All-American football players]]\n[[Category:Texas Longhorns football players]]\n[[Category:SMU Mustangs football players]]\n[[Category:St. Louis Rams players]]\n[[Category:New England Patriots players]]\n[[Category:Detroit Lions players]]\n[[Category:Oakland Raiders players]]\n[[Category:Carolina Panthers players]]\n[[Category:Orlando Apollos players]]\n[[Category:Cleveland Browns players]]\n[[Category:Super Bowl champions]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football quarterback}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n| image         = Garrett Gilbert browns 2019 preseason (cropped).jpg\n| image_size    = \n| name          = Garrett Gilbert\n| caption       = Gilbert with the Cleveland Browns in 2019\n| current_team  = Cleveland Browns\n| number        = 3\n| position      = [[Quarterback]]\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1991|7|1|mf=y}}\n| birth_place   = [[Buffalo, New York]]\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| height_ft     = 6\n| height_in     = 4\n| weight_lbs    = 230\n| high_school   = [[Lake Travis High School|Lake Travis]] ([[Austin, Texas]])\n| college       = [[SMU Mustangs football|SMU]]<br/>[[Texas Longhorns football|Texas]]\n| draftyear     = 2014\n| draftround    = 6\n| draftpick     = 214\n| pastteams     = \n* [[History of the St. Louis Rams|St. Louis Rams]] ({{NFL Year|2014}})*\n* [[New England Patriots]] ({{NFL Year|2014}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2015}})*\n* [[Detroit Lions]] ({{NFL Year|2015}})*\n* [[Oakland Raiders]] ({{NFL Year|2015}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2016}})*\n* [[Carolina Panthers]] ({{NFL Year|2017}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2018}})\n* [[Orlando Apollos]] ({{AAF Year|2019}})\n* [[Cleveland Browns]] ({{NFL Year|2019}}\u2013present)\n| pastteamsnote = yes\n| status        = Active \n| highlights    = \n* [[Super Bowl]] champion ([[Super Bowl XLIX|XLIX]])\n* [[Mr. Football Award (Texas)|Mr. Texas Football]] (2008)\n* Gatorade Male Athlete of the Year (2008)\n* Gatorade Football Player of the Year (2008)\n* USA Today Offensive Player of the Year (2008)\n* ''[[USA Today]]'' High School All-American ([[2008 USA Today All-USA high school football team|2008]])\n| statleague    = NFL\n| statseason    = 2019\n| statweek      = \n| statlabel1    = Passing completions\n| statvalue1    = 2\n| statlabel2    = Passing attempts\n| statvalue2    = 6\n| statlabel3    = Percentage\n| statvalue3    = 33.3%\n| statlabel4    = [[Touchdowns|TD]]\u2013[[Interceptions|INT]]\n| statvalue4    = 0\u20130\n| statlabel5    = Passing yards\n| statvalue5    = 40\n| statlabel6    = [[Passer rating]]\n| statvalue6    = 57.6\n| nflnew        = garrettgilbert/2549982\n| pfr           = G/GilbGa01\n}}\n'''Garrett Antone Gilbert''' (born July 1, 1991) is an [[American football]] [[quarterback]] for the [[Cleveland Browns]] of the [[National Football League]] (NFL). Regarded as one of the best high school quarterbacks of his class, he played [[college football]] at [[Texas Longhorns football|Texas]] and [[SMU Mustangs football|SMU]] and was selected by the [[History of the St. Louis Rams|St. Louis Rams]] in the sixth round of the [[2014 NFL Draft]]. He is the son of former NFL quarterback [[Gale Gilbert]].\n\nGilbert initially saw little playing time as a professional and was primarily assigned to the offseason and practice squads of his teams during his first five seasons in the NFL. He came to prominence as the starting quarterback of the [[Orlando Apollos]] of the [[Alliance of American Football]] (AAF) in 2019 where he led the league in yards and passer rating and helped his team obtain a league-best 7-1 record and playoff berth. After the AAF suspended operations before the scheduled conclusion of the season, Gilbert signed with the Browns.\n\n==High school career==\nGilbert made his first high school start during his sophomore year in the 2006 [[Texas Football Classic]], where he led the Cavaliers to a 41\u201334 victory over Texas City. His performance caused Texas gridiron sportswriters to take notice, including Lone Star Gridiron's Chris Doelle who referred to Gilbert as \"the best high school quarterback I have seen EVER.\" <ref name=\"LSG 09-02-96\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.lonestargridiron.com/2006/09/02/bonus-4a-austin-lake-travis-vs-texas-city/ |title=BONUS \u2013 4A Austin Lake Travis vs. Texas City |last=Doelle |first=Chris |date=September 2, 2006 |publisher=Lone Star Gridiron}}</ref>\n\nGilbert guided Lake Travis to the 2007 Texas [[University Interscholastic League|UIL]] Class 4A Division II State Championship. Upon completing the 2007 season, he broke state records for completions (359), pass attempts (555) and yards (4,827).<ref name=\"AAS 12-28-08\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.statesman.com/sports/content/sports/stories/highschool/12/28/1228gilbert.html |title=A truly Fabulous year for Lake Travis' Gilbert |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090204121625/http://www.statesman.com/sports/content/sports/stories/highschool/12/28/1228gilbert.html |archive-date=February 4, 2009}}</ref>\n\nAfter Lake Travis won the 2007 championship, the team's head coach, Jeff Dicus, resigned to take the head coaching position at Class 5A [[Duncanville High School]]. [[Chad Morris]], then the head coach at [[Stephenville High School]], became the new coach. Prior to his senior season, Gilbert learned Morris' offense.<ref name=\"AAS 12-28-08\" />\n\nOn top of the coaching change, Gilbert had to undergo minor [[shoulder]] surgery, which took five months to recover. He was not able to lift weights during the five-month period, and instead performed rehabilitation exercises. Gilbert recovered in time to play the first game of the 2008 season.<ref name=\"AAS 12-28-08\" />\n\nIn the 2008 season, Gilbert led Lake Travis to a perfect 16\u20130 record<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.news-journal.com/sports/content/sports/stories/2008/12/21/12212008_lobomain.html?imw=Y |title=Title eludes Lobos: Lake Travis' Gilbert lives up to billing in 48\u201323 win}}</ref> and its second straight state title. He finished the season with 4,851 passing yards for 55 [[touchdown]]s.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.wacotrib.com/highschools/content/sports/highschools/stories/2008/12/21/12212008wacUILplayoffs.html |title=HIGH SCHOOL STATE TITLE GAMES: Lake Travis claims 2nd straight 4A state crown}}</ref>\n\nGilbert completed his high school career setting a state record of 12,534<ref name=\"Texas High School Football Records\">{{Cite news |url=http://lonestargridiron.com/history-records/all-time-individual-team-records/passing-career-yardage-leaders/ |title=Texas High School Football Passing Career Yardage Leaders |publisher=Lone Star Gridiron}}</ref> passing yards, breaking the previous mark set by [[Graham Harrell]] by two-yards. Gilbert initially was indifferent to breaking the record when he had the chance during the 2008 state title game; he only did so after his coach insisted.<ref name=\"SA 1-17-09\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.mysanantonio.com/sports/high_school_football/37779869.html |title=UT recruit looks like can't-miss kid }}{{Dead link|date=December 2019 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref> Gilbert finished second to Harrell for career touchdowns, completions and attempts.<ref name=\"AAS 12-28-08\" /> He led his Cavaliers to a 39\u20134 combined record as a starter from his sophomore through senior seasons.<ref name=\"SA 1-17-09\" />\n\n===Football events===\n[[File:Garrett Gilbert High School.jpg|thumb|right|200px|Gilbert playing for his high school in 2008.]]\nGilbert participated in [[ESPN]] RISE's 10th anniversary [[Elite 11]] quarterback event from July 21\u201324. He was one of the 11 high school quarterbacks selected out of a pool of more than a thousand. The Elite 11 played against each other and received coaching from current standout college quarterbacks.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncaa/recruiting/football/news/story?id=3490003 |title=ESPN RISE Announces 2008 ELITE 11 Quarterback Field}}</ref> An [[ESPN]] columnist pointed out that Gilbert was the most likely player from the camp to win the college football national championship.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncaa/recruiting/football/news/story?id=3504655 |title=Murray garners Elite 11 MVP honors}}</ref>\n\nAlong with 79 other high school [[Twelfth grade|seniors]], Gilbert played in the 2009 [[Under Armour All-America Game]] on January 4, 2009.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://insider.espn.go.com/ncf/recruiting/tracker/underarmourgame?&action=login&appRedirect=http%3a%2f%2finsider.espn.go.com%2fncf%2frecruiting%2ftracker%2funderarmourgame |title=Under Armour All-Americans |publisher=ESPN}}</ref> In the nationally televised matchup,<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.espnmediazone.com/press_releases/2008_04_apr/20080401_UnderArmourAll-AmericaHighSchoolFootballGametobePlayedJan.42009onESPN.htm |title=Under Armour All-America High School Football Game to be Played Jan. 4, 2009, and will be televised on ESPN at 8 p.m. ET |date=April 1, 2008 |access-date=December 28, 2008 |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080718025339/http://www.espnmediazone.com/press_releases/2008_04_apr/20080401_UnderArmourAll-AmericaHighSchoolFootballGametobePlayedJan.42009onESPN.htm |archive-date=July 18, 2008 |publisher=ESPN}}</ref> Gilbert completed 11-of-22 passes for 161 yards and an [[interception]] as he guided the Black team in its 27\u201316 loss to the White team.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://recruiting.scout.com/2/827398.html |title=Team White Tops Team Black, 26\u201317 |access-date=January 5, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090118165839/http://recruiting.scout.com/2/827398.html |archive-date=January 18, 2009 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\nIn January 2009, a [[Scouts Inc.]] reporter predicted that Gilbert would win the [[Heisman Trophy]] before his collegiate senior season.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncaa/recruiting/football/columns/story?columnist=luginbill_tom&page=predictions09/recruiting |title=Future holds national titles and Heismans for Class of '09}}</ref>\n\n===College recruitment===\nGilbert verbally committed to play [[college football]] for the [[University of Texas at Austin|Texas]] [[Texas Longhorns football|Longhorns]] on February 7, 2008, the day after he received the offer in the mail.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.chron.com/disp/story.mpl/headline/sports/5524460.html |title=Lake Travis\u2019 Gilbert commits to Texas for 2009 |last=Duarte |first=Joseph |date=February 8, 2008 |work=[[Houston Chronicle]] |access-date=February 23, 2008}}</ref> He always had aspirations to play for Texas since he was a child. During his youth, he pretended to play football for the Longhorns, passing the football to himself in his living room and diving onto the couch to catch it. When he was eight, he had the chance to play catch with then-Texas quarterback [[Major Applewhite]], whom he considered to be his idol growing up. His family members were also season ticket holders.<ref name=\"AAS 12-28-08\" />\n\nGilbert was rated as a five-star prospect by ''[[Rivals.com]]''.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.statesman.com/blogs/content/shared-gen/blogs/austin/longhorns/entries/2008/01/30/gilbert_earns_f.html |title=Quarterback recruit Gilbert earns fifth star |last=Trubow |first=Alan |date=January 30, 2008 |work=[[Austin American-Statesman]] |access-date=February 23, 2008}}</ref> Alongside [[Matt Barkley]] of [[Mater Dei High School (Santa Ana, California)|Mater Dei High School]] in [[California]], Gilbert was the premier quarterback prospect of the class of 2009. Former college head coach [[Jackie Sherrill]] called Gilbert the best quarterback he has seen since [[Dan Marino]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.statesman.com/sports/content/sports/stories/highschool/08/10/0810fabside.html |title=Gilbert or McFarland? For Fab 55, give me the QB}}</ref>\n\n===Awards and honors===\n* 2007, 2008 ''[[Austin American-Statesman]]'' Player of the Year (became the first player to win the honor outright twice)<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.statesman.com/blogs/content/shared-gen/blogs/austin/varsitynews/entries/2008/12/26/and_the_winners.html |title=Gilbert, Stony Point Septuplets on CenTex team}}</ref>\n* 2008 [[Mr. Football Award (Texas)|Mr. Texas Football]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.texasfootball.com/mr-texas-football/?ref=subnav |title=Mr. Texas Football Player of the Year \u2013 Dave Campbell's Texas Football |website=www.texasfootball.com |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref>\n* 2008 [[Gatorade Player of the Year awards|Gatorade National Football Player of the Year]] award; became the first Texas player to receive the honor.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://newsblaze.com/story/2008120907030300016.pnw/topstory.html |title=Gatorade National Football Player of the Year: Garrett Gilbert}}</ref>\n* 2008 Texas [[Associated Press]] Sports Editors Class 4A all-state team<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.tdtnews.com/story/2008/12/19/54495 |title=Killeen's Scales highlights The AP Sports Editors Class 4A all-state team}}</ref>\n* 2008 Texas Associated Press Sports Editors Class 4A Player of the Year<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.dallasnews.com/sharedcontent/APStories/stories/D95645V00.html |title=Lake Travis QB named Texas APSE player of year}}</ref>\n* 2008 ''[[USA Today]]'' Offensive Player of the Year<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/preps/football/2008-all-usa.htm |title=All-USA honors split between Florida, Texas and Hawaii |date=January 1, 2009 |work=USA Today |access-date=May 3, 2010}}</ref>\n* 2009 ''[[Parade (magazine)|Parade]]'' All-American and Player of the Year<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.parade.com/news/2009/01/parade-all-america-high-school-football-team.html |title=Meet PARADE's All-America High School Football Team}}</ref>\n* 2008 [[EA Sports]] Mr. Football USA<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://proxy.espn.go.com/highschool/rise/football/news/story?id=3851921 |title=Gilbert takes home top football award}}</ref>\n* 2008 Built Ford Tough Class 4A Texas High School Player of the Year<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.tylerpaper.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20090210/SPORTS05/902100310 |title=Tucker Named 3A Top Player}}</ref>\n* 2008\u20132009 MaxPreps Male Athlete of the Year<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://www.maxpreps.com/news/tmVzrl0lEd6pcwAcxJTdpg/maxpreps-male-athlete-of-the-year--garrett-gilbert.htm |title=MaxPreps Male Athlete of the Year: Garrett Gilbert}}</ref>\n* 2009 Gatorade Male High School Athlete of the Year<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.maxpreps.com/news/FVC6fHFSEd6OEwAcxJTdpg/gatorade-aoys--diggins,-gilbert-take-top-honors.htm |title=Gatorade AOYs: Diggins, Gilbert Take Top Honors \u2013 MaxPreps |date=July 15, 2009 |website=MaxPreps.com |language=en |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\n\n===2009 season===\n[[File:Gilbert BCS Game.jpg|right|thumb|Gilbert drops back for a pass in the BCS National Championship game.|275px]]\n{{see also|2009 Texas Longhorns football team}}\nIt was at first thought that Gilbert would likely redshirt in 2009 and compete for the starting job in 2010. However, since former backup quarterback [[John Chiles]] was moved to [[wide receiver]], Gilbert competed with Sherrod Harris for the backup job during the off-season. On August 23, 2009, Gilbert became the second-string quarterback as a true freshman, in front of the junior Harris.\n\nIn the 2009 season opener against [[2009 Louisiana\u2013Monroe Warhawks football team|Louisiana-Monroe]], Gilbert lined up behind center during the fourth quarter and drove the Longhorns down the field, completing four-of-five passes for 46 yards, before scoring a twelve-yard rushing [[touchdown]] on a quarterback draw play to end the drive.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://ulmwarhawks.com/news/2009/9/6/204788729 |title=No. 2 Texas Defeats ULM 59\u201320 |website=University of Louisiana Monroe Athletics |language=en |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn January 7, 2010, in the [[2010 BCS National Championship Game|BCS National Championship Game]], Gilbert replaced the injured [[Colt McCoy]]. Gilbert completed 15-of-40 passes for 186 yards, two touchdowns, and four [[interception]]s. One analyst took the position that his stat line did not reflect how well he actually played (even though he was responsible for five turnovers \u2013 the four interceptions and a lost [[fumble]]), and that several of his passes that should have been caught were dropped.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://sports.espn.go.com/ncf/bowls09/news/story?id=4807359 |title=ESPN: Title Game a \"Humbling\" Experience}}</ref> Gilbert led the Longhorns to two scoring drives in the second half to spark a comeback, bringing the score to 24\u201321 [[2009 Alabama Crimson Tide football team|Alabama]]. However, the comeback ultimately fell short late in the game with a turnover inside the Texas five\u2013yard line. The Longhorns lost the game 37\u201321.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://scores.espn.go.com/ncf/boxscore?gameId=300070333 |title=Texas Longhorns vs. Alabama Crimson Tide}}</ref>\n\n===2010 season===\n{{see also|2010 Texas Longhorns football team}}\nGilbert was the starting quarterback during 2010 season. He led the team to a 5\u20137 record, Texas' first losing season since [[1997 Texas Longhorns football team|1997]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/schools/texas/index.html |title=Texas Longhorns Football Record By Year |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref> Against Kansas State, he threw for 5 interceptions as the Longhorns lost by a score of 39\u201314. In that game, Kansas State also only attempted four passes.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/boxscore?gameId=303102306 |title=Texas vs. Kansas State \u2013 Box Score \u2013 November 6, 2010 \u2013 ESPN |website=ESPN.com}}</ref> Soon after that year's bowl season, [[Mack Brown]] announced that every job was up for grabs, leaving Gilbert to compete with sophomores [[Case McCoy]] and Conner Wood, as well as freshman [[David Ash (American football)|David Ash]].\n\n===2011 season===\nOn August 29, it was announced that Gilbert would retain the starting position in the season opener against [[2011 Rice Owls football team|Rice]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.crimsonandcreammachine.com/2011/8/29/2391332/texas-longhorns-name-starting-qb-garrett-gilbert |title=Texas Longhorns Name Starting QB: Garrett Gilbert |last=DeCray |first=Rich |date=August 29, 2011 |website=Crimson And Cream Machine |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref> However, on September 12, it was announced that he was being demoted to the second-string quarterback behind McCoy and Ash, who would share the starting position. On September 20, it was announced that Gilbert underwent successful surgery on his [[shoulder]] and was ruled out the remainder of the season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/college-football/story/_/id/6996396 |title=Texas QB Gilbert has surgery, out for season |date=September 20, 2011 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nGilbert was granted his unconditional release from Texas on October 5, allowing him the opportunity to seek a transfer.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/dallas/colleges/post/_/id/4674129/garrett-gilbert-to-transfer-from-texas |title=Garrett Gilbert to transfer from Texas |date=October 5, 2011 |work=ESPN.com |access-date=October 5, 2011}}</ref> Later that day, he was seen at [[Southern Methodist University]] (SMU), watching the [[SMU Mustangs football|football team]] practice.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://collegefootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2011/10/05/garrett-gilbert-reportedly-at-smu-practice/ |title=Updated: Garrett Gilbert given unconditional release from UT |last=Kercheval |first=Ben |date=October 5, 2011 |work=NBC Sports |access-date=October 5, 2011}}</ref> He completed his [[Academic degree|degree]] at Texas and transferred to SMU for the 2012 season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.espn.com/dallas/ncf/story/_/id/7178558 |title=Source: Ex-Texas QB Gilbert to transfer to SMU |date=November 1, 2011 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2012 season===\nGilbert won the starting job at SMU, where he ran [[June Jones]]'s [[run and shoot offense]]. He began the season with an inconsistent performance at [[2012 Baylor Bears football team|Baylor]], throwing two interceptions in the 59\u201324 loss.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2012-09-02-baylor.html |title=SMU at Baylor Box Score, September 2, 2012 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAs the season progressed, Gilbert gained confidence, completing four touchdown passes against [[2012 Houston Cougars football team|Houston]] en route to a 72\u201342 win, a game which set the SMU record for points in a game.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2012-10-18-southern-methodist.html |title=Houston at SMU Box Score, October 18, 2012 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref> He had his best game of the season the following week against [[2012 Memphis Tigers football team|Memphis]], throwing for 353 yards with one passing touchdown and two rushing touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/boxscores/2012-10-27-southern-methodist.html |title=Memphis at SMU Box Score, October 27, 2012 |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref> Overall, he finished the 2012 season with 2,932 passing yards, 15 touchdowns, and 15 interceptions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/garrett-gilbert-1/gamelog/2012 |title=Garrett Gilbert 2012 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===2013 season===\nGilbert passed for 3,528 yards and 21 touchdowns in [[2013 SMU Mustangs football team|2013]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/garrett-gilbert-1/gamelog/2013 |title=Garrett Gilbert 2013 Game Log |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref> He missed two games due to injury. He finished his college career with 9,761 yards and 49 touchdowns.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.smumustangs.com/sports/m-footbl/mtt/garrett_gilbert_810610.html |title=Garrett Gilbert |website=SMUMustangs.com |access-date=June 17, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Statistics===\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year \n! rowspan=\"2\"| Team \n! colspan=\"2\"| Games\n! colspan=\"8\"| Passing \n! colspan=\"4\"| Rushing \n|-\n! G !! GS !! {{tooltip|Cmp|Passes completed}} !! {{tooltip|Att|Passes attempted}} !! {{tooltip|Pct|Completion percentage}} !! {{tooltip|Yds|Passing yards}} !! {{tooltip|Y/A|Yards per passing attempt}} !! {{tooltip|TD|Passing touchdowns}} !! {{tooltip|Int|Interceptions}} !! {{tooltip|Rtg|Passer rating}} !! {{tooltip|Att|Rushing attempts}} !! {{tooltip|Yds|Rushing yards}} !! {{tooltip|Avg|Yards per rushing attempt}} !! {{tooltip|TD|Rushing touchdowns}}\n|-\n! [[2009 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2009]] !! [[2009 Texas Longhorns football team|TEX]]\n| 10 || 0 || 30 || 66 || 45.5 || 310 || 4.7 || 2 || 4 || 82.8 || 11 || 5 || 0.5 || 1\n|-\n! [[2010 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2010]] !! [[2010 Texas Longhorns football team|TEX]]\n| 12 || 12 || 260 || 441 || 59.0 || 2,744 || 6.2 || 10 || 17 || 111.0 || 100 || 380 || 3.8 || 5\n|-\n! [[2011 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2011]] !! [[2011 Texas Longhorns football team|TEX]] \n| 2 || 2 || 15 || 31 || 48.4 || 247 || 8.0 || 1 || 2 || 113.1 || 7 || 15 || 2.1 || 0\n|-\n! [[2012 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2012]] !! [[2012 SMU Mustangs football team|SMU]]\n| 13 || 13 || 268 || 506 || 53.0 || 2,932 || 5.8 || 15 || 15 || 105.5 || 94 || 346 || 3.7 || 8\n|-\n! [[2013 NCAA Division I FBS football season|2013]] !! [[2013 SMU Mustangs football team|SMU]]\n| 10 || 10 || 335 || 504 || 66.5 || 3,528 || 7.0 || 21 || 7 || 136.2 || 83 || 267 || 3.2 || 6 \n|- \n! colspan=\"2\"| Career !! 47 !! 37 !! 908 !! 1,548 !! 58.7 !! 9,761 !! 6.3 !! 49 !! 45 !! 116.3 !! 295 !! 1,013 !! 3.4 !! 20\n|}\n\n===Records===\n* UT Record \u2013 Attempts, Game (59)\n* UT Record \u2013 Total Plays, Game (68)\n* SMU Record \u2013 Passing Yards, Game (538)\n* SMU Record \u2013 Passing Yards, three consecutive games (1,343)\n* SMU Record \u2013 Completions, Game (45)\n* SMU Record \u2013 Attempts, Game (70)\n* SMU Record \u2013 Total Plays, Game (81)\n* SMU Record \u2013 Touchdowns, Game (7)\n* SMU Record \u2013 Total Offense, Game (635)\n* SMU Record \u2013 Total Offense, Consecutive Games (941)\n* SMU Record \u2013 300 Yard Passing Games, Career (9)\n* SMU Record \u2013 300 Yard Passing Games, Consecutive (5)\n\n==Professional career==\n\n===St. Louis Rams===\nGilbert was selected in the sixth round (214th overall) of the [[2014 NFL Draft]], by the [[St. Louis Rams]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/2014/draft.htm |title=2014 NFL Draft Listing |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref> He was released during final cuts on August 29, 2014. He was signed to the Rams' [[practice squad]] on September 1, 2014. He was cut from the practice squad on October 30, 2014.<ref>{{Cite news |url=http://collegesportsblog.dallasnews.com/2014/10/rams-waive-former-smu-quarterback-garrett-gilbert.html/ |title=Rams waive former SMU quarterback Garrett Gilbert |last=Holland |first=E |date=October 30, 2014 |access-date=December 8, 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141204200012/http://collegesportsblog.dallasnews.com/2014/10/rams-waive-former-smu-quarterback-garrett-gilbert.html/ |archive-date=December 4, 2014 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===New England Patriots===\nOn December 17, 2014, the [[New England Patriots]] signed Gilbert to their practice squad.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.patriots.com/news/2014/12/17/patriots-place-dl-dominique-easley-injured-reserve-sign-te-steve-maneri |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151006104859/http://www.patriots.com/news/2014/12/17/patriots-place-dl-dominique-easley-injured-reserve-sign-te-steve-maneri |url-status=dead |archive-date=October 6, 2015 |title=Patriots place DL Dominique Easley on injured reserve; Sign TE Steve Maneri |date=December 17, 2014 |website=Patriots.com}}</ref> He remained on the practice squad when the Patriots defeated the [[2014 Seattle Seahawks season|Seattle Seahawks]] 28\u201324 in [[Super Bowl XLIX]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/sports/nfl/super/2015/02/01/super-bowl-xlix-patriots-seahawks/22704073/ |title=Patriots hold off late Seahawks drive to win Super Bowl |website=USA TODAY |language=en |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\nOn June 11, 2015, the Patriots [[Waivers (American football)|waived]] Gilbert.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2015/06/11/report-patriots-waive-garrett-gilbert/ |title=Report: Patriots waive Garrett Gilbert |date=June 11, 2015}}</ref>\n\n===Detroit Lions===\nOne day after being waived by the Patriots, Gilbert was claimed off waivers by the [[Detroit Lions]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2015/06/13/lions-make-a-spot-for-former-patriots-qb-garrett-gilbert/ |title=Lions make a spot for former Patriots QB Garrett Gilbert |last=Gantt |first=Darin |date=June 13, 2015 |website=NBCSports.com |access-date=August 20, 2015}}</ref> He was waived on September 1, 2015.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://espn.go.com/blog/detroit-lions/post/_/id/18636/ryan-broyles-among-cuts-as-lions-trim-roster-to-75 |title=Ryan Broyles among cuts as Lions trim roster to 75 |last=Rothstein |first=Michael |date=September 1, 2015 |website=ESPN.com |access-date=January 25, 2016}}</ref>\n\n===Oakland Raiders===\nOn September 6, 2015, Gilbert was signed to the practice squad of the [[Oakland Raiders]]. He was waived on May 24, 2016.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.raiders.com/news/article-1/Oakland-Raiders-Sign-Wide-Receivers-Robert-Herron-and-Nathan-Palmer/8015d0fc-6235-4456-bb26-438237535a42 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201044149/http://www.raiders.com/news/article-1/Oakland-Raiders-Sign-Wide-Receivers-Robert-Herron-and-Nathan-Palmer/8015d0fc-6235-4456-bb26-438237535a42 |url-status=dead |archive-date=December 1, 2017 |title=Oakland Raiders Sign Wide Receivers Robert Herron and Nathan Palmer |website=Raiders.com |access-date=June 17, 2016}}</ref> On January 2, 2017, he was signed to the Raiders' practice squad after [[Matt McGloin]] suffered an injury in the final game of the regular season. Gilbert was to serve as the backup in case McGloin was unable to play in the Wild Card Round. McGloin ended up being active as [[Connor Cook]]'s backup for the playoff game. Gilbert was released at the end of the season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story/0ap3000000768175/article/raiders-sign-qb-garrett-gilbert-to-practice-squad |title=Raiders sign QB Garrett Gilbert to practice squad |last=Patra, Kevin |date=January 2, 2017 |publisher=nfl.com |access-date=January 2, 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Carolina Panthers===\nAfter working out with the Dallas Cowboys in January,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.star-telegram.com/sports/nfl/dallas-cowboys/article129854289.html |title=Cowboys work out former SMU QB Gilbert, sign 2 receivers to reserve/future list |last=Hill Jr. |first=Clarence E. |website=Star-Teletram |access-date=November 26, 2017}}</ref> Gilbert signed with the [[Carolina Panthers]] on March 24, 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2017/03/24/panthers-sign-quarterback-garrett-gilbert/ |title=Panthers sign quarterback Garrett Gilbert |last=Gantt |first=Darin |date=March 24, 2017 |website=ProFootballTalk.NBCSports.com |access-date=December 12, 2019}}</ref> He was waived on September 2, 2017, and was signed to the Panthers' practice squad the next day.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.panthers.com/news/article-2/Panthers-trim-roster-to-53/04544b8e-4a01-4568-9141-9ed61d2d4c51 |title=Panthers trim roster to 53 |last=Henson |first=Max |date=September 2, 2017 |website=Panthers.com |url-status=dead |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170920201032/https://www.panthers.com/news/article-2/Panthers-trim-roster-to-53/04544b8e-4a01-4568-9141-9ed61d2d4c51 |archive-date=September 20, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.panthers.com/news/article-2/Panthers-sign-10-players-to-practice-squad-/13052ee8-0f44-4700-acdb-b5319bd5aff2 |title=Panthers sign 10 players to practice squad |last=Voth |first=Bill |date=September 3, 2017 |website=Panthers.com |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180313143038/http://www.panthers.com/news/article-2/Panthers-sign-10-players-to-practice-squad-/13052ee8-0f44-4700-acdb-b5319bd5aff2 |archive-date=March 13, 2018}}</ref> He was promoted to the active roster, for the first time in his career, on October 16, 2017.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2017/10/16/panthers-promote-qb-garrett-gilbert-from-practice-squad/ |title=Panthers promote QB Garrett Gilbert from practice squad |last=Alper |first=Josh |date=October 16, 2017 |website=ProFootballTalk.NBCSports.com |access-date=December 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\nAfter losing the back-up [[quarterback]] job to [[Taylor Heinicke]] during training camp he was waived on September 1, 2018.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.panthers.com/news/panthers-trim-roster-to-53 |title=Panthers trim roster to 53 |last=Voth |first=Bill |date=September 1, 2018 |website=Panthers.com |access-date=December 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\nGilbert was re-signed by the Panthers on December 26, 2018 after [[Cam Newton]] and Heinicke were both shut down for the season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.abccolumbia.com/2018/12/26/panthers-place-qb-heinicke-on-ir-sign-qb-gilbert/ |title=Panthers place QB Heinicke on IR; sign QB Gilbert |last=Gillespie |first=Mike |date=December 26, 2018 |website=ABC Columbia |language=en-US |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref> He served as the backup to [[Kyle Allen]] in the Panthers last game of the season. He made his NFL debut in relief of the injured Allen. He completed his first career pass to [[Ian Thomas (American football)|Ian Thomas]] for 31 yards. He finished the game with 40 yards passing.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/boxscores/201812300nor.htm |title=Carolina Panthers at New Orleans Saints \u2013 December 30th, 2018 |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref> On December 31, 2018, Gilbert was waived by the Panthers.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.catscratchreader.com/2018/12/31/18163347/nfl-roster-moves-carolina-panthers-waive-qb-garrett-gilbert-sign-13-players-to-future-contracts |title=Panthers sign 13 players to future contracts and waive Garrett Gilbert |last=Smith |first=Bradley |date=December 31, 2018 |website=Cat Scratch Reader |access-date=January 24, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Orlando Apollos===\nOn November 27, 2018, Gilbert was drafted by the [[Orlando Apollos]] in the [[Alliance of American Football]]'s [[2019 AAF QB Draft|quarterback draft]].<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://pantherswire.usatoday.com/2018/11/28/former-panthers-qb-garrett-gilbert-selected-by-aafs-orlando-apollos/ |title=Former Panthers QB Garrett Gilbert selected by AAF's Orlando Apollos |last=Riccette |first=Bill |date=November 28, 2018 |work=[[USA Today]] |access-date=November 28, 2018}}</ref> He played for the team during the inaugural [[2019 AAF season]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.oursportscentral.com/services/releases/orlando-apollos-set-final-roster/n-5442986 |title=Orlando Apollos Set Final Roster |date=January 30, 2019 |website=Our Sports Central |access-date=February 6, 2019}}</ref>\n\nDuring the inaugural game of the 2019 season against the [[Atlanta Legends]], Gilbert went 15 for 25 for 227 yards, with two passing touchdowns and a receiving score in the 40\u20136 win. He also threw the first touchdown in both Apollos and Alliance history, with a 26-yard toss to [[Jalin Marshall]].<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://aaf.com/apollos-shine-in-night-of-firsts-for-the-alliance |title=Apollos shine in night of firsts for the Alliance |date=February 10, 2019 |website=The Alliance |access-date=February 10, 2019}}</ref>\n\nIn week 2 of the 2019 season, Gilbert won Offensive Player of the Week with a 393-yard, two-touchdown performance in the 37\u201329 win over the [[San Antonio Commanders]], and set an early AAF record for passing yards in a single game.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://aaf.com/gilbert-reaser-named-alliance-players-of-the-week |title=Gilbert, Reaser named alliance players of the week |date=February 19, 2019 |website=Tom Alexander/The Alliance |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190220063308/https://aaf.com/gilbert-reaser-named-alliance-players-of-the-week |archive-date=February 20, 2019 |access-date=February 19, 2019}}</ref>\n\nWhen the AAF suspended operations after week 8, Gilbert led the league in passing yards (2,152), attempts (259), completions (157), and passer rating (99.1). He was also second in passing touchdowns (13), second-lowest in interceptions (3), lowest in interception percentage (1.2), and second-highest in touchdown percentage (5.0) among all starting quarterbacks.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.footballdb.com/stats/stats.html?mode=P&lg=AAF |title=2019 AAF Passing Statistics |access-date=April 12, 2019}}</ref>\n\n===Cleveland Browns===\n[[File:Garrett Gilbert browns vs redskins 2019.jpg|thumb|225px|right|Gilbert playing against the [[2019 Washington Redskins season|Washington Redskins]] in [[2019 Cleveland Browns season|2019 preseason]].]]\nOn April 5, 2019, following the AAF's suspension of operations, Gilbert signed with the [[Cleveland Browns]] of the NFL.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.clevelandbrowns.com/news/browns-sign-db-morgan-burnett-qb-garrett-gilbert |title=Browns sign DB Morgan Burnett, QB Garrett Gilbert |date=April 5, 2019 |website=ClevelandBrowns.com |access-date=November 22, 2019}}</ref> He made his debut with the Browns in Week 5, relieving [[Baker Mayfield]] in the fourth quarter of a 31-3 loss to the [[2019 San Francisco 49ers|San Francisco 49ers]] on ''[[Monday Night Football]]''.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/chrismanning/2019/10/07/takeaways-from-the-cleveland-browns-31-3-loss-to-the-san-francisco-49ers |title=Takeaways From The Cleveland Browns 31-3 Loss To The San Francisco 49ers |date=October 7, 2019 |website=Forbes |access-date=October 8, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n====Regular season====\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|-\n! rowspan=\"2\"| Year