{"title_page": "Rick Wills", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=May 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Rick Wills\n| image            = Rick_and_Mac_by_Grifoto.JPG\n| image_size       = \n| caption          = Rick Wills and [[Ian McLagan]] in 1978\n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name       = Richard William Wills\n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1947|12|05}}\n| birth_place      = [[Cambridge]], [[England]]\n| origin           = [[Finchley]], [[London]], England\n| instrument       = Bass, vocals\n| genre            = Rock\n| occupation       = Musician\n| years_active     = 1966\u2013present\n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = [[Foreigner (band)|Foreigner]], [[Small Faces]], [[Bad Company]], [[Jokers Wild (band)|Joker's Wild]], [[Roxy Music]], [[Roger Daltrey]], [[The Jones Gang]], [[Peter Frampton]]\n| website          = \n}}\n\n'''Richard \"Rick\" William Wills''' (born 5 December 1947) is a British bass guitarist. He is best known for his work with the rock band [[Foreigner (band)|Foreigner]] and his associations with the [[Small Faces]], [[Peter Frampton]] and [[Bad Company]].\n\n==Career==\nRick Wills played in the early days of rock music in Cambridge, from c. 1961 in the Vikings, then in a succession of local bands: the Sundowners, Soul Committee, Bullitt (with [[David Gilmour]] on guitars and William \"Willie\" Wilson on drums) and Cochise before joining ''Frampton's Camel''.<ref name=\"Roots of Cambridge Rock family tree\">{{cite web |url=http://s88932719.onlinehome.us/cambridge.htm |title=Roots of Cambridge Rock family tree |website=[[Cambridge Evening News]] |accessdate=18 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nWills joined the [[Rock music|Rock]] band [[Joker's Wild (band)|Joker's Wild]] in 1966, (with David Gilmour on guitars and vocals), replacing Tony Sainty, until they broke up in 1968. He played bass on [[Peter Frampton]]'s first three albums before parting from Frampton in 1975. He became the bassist with [[Roxy Music]] in 1976, before leaving them and joining the [[Small Faces]] in 1977, during their reunion period. He left the Small Faces and appeared on David Gilmour's eponymous album in 1978, with William Wilson on drums. The next year, Wills became a member of rock band [[Foreigner (band)|Foreigner]]<ref name=\"Rick Wills AMG\">{{cite web |url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p138732|pure_url=yes}} |title=Rick Wills\n|publisher=allmusic.com |accessdate=2010-02-18}} </ref> and remained with them for fourteen years. At that time he was the longest-tenured bass player of Foreigner, though was later surpassed by [[Jeff Pilson]].\n\nAfter leaving Foreigner in 1992,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.4eigner.net/theband/members.html|title=Foreigner band members |author=Phoenix |publisher=www.4eigner.net |accessdate=18 February 2010}}</ref> he joined [[Bad Company]] and stayed with them until [[Boz Burrell]] rejoined the band in 1998.<ref name=\"Rick Wills AMG\"/> In July 1999 he filled in for [[Lynyrd Skynyrd]] bassist [[Leon Wilkeson]] for live shows when Wilkeson briefly took ill. He appeared at The Steve Marriott Memorial Concert on 24 April 2001, as part of a backing band with [[Bobby Tench]], [[Zak Starkey]] and [[Rabbit Bundrick]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.humble-pie.net/rockon/pie2/html/news.html |title=Astoria concert 2001 |publisher=humble-pie.net |date=24 April 2001 |accessdate=14 February 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090122213240/http://www.humble-pie.net/rockon/pie2/html/news.html |archivedate=22 January 2009 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.makingtime.co.uk/rfr/memorialcd3.html#.VrISUdKLRdg |title=Mustn't Grumble: Steve Marriott Memorial Concert |publisher=allmusic.com |accessdate=18 February 2010}}</ref>\n\nWills was reunited with Small Faces drummer [[Kenney Jones]] in the Jones Gang during 2006,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.butgroup.com/jonesgang.html |title=The Jones Gang |publisher=butgroup.com |accessdate=18 February 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090320161044/http://www.butgroup.com/jonesgang.html |archivedate=20 March 2009}}</ref> and appeared with [[The RD Crusaders]] for The [[Teenage Cancer Trust]] at The London International Music Show on 15 June 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.soundonsound.com/news?NewsID=10050 |title=RD Crusaders play at LIMS |publisher=www.soundonsound |date=2008-01-05}}</ref>. Wills left [[The Jones Gang]] in the summer of 2015 and was replaced by Pat Davey. \n\nOn 12 January 2015, in [[Sarasota, Florida]], Wills and original drummer [[Dennis Elliott]] joined Foreigner on stage to play \"Headknocker\".\n\n== Discography ==\n\n; Cochise :\n* ''Cochise'' (1970) \n* ''Swallow Tales'' (1971)\n* ''So Far'' (1972) \n* ''Past Loves (A History)'' (1992) - Compilation\n* ''Velvet Mountain: An Anthology 1970-1972'' (2013) - Compilation Double Album \n\n;With [[Peter Frampton]]<ref name=\"Rick Wills AMG\" />\n*''[[Wind of Change (album)|Wind of Change]]'' - [[A&M Records|A&M]] (1972)\n*''[[Frampton's Camel]]'' \u2013 [[A&M Records|A&M]] (1973)\n*''[[Somethin's Happening]]'' \u2013 [[A&M Records|A&M]] (1974)\n\n;With [[Roxy Music]]<ref name=\"Rick Wills AMG\" />\n*''[[Viva! (Roxy Music album)|Viva!]]'' \u2013 [[Atco Records|Atco]] (1976)\n\nWith Kevin Ayers 1976\n*''Yes we have no Ma\u00f1anas (So Get Your Ma\u00f1anas Today)'' \n\n;With The [[Small Faces]]<ref name=\"Rick Wills AMG\" />\n*''[[Playmates (album)|Playmates]]'' \u2013 [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]] (1977)\n*''[[78 in the Shade]]'' \u2013 Atlantic (1978)\n\n;With [[David Gilmour]]<ref name=\"Rick Wills AMG\" />\n*''[[David Gilmour (album)|David Gilmour]]'' \u2013 [[Harvest Records|Harvest]] (1978)\n\n;With [[Foreigner (band)|Foreigner]]<ref name=\"Rick Wills AMG\" />\n*''[[Head Games (album)|Head Games]]'' \u2013 Atlantic (1979)\n*''[[4 (Foreigner album)|4]]'' \u2013 Atlantic (1981)\n*''[[Agent Provocateur (album)|Agent Provocateur]]'' \u2013 Atlantic (1984)\n*''[[Inside Information (album)|Inside Information]]'' \u2013 Atlantic (1987)\n*''[[Unusual Heat]]'' \u2013 Atlantic (1991)\n\n;With [[Bad Company]]<ref name=\"Rick Wills AMG\" />\n*''[[What You Hear Is What You Get: The Best of Bad Company]]'' \u2013 Atco (1993)\n*''[[Company of Strangers (Bad Company album)|Company of Strangers]]'' \u2013 [[Elektra Records|Elektra]](1995)\n*''[[Stories Told & Untold]]'' \u2013 Elektra (1997)\n\n;With [[The Jones Gang]]<ref name=\"Rick Wills AMG\" />\n*''Any Day Now'' - AAO Music (2005)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*The Rolling Stone Encyclopedia of Rock & Roll \u2013 3rd Edition\n\n==External links==\n*{{discogs artist}}\n\n{{Bad Company}}\n{{Foreigner}}\n{{Small Faces}}\n{{Roxy Music}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wills, Rick}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British rock bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:Musicians from London]]\n[[Category:Foreigner (band) members]]\n[[Category:British rhythm and blues boom musicians]]\n[[Category:Small Faces members]]\n[[Category:Jokers Wild (band) members]]\n[[Category:People from Finchley]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=May 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Rick Wills\n| image            = Rick_and_Mac_by_Grifoto.JPG\n| image_size       = \n| caption          = Rick Wills and [[Ian McLagan]] in 1978\n| background       = non_vocal_instrumentalist\n| birth_name       = Richard William Wills\n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1947|12|05}}\n| birth_place      = [[Cambridge]], [[England]]\n| origin           = [[Finchley]], [[London]], England\n| instrument       = Bass, vocals\n| genre            = Rock\n| occupation       = Musician\n| years_active     = 1966\u2013present\n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = [[Foreigner (band)|Foreigner]], [[Small Faces]], [[Bad Company]], [[Jokers Wild (band)|Joker's Wild]], [[Roxy Music]], [[Roger Daltrey]], [[The Jones Gang]], [[Peter Frampton]], [[Spooky Tooth]]\n| website          = \n}}\n\n'''Richard \"Rick\" William Wills''' (born 5 December 1947) is a British bass guitarist. He is best known for his work with the rock band [[Foreigner (band)|Foreigner]] and his associations with the [[Small Faces]], [[Peter Frampton]] and [[Bad Company]].\n\n==Career==\nRick Wills played in the early days of rock music in Cambridge, from c. 1961 in the Vikings, then in a succession of local bands: the Sundowners, Soul Committee, Bullitt (with [[David Gilmour]] on guitars and William \"Willie\" Wilson on drums) and Cochise before joining ''Frampton's Camel''.<ref name=\"Roots of Cambridge Rock family tree\">{{cite web |url=http://s88932719.onlinehome.us/cambridge.htm |title=Roots of Cambridge Rock family tree |website=[[Cambridge Evening News]] |accessdate=18 July 2010}}</ref>\n\nWills joined the [[Rock music|Rock]] band [[Joker's Wild (band)|Joker's Wild]] in 1966, (with David Gilmour on guitars and vocals), replacing Tony Sainty, until they broke up in 1968. He played bass on [[Peter Frampton]]'s first three albums before parting from Frampton in 1975. He became the bassist with [[Roxy Music]] in 1976, before leaving them and joining the [[Small Faces]] in 1977, during their reunion period. He left the Small Faces and appeared on David Gilmour's eponymous album in 1978, with William Wilson on drums. The next year, Wills became a member of rock band [[Foreigner (band)|Foreigner]]<ref name=\"Rick Wills AMG\">{{cite web |url={{Allmusic|class=artist|id=p138732|pure_url=yes}} |title=Rick Wills\n|publisher=allmusic.com |accessdate=2010-02-18}} </ref> and remained with them for fourteen years. At that time he was the longest-tenured bass player of Foreigner, though was later surpassed by [[Jeff Pilson]].\n\nAfter leaving Foreigner in 1992,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.4eigner.net/theband/members.html|title=Foreigner band members |author=Phoenix |publisher=www.4eigner.net |accessdate=18 February 2010}}</ref> he joined [[Bad Company]] and stayed with them until [[Boz Burrell]] rejoined the band in 1998.<ref name=\"Rick Wills AMG\"/> In July 1999 he filled in for [[Lynyrd Skynyrd]] bassist [[Leon Wilkeson]] for live shows when Wilkeson briefly took ill. He appeared at The Steve Marriott Memorial Concert on 24 April 2001, as part of a backing band with [[Bobby Tench]], [[Zak Starkey]] and [[Rabbit Bundrick]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.humble-pie.net/rockon/pie2/html/news.html |title=Astoria concert 2001 |publisher=humble-pie.net |date=24 April 2001 |accessdate=14 February 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090122213240/http://www.humble-pie.net/rockon/pie2/html/news.html |archivedate=22 January 2009 |df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.makingtime.co.uk/rfr/memorialcd3.html#.VrISUdKLRdg |title=Mustn't Grumble: Steve Marriott Memorial Concert |publisher=allmusic.com |accessdate=18 February 2010}}</ref>\n\nWills was reunited with Small Faces drummer [[Kenney Jones]] in the Jones Gang during 2006,<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.butgroup.com/jonesgang.html |title=The Jones Gang |publisher=butgroup.com |accessdate=18 February 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20090320161044/http://www.butgroup.com/jonesgang.html |archivedate=20 March 2009}}</ref> and appeared with [[The RD Crusaders]] for The [[Teenage Cancer Trust]] at The London International Music Show on 15 June 2008.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.soundonsound.com/news?NewsID=10050 |title=RD Crusaders play at LIMS |publisher=www.soundonsound |date=2008-01-05}}</ref>. Wills left [[The Jones Gang]] in the summer of 2015 and was replaced by Pat Davey. \n\nOn 12 January 2015, in [[Sarasota, Florida]], Wills and original drummer [[Dennis Elliott]] joined Foreigner on stage to play \"Headknocker\".\n\n== Discography ==\n\n; Cochise :\n* ''Cochise'' (1970) \n* ''Swallow Tales'' (1971)\n* ''So Far'' (1972) \n* ''Past Loves (A History)'' (1992) - Compilation\n* ''Velvet Mountain: An Anthology 1970-1972'' (2013) - Compilation Double Album \n\n;With [[Peter Frampton]]<ref name=\"Rick Wills AMG\" />\n*''[[Wind of Change (album)|Wind of Change]]'' - [[A&M Records|A&M]] (1972)\n*''[[Frampton's Camel]]'' \u2013 [[A&M Records|A&M]] (1973)\n*''[[Somethin's Happening]]'' \u2013 [[A&M Records|A&M]] (1974)\n\n;With [[Roxy Music]]<ref name=\"Rick Wills AMG\" />\n*''[[Viva! (Roxy Music album)|Viva!]]'' \u2013 [[Atco Records|Atco]] (1976)\n\nWith Kevin Ayers 1976\n*''Yes we have no Ma\u00f1anas (So Get Your Ma\u00f1anas Today)'' \n\n;With The [[Small Faces]]<ref name=\"Rick Wills AMG\" />\n*''[[Playmates (album)|Playmates]]'' \u2013 [[Atlantic Records|Atlantic]] (1977)\n*''[[78 in the Shade]]'' \u2013 Atlantic (1978)\n\n;With [[David Gilmour]]<ref name=\"Rick Wills AMG\" />\n*''[[David Gilmour (album)|David Gilmour]]'' \u2013 [[Harvest Records|Harvest]] (1978)\n\n;With [[Foreigner (band)|Foreigner]]<ref name=\"Rick Wills AMG\" />\n*''[[Head Games (album)|Head Games]]'' \u2013 Atlantic (1979)\n*''[[4 (Foreigner album)|4]]'' \u2013 Atlantic (1981)\n*''[[Agent Provocateur (album)|Agent Provocateur]]'' \u2013 Atlantic (1984)\n*''[[Inside Information (album)|Inside Information]]'' \u2013 Atlantic (1987)\n*''[[Unusual Heat]]'' \u2013 Atlantic (1991)\n\n;With [[Bad Company]]<ref name=\"Rick Wills AMG\" />\n*''[[What You Hear Is What You Get: The Best of Bad Company]]'' \u2013 Atco (1993)\n*''[[Company of Strangers (Bad Company album)|Company of Strangers]]'' \u2013 [[Elektra Records|Elektra]](1995)\n*''[[Stories Told & Untold]]'' \u2013 Elektra (1997)\n\n;With [[The Jones Gang]]<ref name=\"Rick Wills AMG\" />\n*''Any Day Now'' - AAO Music (2005)\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n*The Rolling Stone Encyclopedia of Rock & Roll \u2013 3rd Edition\n\n==External links==\n*{{discogs artist}}\n\n{{Bad Company}}\n{{Foreigner}}\n{{Small Faces}}\n{{Roxy Music}}\n{{Spooky Tooth}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Wills, Rick}}\n[[Category:1947 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:British rock bass guitarists]]\n[[Category:Musicians from London]]\n[[Category:Foreigner (band) members]]\n[[Category:British rhythm and blues boom musicians]]\n[[Category:Small Faces members]]\n[[Category:Jokers Wild (band) members]]\n[[Category:Spooky Tooth members]]\n[[Category:People from Finchley]]\n", "name_user": "188.141.87.103", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eExternal links)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Rick_Wills"}
{"title_page": "Mindless Behavior", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=June 2016}}\n{{Infobox musical artist    <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject Musicians -->\n| name = Mindless Behavior\n| image = Mindless Behavior.jpg\n| image_size = 300px\n| caption = Original Mindless Behavior members (left and right): [[Santo August|Roc Royal]], [[Jacob Perez|Princeton]], Prodigy, and Ray Ray\n| background = group_or_band    <!-- mandatory format: please do not change or remove -->\n| alias = {{Flatlist |\n* The New MB\n* MB}}\n| origin = [[Los Angeles, California]], [[United States]]\n| genre = {{flatlist |\n* [[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n* [[Hip hop music|hip hop]]}}\n| years_active = 2008&ndash;2017\n| label = {{flatlist |\n* [[Interscope Records|Interscope]]\n* [[Epic Records|Epic]]\n* Conjunction}}\n| associated_acts = {{Flatlist |\n* [[Diggy Simmons]]\n* Candice Nelson\n* [[Sean Garrett]]\n* [[OMG (group)|OMG]]\n}}\n| website = {{URL|officialmbmusic.com}}\n| past_members = Craig \"Prodigy\" Crippen, Jr.<br>[[Jacob Perez|Jacob \"Princeton\" Perez]]<br>Rayan \"Ray Ray\" Lopez<br>[[Santo August|Chresanto \"Roc Royal\" August]]<br>[[Elijah \"EJ\" Johnson]]<br>Michael \"Mike River\" Martin\n}}\n'''Mindless Behavior''' was an American [[boy band]] who were best known for the singles \"[[My Girl (Mindless Behavior song)|My Girl]]\" and \"[[Mrs. Right]]\", produced by Walter Millsap. The band was put together in Los Angeles in 2008, by Keisha Gamble, Vincent Herbert and Walter Millsap. The band trained in dance and singing for two years before releasing a recording in Japan Music.<ref name=Lipshutz>Lipshutz, Jason (December 4, 2010). \"Just the beginning\", ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]'' '''122''' (48): 27</ref> The members were all in their early teens when the band was created.<ref>Vena, Jocelyn (November 16, 2010). [http://www.mtv.com/news/articles/1652427/mindless-behavior-break-down-ode-texting-my-girl.jhtml \"Mindless Behavior Break Down Ode To Texting, 'My Girl{{'\"}}], [[MTV News]]. Retrieved February 17, 2011.</ref>\n\nShortly after, lead singer Crippen separated himself from the group, leaving behind the, original, remaining three members. The teen group would then introduce two other members, singer EJ and Mike. The group disbanded into solo careers after, with no intention of reuniting.\n\n==Career==\nThey performed \"My Girl\" on ''[[The Today Show]]'' in November 2010.<ref name=Lipshutz /> Their debut album, ''[[Number 1 Girl|#1 Girl]]'', was released on September 20, 2011.<ref>Caramanica, Jon (September 26, 2011). [https://www.nytimes.com/2011/09/27/arts/music/mindless-behavior-and-leann-rimes-review.html \"Albums by Mindless Behavior and LeAnn Rimes\"], ''[[The New York Times]]''. Retrieved October 20, 2011.</ref> It debuted on the US [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] album chart at number seven.<ref>Trust, Gary, and Caulfield, Keith (September 29, 2011). [http://www.billboard.biz/bbbiz/industry/record-labels/mindless-behavior-cody-simpson-teenagers-1005377702.story \"Mindless Behavior, Cody Simpson: Teenagers Hit the Charts\"], [[Billboard.biz]]. Retrieved October 20, 2011.</ref>\n\nMindless Behavior toured with the [[Backstreet Boys]], [[Justin Bieber]], [[Jason Der\u00fclo]], and was the opening act for [[Janet Jackson]]'s 2011 tour.<ref>Sciarretto, Amy (February 2, 2011). [http://www.artistdirect.com/entertainment-news/article/janet-jackson-to-take-mindless-behavior-on-tour/8692517 \"Janet Jackson to Take Mindless Behavior on Tour\"]. Retrieved March 5, 2011.</ref> Mindless Behavior also headlined the first [[BET]] Closer to My Dreams Tour alongside [[Diggy Simmons]], [[Lil Twist]], [[Tyga]], Trevante, and Jawan Harris.<ref>Thompson, Erica (July 29, 2011). [http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/the-juice/468757/tyga-diggy-simmons-and-more-realize-dreams-in-nyc-show \"Tyga, Diggy Simmons and More Realize 'Dreams' in NYC Show\"], ''[[Billboard (magazine)|Billboard]]''. Retrieved October 22, 2011.</ref> In 2011, Mindless Behavior headlined the SCREAM Tour with [[Diggy Simmons]] featuring [[OMG (group)|OMG Girlz]], [[Jacob Latimore]], and Hamiliton Park. They have been predicted as Future Stars by This Must Be Pop.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thismustbepop.com/2011/11/this-must-be-pop-brings-you-future-pop_14.html |title=brings you Future Pop! (Issue #05) |publisher=This Must Be Pop |date=November 7, 2011 |accessdate=2013-03-11 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20120501143126/http://www.thismustbepop.com/2011/11/this-must-be-pop-brings-you-future-pop_14.html |archivedate=May 1, 2012 }}</ref>\n\nIn July 2012, they embarked their own 25-city tour, (#1 Girl Tour) with opening acts [[Jacob Latimore]], [[Lil Twist]], and rising star Kayla Brianna.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mindlessbehavior.com/news/default.aspxnid=38504 |title=News : MINDLESS BEHAVIOR ANNOUNCES THE #1 GIRL TOUR |publisher=Mindless Behavior |date=May 15, 2012 |accessdate=2013-03-11}}</ref>\n\nIn March 2013, the band released their second studio album, ''[[All Around the World (Mindless Behavior album)|All Around the World]]'' on March 12, 2013 and their feature film documentary, ''[[Mindless Behavior: All Around the World]]''. Mindless Behavior announced the All Around The World Tour starting in July 2013.\n\nOn June 17, 2016, they released the music video for their third single, #OverNightBag. They announced that they were going on a tour their third album \"No Parents Allowed Tour\" but was cancelled soon after for unexplained reasons and are getting ready to release an independent movie titled \"[[Misguided Behavior]]\u201d. In February 2017, rumors started spreading around that the group had disbanded after [[Jacob Perez|Princeton]] announced it after answering a fan question as he claimed that the group wasn't getting the rights to their music and the members decided that they wanted to do solo careers.\n\n==Band members==\n===Past members===\n* Prodigy (Craig Crippen, Jr.) \u2013 lead singer <small>(2008\u20132013; 2014\u20132015)</small>\n* [[Jacob Anthony Perez|Princeton]]  (Jacob Perez) \u2013 backing vocalist, spokesperson<small> (2008\u20132017)</small>\n* Ray Ray (Rayan Lopez) \u2013 backing vocalist, sub-rapper, main rapper <small>(2008\u20132015)</small>\n* [[Santo August|Roc Royal]] (Chresanto August) \u2013 backing vocalist, main rapper <small>(2008\u20132014)</small>\n* [[Elijah \"EJ\" Johnson|EJ]]  (Elijah Johnson) \u2013 lead singer <small>(2014\u20132017)</small>\n* Mike (Michael Martin) \u2013 backing vocalist, sub-lead singer <small>(2015\u20132017)</small>\n\n===Timeline===\n{{#tag:timeline|\nImageSize = width:1000 height:auto barincrement:30\nPlotArea = left:115 bottom:60 top:05 right:10\nAlignbars = justify\nDateFormat  = dd/mm/yyyy\nPeriod = from:01/01/2008 till:28/02/2017\nTimeAxis = orientation:horizontal format:mm/yyyy\nLegend = orientation:horizontal position:bottom\nScaleMajor = increment:1 start:2008\nScaleMinor = increment:1 start:2008\n\nColors =\n  id:lead value:red legend:Lead_Singer\n  id:back value:green legend:Backing_Vocalist\n  id:main value:blue legend:Main_Rapper\n  id:spoke value:purple legend:Spokesperson\n  id:rap value:orange legend:Sub-Rapper\n  id:sing value:yellow legend:Sub-Lead_Singer\n  id:studio value:black legend:Studio_albums\n\nBarData =\n  bar:Prod text:\"Prodigy\"\n  bar:Prince text:\"Princeton\"\n  bar:Ray text:\"Ray Ray\"\n  bar:Roc text:\"Roc Royal\"\n  bar:EJ text:\"EJ\"\n  bar:Mike text:\"Mike\"\n\nPlotData=\n  \n  bar:Prod from:01/01/2008 till:01/11/2013 color:lead\n  bar:Prod from:01/12/2014 till:01/06/2015 color:lead\n  bar:Prince from:01/01/2008 till:28/02/2017 color:back\n  bar:Ray from:01/01/2008 till:01/09/2015 color:back\n  bar:Roc from:01/01/2008 till:01/12/2014 color:back\n  bar:EJ  from:01/04/2014 till:28/02/2017 color:back\n  bar:Mike from:01/06/2015 till:28/02/2017 color:lead\n  width:3 textcolor:black align:left anchor:from shift:(10,-4)\n  bar:Prince from:01/01/2008 till:28/02/2017 color:spoke\n  bar:Ray from:01/01/2008 till:01/12/2014 color:rap\n  bar:Ray from:01/12/2014 till:01/09/2015 color:main\n  bar:Roc from:01/01/2008 till:01/12/2014 color:main\n  bar:EJ  from:01/09/2015 till:28/02/2017 color:main\n\n\nLineData =\n  layer:back color:studio\n  at:20/09/2011\n  at:12/03/2013\n  at:24/06/2016\n}}\n\n===Member adjustments===\nThe group experienced a lot of adjustments since their formation in 2008 that included original members Prodigy, Princeton, Ray Ray and Roc Royal.\n\nIn November 2013, it was announced that lead singer Prodigy left the group to pursue a solo career, which he proved to be untrue. He left the group because of bullying and mistreatment received from the camp.<ref>https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=VcLI_rADtlk</ref> This left Princeton, Ray Ray and Roc Royal as a trio.\n\nIn April 2014, the group announced that EJ would replace Prodigy as the group's new lead singer.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rap-up.com/2014/04/04/mindless-behavior-announces-new-member/|title=Mindless Behavior Announces New Member - Rap-Up -  Rap-Up|author=|date=|website=www.rap-up.com|accessdate=April 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn December 2014, Roc Royal was fired from the group due to his ill-mannered behavior. This included beating up a drug addict over money, having a baby at an early age and accusations of him stealing a producer's car.<ref>[http://www.spitfirehiphop.com/santo-august-amazing/music.70726.php]{{dead link|date=August 2019}}</ref> This in turn prompted Prodigy to return to the group to replace Roc Royal, who served a two-year sentence in prison for battery and robbery.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thacelebritea.com/former-mindless-behavior-member-roc-royal-sentenced-to-2-years-in-prison/|title=thacelebritea.com|author=|date=|website=Go Daddy|accessdate=April 5, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://theshaderoom.com/tsrexclusive-former-mindless-behavior-member-roc-royal-sentenced-to-two-years-in-jail/|title=TSRExclusive: Former Mindless Behavior Member Roc Royal Sentenced To Two Years In Jail - The Shade Room|author=|date=|website=theshaderoom.com|accessdate=April 5, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://music.allaccess.com/an-interview-with-mindless-behavior-about-their-soon-to-be-released-album/|title=An Interview With MINDLESS BEHAVIOR About Their Soon-To-Be Released Album! - All Access Music|author=|date=|website=music.allaccess.com|accessdate=April 5, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn June 2015, Prodigy left the group again, and it turned out that Prodigy was only a placeholder in the group to keep it a quartet. He left when Mike (who was the actual replacement of Roc Royal) joined the group.{{Citation needed|date=September 2019}}\n\nIn September 2015, Ray Ray decided to leave the group to pursue a solo career. This left EJ, Mike and Princeton (who was the only original member of the group left) as a trio until the disbandment of the group in February 2017.\n\n==Discography==\n===Studio albums===\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of albums, with selected chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:5em;\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:16em;\" | Album details\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=\"2\" | Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=\"2\" style=\"width:11em;\"| Sales\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\" | [[Billboard 200|US]]<br><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.allmusic.com/artist/mindless-behavior-p2243671/charts-awards |title=Mindless Behavior \u2013 Awards |website=AllMusic |accessdate=2013-03-11}}</ref>\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\" | [[Top R&B/Hip-Hop Albums|US R&B]]\n|-\n! scope=\"row\" | ''[[Number 1 Girl|#1 Girl]]''\n|\n* Released: September 20, 2011\n* Label: [[Interscope Records|Interscope]], Streamline\n* Format: CD, digital download\n| 7 || 1\n|\n* [[Nielsen SoundScan|US]]: 290,000<ref>{{cite web|url=http://music.broadwayworld.com/article/Mindless-Behaviors-ALL-AROUND-THE