v.com/news/1707339/bet-awards-2013-nominations/|title=BET Awards 2013 Nominees}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Mindless Behavior}}\n* [http://www.mindlessbehavior.com/ Official site]\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Mindless Behavior}}\n[[Category:American boy bands]]\n[[Category:Musical groups established in 2008]]\n[[Category:Musical groups disestablished in 2017]]\n[[Category:Musical quartets]]\n[[Category:American musical trios]]\n[[Category:Musical groups from Los Angeles]]\n[[Category:American contemporary R&B musical groups]]\n[[Category:African-American musical groups]]\n", "name_user": "72.234.126.122", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(you are ads the big you the)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mindless_Behavior"}
{"title_page": "WMIT", "text_new": "{{short description|Radio station in Black Mountain, North Carolina}}\n{{for|the radio station serving Cambridge, Massachusetts, formerly known as WMIT|WMBR}}\n{{Infobox radio station\n| name = WMIT\n| image = <!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:WMIT.jpg]] -->\n| city = [[Black Mountain, North Carolina|Black Mountain]], [[North Carolina]]\n| area = [[Asheville metropolitan area|Asheville metro]]<br>[[Charlotte metropolitan area|Charlotte metro]] (limited)<br>[[Knoxville metropolitan area|Knoxville metro]]<br>[[Tri-Cities, Tennessee|Tri-Cities]]<br>[[Upstate South Carolina]]\n| branding = ''106.9 The Light''\n| slogan = \"Radio You Can Believe In\"\n| frequency = 106.9 [[MHz]] {{HD Radio}}\n| translator = 94.7 W234CF (Boone)<br>HD2: 106.3 W292CJ (Asheville)\n| repeater = 106.7 [[WFGW]] (Norris, TN)\n| airdate = {{start date and age|1941}}\n| share = \n| share as of = \n| share source = \n| format = [[Christian radio]]<br>HD2: [[Christian rock]]\n| power = \n| erp = 36,000 [[watt]]s\n| haat = 942 meters (3,091 ft)\n| class = C\n| facility_id = 5970\n| coordinates = {{coord|35|44|6.00|N| 82|17|10.00|W|region:US_type:city}}\n| callsign_meaning = [[Mount Mitchell (North Carolina)|Mount <u>MIT</u>chell]] is located near the station's transmitter location\n| former_callsigns = \n| affiliations = [[Fox News Radio]]\n| owner = [[Billy Graham Evangelistic Association]]\n| licensee = Blue Ridge Broadcasting Corporation\n| sister_stations = [[WFGW]]\n| webcast = [http://www.1069thelight.org/wp-content/themes/brb/listen/ Listen Live]<br>[http://184.173.80.154/theedge/player.html Listen Live] (HD2)\n| website = {{url|1069thelight.org}}\n}}\n\n'''WMIT''' (106.9 [[Hertz|MHz]], \"106.9 The Light\") is a [[nonprofit organization|non-profit]] [[FM radio|FM]] [[radio station]] [[city of license|licensed]] to [[Black Mountain, North Carolina]].  WMIT is a listener-supported ministry of the [[Billy Graham Evangelistic Association]].  It airs a mix of [[Contemporary Christian music]] with some [[Christian talk and teaching]] programs, including national religious leaders [[Jim Daly (evangelist)|Jim Daly]], [[John F. MacArthur|John MacArthur]], [[David Jeremiah]], [[Chuck Swindoll]] and [[Charles Stanley]].<ref>[https://thelightfm.org/on-air-schedule/ TheLightFM.org/on-air-schedule]</ref>  Studios and offices are on Porters Cove Road in [[Asheville, North Carolina|Asheville]].  WMIT's tower rises {{convert|180|ft|m}} above {{convert|6557|ft|m|adj=on}} Clingman's Peak.  \n\nIn 2007, WMIT began broadcasting in the [[HD Radio]] format, adding \"''theEdge 106.9\"'' on the HD2 channel, featuring [[Christian rock]] music for teenagers and young adults, which is also heard on [[broadcast relay station|translator]] W292CJ (106.3 FM) in Asheville. In addition, WMIT is heard on translator station W234CF (94.7 FM) in [[Boone, North Carolina]], and most of WMIT's schedule is [[simulcast]] on [[WFGW]] in the [[Knoxville, Tennessee]], [[media market|radio market]].\n\n==\"Superpower\" Coverage==\nWMIT has one of the largest coverage areas for an FM radio station in the [[Eastern United States]].  Its signal can be heard in the [[Tri-Cities, Tennessee|Tri-Cities]] of [[Tennessee]] (where it provides city-grade coverage), [[Greenville, South Carolina|Greenville]]/[[Spartanburg]], [[Charlotte]] and its hometown of Asheville.  Recently, the station has begun identifying as \"WMIT, Black Mountain-Charlotte-Asheville,\" acknowledging its large following in the Charlotte area.  \n\nAll told, WMIT claims a potential audience of five million people in [[North Carolina]], [[South Carolina]], [[Tennessee]], [[Virginia]] and [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]. This is because its [[transmitter]] is located on Clingman's Peak, over {{convert|6600|ft|m}} above [[sea level]], one of the highest transmitter sites east of the [[Mississippi River]].  Its [[effective radiated power]] (ERP) is 36,000 [[watt]]s, while many FM stations nearby run at 100,000 watts.   But their towers are only a third the height of WMIT.  Due to its unusual [[height above average terrain]] (HAAT), WMIT is [[grandfather clause|grandfathered]] with a \"superpower\" signal.<ref>[http://jeff560.tripod.com/fm-max.html \"The History of American Broadcasting\" by Jeff Miller. Retrieved 2018-08-20]</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn the summer of 1941, Mount Mitchell Broadcasters [[sign-on|signed on]] W41MM, with 50,000 watts, on 44.1 MHz, within the old FM band.  It is the oldest FM station in North Carolina and among the earliest FM stations in U.S.  The station's transmitter was {{convert|6885|ft|m}} above sea level. Originally licensed to [[Winston-Salem, North Carolina|Winston-Salem]], {{convert|105|mi|km}} away, the station operated by remote telephone line.<ref name=fybush/> The Winston-Salem studios were eventually housed in a two-story building built in 1942 at 419 Spruce Street by the ''[[Winston-Salem Journal]]'' and ''[[Twin City Sentinel|The Twin City Sentinel]]'' for their AM station [[WSJS]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.journalnow.com/news/local/arts-move-black-theater-hall-of-fame-could-come-downtown/article_2d4138eb-7d7d-54a8-a8b9-59c7ed13be35.html|title=Arts move: Black theater hall of fame could come downtown|last=Young|first=Wesley|work=[[Winston-Salem Journal]]|date=2016-06-30|accessdate=2016-07-01}}</ref> \n\nW41MM became WMIT, and moved to 97.3, when the FM dial moved to 88 - 108 MHz.  Sometime before 1950, WMIT switched to 106.9 MHz and relocated its studios and [[city of license]] to Charlotte.<ref>[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/1957/Radio-NE-Ter-1957-BC-YB.pdf Broadcasting Magazine 1957 page 194]</ref>  \n\nIts transmitter rises {{convert|180|ft|m}} above {{convert|6557|ft|m|adj=on}} Clingman's Peak, putting WMIT tower's light higher than anything else east of the Mississippi.  The station's call letters stand for [[Mount Mitchell (North Carolina)|Mount Mitchell]], the highest mountain east of the Mississippi River, located about 2\u00bd miles northeast of the station's transmitter. The two-story building housing the transmitter equipment included living space for station engineers needing to stay during difficult winter weather when the road to the top might be impassable. Diesel engines powered the station at first, but eventually power lines were installed.\n    \nGordon Gray had to close the station in Spring 1950 because he did not have the time to run it. When the station returned to the air in 1951, its power was the equivalent of 325,000 watts.<ref name=fybush>{{cite web|url=http://www.fybush.com/site-030612.html|title=Asheville and Western North Carolina|publisher=fybush.com|accessdate=2015-06-01}}</ref>  WMIT could be picked up in [[Atlanta, Georgia]], {{convert|190|mi|km}} away. Six and a half million potential listeners could receive the signal. Studios were in Charlotte, {{convert|90|mi|km}} away, and programming was delivered by means of an [[Studio/transmitter link|STL]]. Much of the music was [[Classical music|classical]] or [[beautiful music]], though three hours a day of local, regional music was played due to listener interest.<ref>http://ourworld.compuserve.com/homepages/ggninfo/15.htm, Retrieved on 2008/08/14.</ref>\n\nThe station was donated to the Billy Graham ministry in 1963.  At first Graham used the station to broadcast Christian instructional and preaching programs, hosted by Graham and other religious leaders.  But around 2000, the station shifted its focus to airing a music-oriented Christian contemporary format, with some instructional and preaching programs during the day.\n\n==References==\n<References/>\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Official website|http://www.1069thelight.org/}}{{FM station data|WMIT}}\n\n{{Asheville Radio}}\n{{Tri-Cities TN / VA Radio}}\n{{Upstate Radio}}\n{{Charlotte Radio}}\n{{Religious Radio Stations in North Carolina}}\n\n[[Category:Radio stations in Asheville, North Carolina|MIT]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1941]]\n[[Category:Billy Graham]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Radio station in Black Mountain, North Carolina}}\n{{for|the radio station serving Cambridge, Massachusetts, formerly known as WMIT|WMBR}}\n{{Infobox radio station\n| name = WMIT\n| image = <!-- Deleted image removed: [[Image:WMIT.jpg]] -->\n| city = [[Black Mountain, North Carolina|Black Mountain]], [[North Carolina]]\n| area = [[Asheville metropolitan area|Asheville metro]]<br>[[Charlotte metropolitan area|Charlotte metro]] (limited)<br>[[Knoxville metropolitan area|Knoxville metro]]<br>[[Tri-Cities, Tennessee|Tri-Cities]]<br>[[Upstate South Carolina]]\n| branding = ''106.9 The Light''\n| slogan = \"Radio You Can Believe In\"\n| frequency = 106.9 [[MHz]] {{HD Radio}}\n| translator = 94.7 W234CF (Boone)<br>HD2: 106.3 W292CJ (Asheville)\n| repeater = 106.7 [[WFGW]] (Norris, TN)\n| airdate = {{start date and age|1941}}\n| share = \n| share as of = \n| share source = \n| format = [[Christian radio]]<br>HD2: [[Christian rock]]\n| power = \n| erp = 36,000 [[watt]]s\n| haat = 942 meters (3091 ft)\n| class = C\n| facility_id = 5970\n| coordinates = {{coord|35|44|6.00|N| 82|17|10.00|W|region:US_type:city}}\n| callsign_meaning = [[Mount Mitchell (North Carolina)|Mount <u>MIT</u>chell]] is located near the station's transmitter location\n| former_callsigns = \n| affiliations = [[Fox News Radio]]\n| owner = [[Billy Graham Evangelistic Association]]\n| licensee = Blue Ridge Broadcasting Corporation\n| sister_stations = [[WFGW]]\n| webcast = [http://www.1069thelight.org/wp-content/themes/brb/listen/ Listen Live]<br>[http://184.173.80.154/theedge/player.html Listen Live] (HD2)\n| website = {{url|1069thelight.org}}\n}}\n\n'''WMIT''' (106.9 [[Hertz|MHz]], \"106.9 The Light\") is a [[nonprofit organization|non-profit]] [[FM radio|FM]] [[radio station]] [[city of license|licensed]] to [[Black Mountain, North Carolina]].  WMIT is a listener-supported ministry of the [[Billy Graham Evangelistic Association]].  It airs a mix of [[Contemporary Christian music]] with some [[Christian talk and teaching]] programs, including national religious leaders [[Jim Daly (evangelist)|Jim Daly]], [[John F. MacArthur|John MacArthur]], [[David Jeremiah]], [[Chuck Swindoll]] and [[Charles Stanley]].<ref>[https://thelightfm.org/on-air-schedule/ TheLightFM.org/on-air-schedule]</ref>  Studios and offices are on Porters Cove Road in [[Asheville, North Carolina|Asheville]].  WMIT's tower rises {{convert|180|ft|m}} above {{convert|6557|ft|m|adj=on}} Clingman's Peak.  \n\nIn 2007, WMIT began broadcasting in the [[HD Radio]] format, adding \"''theEdge 106.9\"'' on the HD2 channel, featuring [[Christian rock]] music for teenagers and young adults, which is also heard on [[broadcast relay station|translator]] W292CJ (106.3 FM) in Asheville. In addition, WMIT is heard on translator station W234CF (94.7 FM) in [[Boone, North Carolina]], and most of WMIT's schedule is [[simulcast]] on [[WFGW]] in the [[Knoxville, Tennessee]], [[media market|radio market]].\n\n==\"Superpower\" Coverage==\nWMIT has one of the largest coverage areas for an FM radio station in the [[Eastern United States]].  Its signal can be heard in the [[Tri-Cities, Tennessee|Tri-Cities]] of [[Tennessee]] (where it provides city-grade coverage), [[Greenville, South Carolina|Greenville]]/[[Spartanburg]], [[Charlotte]] and its hometown of Asheville.  Recently, the station has begun identifying as \"WMIT, Black Mountain-Charlotte-Asheville,\" acknowledging its large following in the Charlotte area.  \n\nAll told, WMIT claims a potential audience of five million people in [[North Carolina]], [[South Carolina]], [[Tennessee]], [[Virginia]] and [[Georgia (U.S. state)|Georgia]]. This is because its [[transmitter]] is located on Clingman's Peak, over {{convert|6600|ft|m}} above [[sea level]], one of the highest transmitter sites east of the [[Mississippi River]].  Its [[effective radiated power]] (ERP) is 36,000 [[watt]]s, while many FM stations nearby run at 100,000 watts.   But their towers are only a third the height of WMIT.  Due to its unusual [[height above average terrain]] (HAAT), WMIT is [[grandfather clause|grandfathered]] with a \"superpower\" signal.<ref>[http://jeff560.tripod.com/fm-max.html \"The History of American Broadcasting\" by Jeff Miller. Retrieved 2018-08-20]</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn the summer of 1941, Mount Mitchell Broadcasters [[sign-on|signed on]] W41MM, with 50,000 watts, on 44.1 MHz, within the old FM band.  It is the oldest FM station in North Carolina and among the earliest FM stations in U.S.  The station's transmitter was {{convert|6885|ft|m}} above sea level. Originally licensed to [[Winston-Salem, North Carolina|Winston-Salem]], {{convert|105|mi|km}} away, the station operated by remote telephone line.<ref name=fybush/> The Winston-Salem studios were eventually housed in a two-story building built in 1942 at 419 Spruce Street by the ''[[Winston-Salem Journal]]'' and ''[[Twin City Sentinel|The Twin City Sentinel]]'' for their AM station [[WSJS]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.journalnow.com/news/local/arts-move-black-theater-hall-of-fame-could-come-downtown/article_2d4138eb-7d7d-54a8-a8b9-59c7ed13be35.html|title=Arts move: Black theater hall of fame could come downtown|last=Young|first=Wesley|work=[[Winston-Salem Journal]]|date=2016-06-30|accessdate=2016-07-01}}</ref> \n\nW41MM became WMIT, and moved to 97.3, when the FM dial moved to 88 - 108 MHz.  Sometime before 1950, WMIT switched to 106.9 MHz and relocated its studios and [[city of license]] to Charlotte.<ref>[https://www.americanradiohistory.com/Archive-BC-YB/1957/Radio-NE-Ter-1957-BC-YB.pdf Broadcasting Magazine 1957 page 194]</ref>  \n\nIts transmitter rises {{convert|180|ft|m}} above {{convert|6557|ft|m|adj=on}} Clingman's Peak, putting WMIT tower's light higher than anything else east of the Mississippi.  The station's call letters stand for [[Mount Mitchell (North Carolina)|Mount Mitchell]], the highest mountain east of the Mississippi River, located about 2\u00bd miles northeast of the station's transmitter. The two-story building housing the transmitter equipment included living space for station engineers needing to stay during difficult winter weather when the road to the top might be impassable. Diesel engines powered the station at first, but eventually power lines were installed.\n    \nGordon Gray had to close the station in Spring 1950 because he did not have the time to run it. When the station returned to the air in 1951, its power was the equivalent of 325,000 watts.<ref name=fybush>{{cite web|url=http://www.fybush.com/site-030612.html|title=Asheville and Western North Carolina|publisher=fybush.com|accessdate=2015-06-01}}</ref>  WMIT could be picked up in [[Atlanta, Georgia]], {{convert|190|mi|km}} away. Six and a half million potential listeners could receive the signal. Studios were in Charlotte, {{convert|90|mi|km}} away, and programming was delivered by means of an [[Studio/transmitter link|STL]]. Much of the music was [[Classical music|classical]] or [[beautiful music]], though three hours a day of local, regional music was played due to listener interest.<ref>http://ourworld.compuserve.com/homepages/ggninfo/15.htm, Retrieved on 2008/08/14.</ref>\n\nThe station was donated to the Billy Graham ministry in 1963.  At first Graham used the station to broadcast Christian instructional and preaching programs, hosted by Graham and other religious leaders.  But around 2000, the station shifted its focus to airing a music-oriented Christian contemporary format, with some instructional and preaching programs during the day.\n\n==References==\n<References/>\n\n== External links ==\n*{{Official website|http://www.1069thelight.org/}}{{FM station data|WMIT}}\n\n{{Asheville Radio}}\n{{Tri-Cities TN / VA Radio}}\n{{Upstate Radio}}\n{{Charlotte Radio}}\n{{Religious Radio Stations in North Carolina}}\n\n[[Category:Radio stations in Asheville, North Carolina|MIT]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1941]]\n[[Category:Billy Graham]]\n", "name_user": "Stereorock", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/WMIT"}
{"title_page": "Dennis Elliott", "text_new": "{{short description|British musician and artist|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2015}}\n{{BLP sources|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name          = Dennis Elliott\n| image         = File:Dennis Elliott with Foreigner 1977.jpg\n| caption       = Elliott performing with Foreigner in 1977\n| background    = solo_singer\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1950|08|18}}\n| birth_place   = [[Peckham]], [[London]], [[England]]\n| origin        = [[London Borough of Hackney|Hanckey]], London, England\n| occupation    = \n| instrument    = Drums<!--- If you think an instrument should be listed, a discussion to reach consensus is needed first per: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Infobox_musical_artist#instrument--->\n| birth_name    = Dennis Leslie Eliott\n| genre         = \n| associated_acts = [[Foreigner (band)|Foreigner]], [[If (band)|If]]\n| label         =  \n| years_active  = 1969\u2013present\n| website       =\n}}\n\n'''Dennis Leslie Elliott''' (born 18 August 1950,<ref>{{cite news |title= Today in history |date= 18 August 2014 |url= http://nyti.ms/1t9nSQB |newspaper= [[The New York Times]] |agency= [[Associated Press]] |accessdate= 18 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ezrock.com/performer/73823/dennis-elliott |title=Dennis Elliot |accessdate=2007-07-10 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928220946/http://www.ezrock.com/performer/73823/dennis-elliott |archivedate=28 September 2007 |df=dmy-all }}, Ezrock.com</ref> [[Peckham]], [[London]]) is a British musician and artist, who was the original drummer for the rock band, [[Foreigner (band)|Foreigner]]. He played with the band from 1976 until leaving between 1991 and 1993. He went on to become a sculptor.\n\n==Life and career==\nDennis Leslie Elliott played the drums with his family band at age five in shows around [[London]].  As a teenager, he joined The Tea Set with his older brother Raymond, who sang and played trumpet. After The Tea Set, he became a member of The Shevelles at age sixteen. At eighteen, he played in the band [[The Ferris Wheel (band)|Ferris Wheel]] and on their album of the same name. When he was nineteen, Dennis joined the jazz/rock band [[If (band)|If]] and recorded four [[LP record|LP]]s with the ensemble. They continually toured Europe and the US, where he met and later married Iona Elliott on March 2, 1972. Later that year, Dennis joined [[The Roy Young Band]], touring the UK and Europe and recording four singles with that band over the following year.\n\n[[File:Dennis Elliott and his wood sculptures 1997.jpg|thumb|Elliott with Maple Burl Wall Sculpture & Vessels.]]\n\nIn 1974, Elliott toured and played on former [[Mott the Hoople]] lead singer [[Ian Hunter (singer)|Ian Hunter]]'s first solo recording, ''[[Ian Hunter (album)|Ian Hunter]]''. After emigrating to the US in April 1975, he became a US Resident Alien.\n\nHe was the original drummer for Foreigner when the band started in 1976.<ref>{{cite news |last= Gloss |first= Megan |date= 18 May 2012 |title= They've been 'Juke Box Heroes' |url= https://www.questia.com/read/1P2-31391792 |newspaper= [[Telegraph Herald]] |location= Dubuque, IA |via= [[Questia Online Library]] |accessdate= 18 August 2014 |url-access=subscription }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= Stemkovsky |first= Ilya |date= 1 August 2010 |title= Jason Sutter |magazine= [[Modern Drummer]] |via= [[HighBeam Research]] |url= http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-2073462441.html |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140921192558/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-2073462441.html |url-status= dead |archive-date= 21 September 2014 |accessdate= 18 August 2014}}</ref> He officially left in January 1993.\n\nAfter leaving the [[music industry]], Elliott turned to [[sculpture]], working mainly in the [[art medium|medium]] of wood.<ref>{{cite news |last= Pandolfi |first= Keith |date= 1 November 2003 |title= After three decades spent banging out songs such as 'Hot Blooded' and 'Urgent,' former Foreigner drummer Dennis Elliott left rock'n'roll to pursue his real passion\u2014woodworking |magazine= Art Business News |accessdate= 18 August 2014 |url= http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-111164182.html |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140921192652/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-111164182.html |url-status= dead |archive-date= 21 September 2014 |via= [[HighBeam Research]] |url-access=subscription }}</ref> Self-taught, many of his works have been vessels made of burlwood, sculpted wall mirrors, wall sculptures, and orbital sculptures.<ref name=askart>[http://www.askart.com/AskART/artists/biography.aspx?searchtype=BIO&artist=129225 \"Biography for Dennis Elliott\"], Askart.com</ref>\n\nOn June 2, 1990, Elliott and his wife, Iona, were rescued by the [[US Coast Guard]] after jumping from their yacht ''Charisma III'', which had caught fire.<ref>{{cite news |title= Musician, wife go overboard as yacht burns |newspaper= [[Chicago Sun-Times]] |date= 4 June 1990 |via= [[HighBeam Research]] |url= http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4001572.html |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140921192543/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4001572.html |url-status= dead |archive-date= 21 September 2014 |accessdate= 18 August 2014 |url-access=subscription }}</ref> Elliott became a US [[citizenship|citizen]] in 1993.<ref name=askart/>\n\nOn January 9, 2013, he joined Foreigner on stage at the [[Hard Rock Live]] in [[Hollywood, Florida]] to perform \"[[Hot Blooded]]\".\n\nOn January 12, 2015 in Sarasota, Florida, Foreigner were joined on stage by original drummer Elliott and former bassist Rick Wills to play \"Hot Blooded\".[20]\nDennis Elliott joined his old mates for two songs at Foreigner's show on August 2, 2017 at MidFlorida Credit Union Amphitheater in Tampa, Florida.\n\nA pair of '40th Anniversary Reunion Shows\u2019 took place on October 6\u20137, 2017 at the Soaring Eagle Casino & Resort in Mount Pleasant, Michigan, where the current Foreigner group played one set and the Original members consisting of the Head Games-era lineup: Mick Jones, Lou Gramm, Dennis Elliott, Al Greenwood, Ian McDonald and Rick Wills played the second set & were rejoined at the end with all members. The concerts were filmed for future release.\n\nOn August 4, 2018, Elliott again joined a \u2018Reunion Show\u2019 at the Buffalo Chip in Sturgis, SD were the current Foreigner group played one set and the Original members consisting of the Head Games-era lineup: Mick Jones, Lou Gramm, Dennis Elliott, Al Greenwood, Ian McDonald and Rick Wills played the second set & were rejoined at the end with all members.<ref>self</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===The Shevells===\n*1968: ''[[Big City Lights /The Coffee Song ]] (single)''\n\n===The Ferris Wheel===\n*1970: ''Ferris Wheel'' (album)\n*1970: ''Can't Stop Now / I Know You Well'' (UK single)\n*1970: ''Ugly Duckling / I Know You Well'' (US single)\n\n===IF===\n*1970: ''[[If (If album)|If]]'' \n*1970: ''[[If 2]]''\n*1971: ''[[If 3]]'' \n*1972: ''[[If 4]]'' \n*1972: ''[[Waterfall (album)|Waterfall]]'' \n*1995: ''[[Forgotten Roads: The Best of If]]'' \n*1997: ''[[Europe '72 (Live)|Europe '72]]''\n*2010: ''[[Fibonacci's Number - More Live If]]''\n*2012: ''[[If 2 + Live in Liverpool]]''\n\n===The Roy Young Band===\n*1973: ''[[Back Up Train]] (single)'' \n*1973: ''Devil's Daughter (single)'' \n*1973: ''Dig A Hole (single)'' \n*1973: ''[[If You Could Only See Me Now]] (single)''\n*2009: ''The Best Of 50 years (album)''\n\n===Tony Ashton and Jon Lord===\n*1974: ''[[First of the Big Bands]]''\n\n===Ian Hunter===\n*1975: ''[[Ian Hunter (album)|Ian Hunter]]'' \n*1977: ''[[Overnight Angels]]''\n\n===Foreigner===\n*1977: ''[[Foreigner (Foreigner album)|Foreigner]]'' (#4 US)\n*1978: ''[[Double Vision (Foreigner album)|Double Vision]]'' (#3 US, #32 UK)\n*1979: ''[[Head Games (album)|Head Games]]'' (#5 US)\n*1981: ''[[4 (Foreigner album)|4]]'' (#1 US, #5 UK)\n*1982: ''[[Records (album)|Records]]'' (#10 US, #58 UK)\n*1984: ''[[Agent Provocateur (album)|Agent Provocateur]]'' (#4 US, #1 UK)\n*1987: ''[[Inside Information (album)|Inside Information]]'' (#15 US, #64 UK)\n*1991: ''[[Unusual Heat]]''\n*1992: ''[[The Very Best ... and Beyond]]'' (#123 US, #19 UK)\n*1993: ''[[Classic Hits Live/Best of Live|Classic Hits Live/Best Of Live]]''\n*1994: ''JukeBox Heroes: The Best Of''\n*1998: ''The Best of Ballads\u2013 I Want to Know What Love Is''\n*1999: ''The Platinum Collection''\n*2000: ''Hot Blooded And Other Hits''\n*2000: ''Jukebox Heroes: The Foreigner Anthology''\n*2002: ''[[Complete Greatest Hits (Foreigner album)|Complete Greatest Hits]]'' (#80 US)\n*2002: ''The Definitive'' (#33 UK)\n*2004: ''Hot Blooded And Other Hits''\n*2005: ''The Essentials'' \n*2008: ''[[No End in Sight: The Very Best of Foreigner]]'' (#132 US)\n*2009: ''[[Can't Slow Down (Foreigner album)|Can't Slow Down]]'' (#29 US)\n*2014: ''The Complete Atlantic Studio Albums 1977-1991''\n\n===Ian Lloyd===\n*1980: ''Third Wave Civilization''\n\n===Mick Jones===\n*1989: ''Just Wanna Hold (single)'' (#19 US Rock)\n*1989: ''[[Mick Jones (album)|Mick Jones]]'' (album)\n\n==Museum collections==\n*Arkansas Art Center, Decorative Arts Museum - Little Rock, Arkansas\n*Art Museum of South Texas, Corpus Christi, TX\n*The Charles A. Wustum Museum of Fine Arts - Racine, Wisconsin\n*Cincinnati Art Museum, Cincinnati, Ohio\n*The Contemporary Museum of Art - Honolulu, Hawaii\n*Craft & Folk Art Museum - Los Angeles, California\n*The Detroit Institute of Arts - Detroit, Michigan\n*Fuller Craft Museum - Brockton, Massachusetts\n*Honolulu Museum of Art, Honolulu, HI\n*Los Angeles County Museum of Art - Los Angeles, California\n*The Mabel Brady Garven Collection, Yale University Art Gallery - New Haven, Connecticut\n*The Mint Museum of Craft & Design - Charlotte, North Carolina\n*Mobile Museum of Art, (formerly, Fine Arts Museum of the South) - Mobile, Alabama\n*Museum of Arts & Design, formerly The American Craft Museum - New York, New York\n*Museum of Fine Arts - Boston, Massachusetts\n*Peabody Essex Museum, Salem, Massachusetts\n*Racine Art Museum, Racine, Wisconsin\n*Renwick Gallery of the Smithsonian American Art Museum - Washington, D.C.\n*The Slater Museum - Norwich, Connecticut\n*University of Michigan Museum - Ann Arbor, Michigan\n\n==Special collections==\n*Columbia Pictures, Star Trek Voyager set - Wall Sculpture - Bleached Maple Burl\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.denniselliott.com Dennis Elliott's official website]\n*[http://www.askart.com/askart/e/dennis_elliott/dennis_elliott.aspx Askart.com \u2013 reference site for Elliott's sculptures]\n\n{{Foreigner}}\n{{If (band)}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Elliott, Dennis}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English rock drummers]]\n[[Category:Foreigner (band) members]]\n[[Category:People from Peckham]]\n[[Category:English sculptors]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:If (band) members]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|British musician and artist|bot=PearBOT 5}}\n{{EngvarB|date=February 2015}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2015}}\n{{BLP sources|date=August 2014}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name          = Dennis Elliott\n| image         = File:Dennis Elliott with Foreigner 1977.jpg\n| caption       = Elliott performing with Foreigner in 1977\n| background    = solo_singer\n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|df=y|1950|08|18}}\n| birth_place   = [[Peckham]], [[London]], [[England]]\n| origin        = [[London Borough of Hackney|Hanckey]], London, England\n| occupation    = \n| instrument    = Drums<!--- If you think an instrument should be listed, a discussion to reach consensus is needed first per: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Infobox_musical_artist#instrument--->\n| birth_name    = Dennis Leslie Eliott\n| genre         = \n| associated_acts = [[Foreigner (band)|Foreigner]], [[If (band)|If]], [[Spooky Tooth]]\n| label         =  \n| years_active  = 1969\u2013present\n| website       =\n}}\n\n'''Dennis Leslie Elliott''' (born 18 August 1950,<ref>{{cite news |title= Today in history |date= 18 August 2014 |url= http://nyti.ms/1t9nSQB |newspaper= [[The New York Times]] |agency= [[Associated Press]] |accessdate= 18 August 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ezrock.com/performer/73823/dennis-elliott |title=Dennis Elliot |accessdate=2007-07-10 |url-status=bot: unknown |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20070928220946/http://www.ezrock.com/performer/73823/dennis-elliott |archivedate=28 September 2007 |df=dmy-all }}, Ezrock.com</ref> [[Peckham]], [[London]]) is a British musician and artist, who was the original drummer for the rock band, [[Foreigner (band)|Foreigner]]. He played with the band from 1976 until leaving between 1991 and 1993. He went on to become a sculptor.\n\n==Life and career==\nDennis Leslie Elliott played the drums with his family band at age five in shows around [[London]].  As a teenager, he joined The Tea Set with his older brother Raymond, who sang and played trumpet. After The Tea Set, he became a member of The Shevelles at age sixteen. At eighteen, he played in the band [[The Ferris Wheel (band)|Ferris Wheel]] and on their album of the same name. When he was nineteen, Dennis joined the jazz/rock band [[If (band)|If]] and recorded four [[LP record|LP]]s with the ensemble. They continually toured Europe and the US, where he met and later married Iona Elliott on March 2, 1972. Later that year, Dennis joined [[The Roy Young Band]], touring the UK and Europe and recording four singles with that band over the following year.\n\n[[File:Dennis Elliott and his wood sculptures 1997.jpg|thumb|Elliott with Maple Burl Wall Sculpture & Vessels.]]\n\nIn 1974, Elliott toured and played on former [[Mott the Hoople]] lead singer [[Ian Hunter (singer)|Ian Hunter]]'s first solo recording, ''[[Ian Hunter (album)|Ian Hunter]]''. After emigrating to the US in April 1975, he became a US Resident Alien.\n\nHe was the original drummer for Foreigner when the band started in 1976.<ref>{{cite news |last= Gloss |first= Megan |date= 18 May 2012 |title= They've been 'Juke Box Heroes' |url= https://www.questia.com/read/1P2-31391792 |newspaper= [[Telegraph Herald]] |location= Dubuque, IA |via= [[Questia Online Library]] |accessdate= 18 August 2014 |url-access=subscription }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last= Stemkovsky |first= Ilya |date= 1 August 2010 |title= Jason Sutter |magazine= [[Modern Drummer]] |via= [[HighBeam Research]] |url= http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-2073462441.html |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140921192558/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-2073462441.html |url-status= dead |archive-date= 21 September 2014 |accessdate= 18 August 2014}}</ref> He officially left in January 1993.\n\nAfter leaving the [[music industry]], Elliott turned to [[sculpture]], working mainly in the [[art medium|medium]] of wood.<ref>{{cite news |last= Pandolfi |first= Keith |date= 1 November 2003 |title= After three decades spent banging out songs such as 'Hot Blooded' and 'Urgent,' former Foreigner drummer Dennis Elliott left rock'n'roll to pursue his real passion\u2014woodworking |magazine= Art Business News |accessdate= 18 August 2014 |url= http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-111164182.html |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140921192652/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-111164182.html |url-status= dead |archive-date= 21 September 2014 |via= [[HighBeam Research]] |url-access=subscription }}</ref> Self-taught, many of his works have been vessels made of burlwood, sculpted wall mirrors, wall sculptures, and orbital sculptures.<ref name=askart>[http://www.askart.com/AskART/artists/biography.aspx?searchtype=BIO&artist=129225 \"Biography for Dennis Elliott\"], Askart.com</ref>\n\nOn June 2, 1990, Elliott and his wife, Iona, were rescued by the [[US Coast Guard]] after jumping from their yacht ''Charisma III'', which had caught fire.<ref>{{cite news |title= Musician, wife go overboard as yacht burns |newspaper= [[Chicago Sun-Times]] |date= 4 June 1990 |via= [[HighBeam Research]] |url= http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4001572.html |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20140921192543/http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P2-4001572.html |url-status= dead |archive-date= 21 September 2014 |accessdate= 18 August 2014 |url-access=subscription }}</ref> Elliott became a US [[citizenship|citizen]] in 1993.<ref name=askart/>\n\nOn January 9, 2013, he joined Foreigner on stage at the [[Hard Rock Live]] in [[Hollywood, Florida]] to perform \"[[Hot Blooded]]\".\n\nOn January 12, 2015 in Sarasota, Florida, Foreigner were joined on stage by original drummer Elliott and former bassist Rick Wills to play \"Hot Blooded\".[20]\nDennis Elliott joined his old mates for two songs at Foreigner's show on August 2, 2017 at MidFlorida Credit Union Amphitheater in Tampa, Florida.\n\nA pair of '40th Anniversary Reunion Shows\u2019 took place on October 6\u20137, 2017 at the Soaring Eagle Casino & Resort in Mount Pleasant, Michigan, where the current Foreigner group played one set and the Original members consisting of the Head Games-era lineup: Mick Jones, Lou Gramm, Dennis Elliott, Al Greenwood, Ian McDonald and Rick Wills played the second set & were rejoined at the end with all members. The concerts were filmed for future release.\n\nOn August 4, 2018, Elliott again joined a \u2018Reunion Show\u2019 at the Buffalo Chip in Sturgis, SD were the current Foreigner group played one set and the Original members consisting of the Head Games-era lineup: Mick Jones, Lou Gramm, Dennis Elliott, Al Greenwood, Ian McDonald and Rick Wills played the second set & were rejoined at the end with all members.<ref>self</ref>\n\n==Discography==\n\n===The Shevells===\n*1968: ''[[Big City Lights /The Coffee Song ]] (single)''\n\n===The Ferris Wheel===\n*1970: ''Ferris Wheel'' (album)\n*1970: ''Can't Stop Now / I Know You Well'' (UK single)\n*1970: ''Ugly Duckling / I Know You Well'' (US single)\n\n===IF===\n*1970: ''[[If (If album)|If]]'' \n*1970: ''[[If 2]]''\n*1971: ''[[If 3]]'' \n*1972: ''[[If 4]]'' \n*1972: ''[[Waterfall (album)|Waterfall]]'' \n*1995: ''[[Forgotten Roads: The Best of If]]'' \n*1997: ''[[Europe '72 (Live)|Europe '72]]''\n*2010: ''[[Fibonacci's Number - More Live If]]''\n*2012: ''[[If 2 + Live in Liverpool]]''\n\n===The Roy Young Band===\n*1973: ''[[Back Up Train]] (single)'' \n*1973: ''Devil's Daughter (single)'' \n*1973: ''Dig A Hole (single)'' \n*1973: ''[[If You Could Only See Me Now]] (single)''\n*2009: ''The Best Of 50 years (album)''\n\n===Tony Ashton and Jon Lord===\n*1974: ''[[First of the Big Bands]]''\n\n===Ian Hunter===\n*1975: ''[[Ian Hunter (album)|Ian Hunter]]'' \n*1977: ''[[Overnight Angels]]''\n\n===Foreigner===\n*1977: ''[[Foreigner (Foreigner album)|Foreigner]]'' (#4 US)\n*1978: ''[[Double Vision (Foreigner album)|Double Vision]]'' (#3 US, #32 UK)\n*1979: ''[[Head Games (album)|Head Games]]'' (#5 US)\n*1981: ''[[4 (Foreigner album)|4]]'' (#1 US, #5 UK)\n*1982: ''[[Records (album)|Records]]'' (#10 US, #58 UK)\n*1984: ''[[Agent Provocateur (album)|Agent Provocateur]]'' (#4 US, #1 UK)\n*1987: ''[[Inside Information (album)|Inside Information]]'' (#15 US, #64 UK)\n*1991: ''[[Unusual Heat]]''\n*1992: ''[[The Very Best ... and Beyond]]'' (#123 US, #19 UK)\n*1993: ''[[Classic Hits Live/Best of Live|Classic Hits Live/Best Of Live]]''\n*1994: ''JukeBox Heroes: The Best Of''\n*1998: ''The Best of Ballads\u2013 I Want to Know What Love Is''\n*1999: ''The Platinum Collection''\n*2000: ''Hot Blooded And Other Hits''\n*2000: ''Jukebox Heroes: The Foreigner Anthology''\n*2002: ''[[Complete Greatest Hits (Foreigner album)|Complete Greatest Hits]]'' (#80 US)\n*2002: ''The Definitive'' (#33 UK)\n*2004: ''Hot Blooded And Other Hits''\n*2005: ''The Essentials'' \n*2008: ''[[No End in Sight: The Very Best of Foreigner]]'' (#132 US)\n*2009: ''[[Can't Slow Down (Foreigner album)|Can't Slow Down]]'' (#29 US)\n*2014: ''The Complete Atlantic Studio Albums 1977-1991''\n\n===Ian Lloyd===\n*1980: ''Third Wave Civilization''\n\n===Mick Jones===\n*1989: ''Just Wanna Hold (single)'' (#19 US Rock)\n*1989: ''[[Mick Jones (album)|Mick Jones]]'' (album)\n\n==Museum collections==\n*Arkansas Art Center, Decorative Arts Museum - Little Rock, Arkansas\n*Art Museum of South Texas, Corpus Christi, TX\n*The Charles A. Wustum Museum of Fine Arts - Racine, Wisconsin\n*Cincinnati Art Museum, Cincinnati, Ohio\n*The Contemporary Museum of Art - Honolulu, Hawaii\n*Craft & Folk Art Museum - Los Angeles, California\n*The Detroit Institute of Arts - Detroit, Michigan\n*Fuller Craft Museum - Brockton, Massachusetts\n*Honolulu Museum of Art, Honolulu, HI\n*Los Angeles County Museum of Art - Los Angeles, California\n*The Mabel Brady Garven Collection, Yale University Art Gallery - New Haven, Connecticut\n*The Mint Museum of Craft & Design - Charlotte, North Carolina\n*Mobile Museum of Art, (formerly, Fine Arts Museum of the South) - Mobile, Alabama\n*Museum of Arts & Design, formerly The American Craft Museum - New York, New York\n*Museum of Fine Arts - Boston, Massachusetts\n*Peabody Essex Museum, Salem, Massachusetts\n*Racine Art Museum, Racine, Wisconsin\n*Renwick Gallery of the Smithsonian American Art Museum - Washington, D.C.\n*The Slater Museum - Norwich, Connecticut\n*University of Michigan Museum - Ann Arbor, Michigan\n\n==Special collections==\n*Columbia Pictures, Star Trek Voyager set - Wall Sculpture - Bleached Maple Burl\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.denniselliott.com Dennis Elliott's official website]\n*[http://www.askart.com/askart/e/dennis_elliott/dennis_elliott.aspx Askart.com \u2013 reference site for Elliott's sculptures]\n\n{{Foreigner}}\n{{If (band)}}\n{{Spooky Tooth}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Elliott, Dennis}}\n[[Category:1950 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English rock drummers]]\n[[Category:Foreigner (band) members]]\n[[Category:People from Peckham]]\n[[Category:English sculptors]]\n[[Category:Place of birth missing (living people)]]\n[[Category:If (band) members]]\n[[Category:Spooky Tooth members]]\n", "name_user": "188.141.87.103", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dennis_Elliott"}
{"title_page": "Ian McDonald (musician)", "text_new": "{{distinguish|text=Iain Matthew McDonald (another English musician born June 1946), professionally known as [[Iain Matthews]]}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{one source|date=November 2011}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name                = Ian McDonald \n| image               = Ian McDonald (2009).jpg\n| caption             = McDonald in 2009\n| image_size          = \n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist \n| birth_name          = \n| alias               = \n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1946|6|25}}\n| birth_place         = [[Osterley]], [[Middlesex]], [[England]]\n| origin              = [[Chiswick]], Middlesex, England\n| instrument          = Saxophone, flute, keyboards, guitar <!--- If you think an instrument should be listed, a discussion to reach consensus is needed first per: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Infobox_musical_artist#instrument--->\n| genre               = [[Rock music|Rock]], [[progressive rock]], [[jazz fusion]], [[hard rock]]\n| occupation          = {{hlist|Musician|producer|songwriter}}\n| years_active        = 1968\u2013present \n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = [[King Crimson]]<br />[[Foreigner (band)|Foreigner]]\n| website             = [http://www.allmusic.com/artist/ian-mcdonald-p103833/biography/ allmusic.com/ian mcdonald] \n}}\n\n'''Ian McDonald''' (born 25 June 1946 from [[Osterley]], [[Middlesex]]) is an English [[multi-instrumentalist|multi-instrumental]] musician, best known as a founding member of [[progressive rock]] band [[King Crimson]], formed in 1969, and of the [[hard rock]] band [[Foreigner (band)|Foreigner]] in 1976. He is well known as a rock [[session musician]], predominantly as a saxophonist. He also plays keyboards, flute, [[vibraphone]] and guitar.\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in [[Osterley]], [[Middlesex]], McDonald served five years in the [[British Army]] as a bandsman. His music talent ranged from [[European classical music|classical]] orchestra to dance bands to [[rock and roll|rock]]. In 1969, he was in [[King Crimson]]'s initial line up, which recorded their first album ''[[In the Court of the Crimson King]]''. McDonald and drummer [[Michael Giles]] departed and formed a spin-off group that released one album titled ''[[McDonald and Giles]]''. He reappeared in King Crimson in 1974 and intended to rejoin the band as a full member but did not get the opportunity to do so given Fripp's decision to split the band.\n\nHe became a founding member of the band [[Foreigner (band)|Foreigner]] in 1976, for whom he played guitar as well as his woodwinds and keyboards.<ref name=\"NME Rock 'N' Roll Years\">{{cite book\n| first= John\n| last= Tobler\n| year= 1992\n| title= NME Rock 'N' Roll Years\n| edition= 1st\n| publisher= Reed International Books Ltd \n| location= London\n| page= 318\n| id= CN 5585}}</ref> He has been a session musician and appeared in the recording of the hit single \"[[Get It On (T. Rex song)|Get It On (Bang a Gong)]]\" by [[T. Rex (band)|T. Rex]], and recordings by Linda Lewis, Christine Harwood amongst others. He also has some production credits to his name, including albums by [[Fruupp]], Darryl Way's Wolf and Fireballet. In 1999, he released a solo album, ''Drivers Eyes''.\n\nIn 1997, the release of the King Crimson four CD set ''[[Epitaph (King Crimson album)|Epitaph]]'', consisting of rare live recordings of the 1969 version of King Crimson, renewed interest in the early Crimson material. Out of that interest, the [[21st Century Schizoid Band]] was formed in 2002 and several tours and live albums have followed. The band included former King Crimson members Michael Giles (drums and percussion), [[Peter Giles (musician)|Peter Giles]] (bass), McDonald (sax, flute, keyboards), [[Mel Collins]] (alto/tenor sax, flute, keyboards) and also [[Jakko Jakszyk]], who later joined King Crimson, on guitar and lead vocals. After the first tour Michael Giles was replaced with another former King Crimson drummer [[Ian Wallace (drummer)|Ian Wallace]], who has since died.\n\nMcDonald has contributed saxophone and flute to several tracks on [[Judy Dyble]]'s 2009 release, [[Talking With Strangers]]. The album sees McDonald reunited with former [[King Crimson]] bandmate [[Robert Fripp]] on the 20-minute \"Harpsong\".\n\nOn 28 July 2009, McDonald made a guest appearance with [[Asia (band)|Asia]] during their opening set for [[Yes (band)|Yes]] at the [[Tower Theater (Upper Darby, Pennsylvania)|Tower Theater]] in [[Upper Darby Township, Delaware County, Pennsylvania|Upper Darby]], Pennsylvania, just outside of [[Philadelphia]]. McDonald played flute, clarinet, saxophone and sang backing vocals for \"In the Court of the Crimson King\" and also returned for the encore to sing backing vocals for \"Heat of the Moment\". His guest appearance on \"In the Court of the Crimson King\" is featured as a bonus track on Asia's 2011 DVD release, \"Spirit of the Night: Live\".\n\nOn 14 May 2010 (Sherman Theatre, Stroudsburg, Pennsylvania) and 15 May 2010 (Trump Taj Mahal Casino Resort, Atlantic City, New Jersey), Ian made guest appearances during \"An Intimate Evening with Keith Emerson and Greg Lake\". Played flute and shared lead vocals/vocal harmonies with Greg Lake on \"I Talk to the Wind\" while playing solo flute on \"Lucky Man\". For these two songs, it was \"Emerson, Lake & McDonald\".\n\nIn 2010, Ian provided alto sax, flute and percussion textures to ''Beautiful Accident'', the debut album by progressive blues band, Third International. One track, \"Penitentiary\" was co-written by Ian with Third International frontman, Andrew Pearson.\n\nIn 2011, McDonald began working with long-time neighbour Lynnea Benson and her husband Ted Zurkowski, directors of New York City's Frog and Peach Theatre Company, which specialises in off-Broadway productions and readings of Shakespearean plays. In collaboration with Zurkowski, McDonald composed and performed guitar and piano music to accompany select Frog and Peach Shakespearean productions and readings: ''Julius Caesar'', ''Two Gentleman of Verona'', ''Hamlet'', ''A Midsummer Nights Dream'', ''King Lear'', ''The Taming of the Shrew'' and ''Measure for Measure''. In addition, Ian became involved with Zurkowski' band, Honey West, the self-described \"US/UK Indie Rock Country Fusion Invasion\" band where he is providing lead guitar, flute, sax, keyboards and background vocals to their current NYC live performances and to their second album, \"Bad Old World,\" released in May 2017.\n\n==Discography==\n\n===With Giles, Giles and Fripp===\n* ''[[The Cheerful Insanity of Giles, Giles and Fripp]]'' (1968) (1992 CD reissue has bonus track, \"Under The Sky,\" which Ian McDonald  played acoustic guitar/flute, sang vocals and co-wrote with Peter Sinfield)\n* ''The Brondesbury Tapes'' (1968 demo recordings, released 2001) (Ian McDonald contributed clarinet, flute, guitar, saxophone and vocals)\n* ''Metamorphosis'' (2001) (Edited in vinyl only)\n\n===With King Crimson===\n* ''[[In the Court of the Crimson King]]'' (#28 US, #5 UK) (1969)\n* ''[[Red (King Crimson album)|Red]]'' (#66 US, #45 UK)  (1974) (Ian McDonald played alto saxophone as a guest instrumentalist)\n* ''[[A Young Person's Guide to King Crimson]]'' (1976)\n* ''[[The Compact King Crimson]]'' (1986)\n* ''[[Heartbeat: The Abbreviated King Crimson]]'' (1991)\n* ''[[Frame by Frame: The Essential King Crimson]]'' (1991)\n* ''[[Sleepless: The Concise King Crimson]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[Epitaph (King Crimson album)|Epitaph]]'' (1969 live recording) (1997) \n* ''[[Live at the Marquee (King Crimson album)|Live at the Marquee]]'' (1969 live recording) (1998)\n* ''[[Cirkus: The Young Persons' Guide to King Crimson Live]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[The Beginners' Guide to the King Crimson Collectors' Club]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[King Crimson Live in Hyde Park, London|Live in Hyde Park]]'' (1969 live recording) (2000)\n* ''[[Live at Fillmore East (King Crimson album)|Live at Fillmore East]]'' (1969 live recording) (2004)\n* ''[[The 21st Century Guide to King Crimson - Volume One - 1969\u20131974]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[The Condensed 21st Century Guide to King Crimson]]'' (2006)\n* ''40th Anniversary Tour Box'' (2008)\n* ''[[The Elements of King Crimson]]'' (2014)\n\nAdditionally, McDonald is credited as co-composer of \"Cat Food\" and \"The Devil's Triangle\" from ''[[In the Wake of Poseidon]]'', even though he didn't play on the album.\n\n===With McDonald and Giles===\n* ''[[McDonald and Giles]]'' (1971)\n\n===With Foreigner===\n* ''[[Foreigner (Foreigner album)|Foreigner]]'' (#4 US) (1977)\n* ''[[Double Vision (Foreigner album)|Double Vision]]'' (#3 US, #32 UK) (1978)\n* ''[[Head Games (album)|Head Games]]'' (#5 US) (1979)\n* ''[[Records (album)|Records]]'' (#10 US, #58 UK) (1982)\n* ''[[The Very Best ... and Beyond]]'' (#123 US, #19 UK) (1992)\n* ''[[Classic Hits Live/Best of Live|Classic Hits Live/Best Of Live]]'' (1993)\n* ''JukeBox Heroes: The Best Of'' (1994)\n* ''The Best of Ballads\u2013 I Want to Know What Love Is'' (1998)\n* ''The Platinum Collection'' (1999)\n* ''Hot Blooded And Other Hits'' (2000)\n* ''Jukebox Heroes: The Foreigner Anthology'' (2000)\n* ''[[Complete Greatest Hits (Foreigner album)|Complete Greatest Hits]]'' (#80 US) (2002)\n* ''The Definitive'' (#33 UK) (2002)\n* ''Hot Blooded And Other Hits'' (2004)\n* ''The Essentials'' (2005)\n* ''[[The Definitive Collection (Foreigner album)|The Definitive Collection]]'' (2006)\n* ''The Very Best of Toto & Foreigner'' (2007)\n* ''[[No End in Sight: The Very Best of Foreigner]]'' (#132 US) (2008)\n* ''[[Can't Slow Down (Foreigner album)|Can't Slow Down]]'' (#29 US) (2009)\n* ''The Complete Atlantic Studio Albums 1977-1991'' (2014)\n\n===With Ian Lloyd===\n* ''Ian Lloyd'' (1976) \n* ''3WC (Third Wave Civilization)'' (1980) (co-producer for one song, \"Trouble\")\n\n===With Steve Hackett===\n* ''[[Genesis Revisited]]'' (1997)\n* ''[[The Tokyo Tapes]]'' (1998)\n* ''[[Darktown (album)|Darktown]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[To Watch the Storms|To Watch The Storms]]'' (2003)\n\n===With John Wetton===\n* ''Hazy Monet Live In New York City May 27, 1997'' (1999)\n* ''[[Welcome to Heaven (album)|Welcome to Heaven]]'' / ''[[Sinister (album)|Sinister]]'' (2000)\n\n===Solo album===\n* ''Drivers Eyes'' (1999)\n\n===With 21st Century Schizoid Band===\n* ''[[Official Bootleg V.1]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[Live in Japan (21st Century Schizoid Band album)|Live in Japan]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Live in Japan (21st Century Schizoid Band album)|Live in Japan]]'' (2003) (DVD)\n* ''[[Live in Italy (21st Century Schizoid Band album)|Live in Italy]]'' (2003)\n* ''Pictures of a City \u2013 Live in New York'' (2006)\n\n===With Honey West===\n* ''Bad Old World'' (released on 19 May 2017)\n\n===As producer or guest instrumentalist===\n* Christine Harwood ''Nice To Meet Miss Christine'' (1970) (guest instrumentalist)\n* [[Centipede (band)|Centipede]] ''[[Septober Energy]]'' (1971) (guest instrumentalist)\n* [[Linda Lewis]] ''[[Say No More (Linda Lewis album)|Say No More]]'' (1971) (guest instrumentalist)\n* [[T. Rex (band)|T. Rex]] ''[[Electric Warrior]]'' (#32 US, #1 UK) (1971) (guest instrumentalist)\n* [[Silverhead]] ''Sixteen and Savaged'' (1973) (guest instrumentalist)\n* [[Herbie Mann]] ''[[London Underground (album)|London Underground]]'' (1973) (guest instrumentalist)\n* Darryl Way's Wolf ''Canis Lupus'' (1973) (producer and guest instrumentalist)\n* [[Keith Christmas]] ''Brighter Day'' (1974) (guest instrumentalist)\n* [[Fruupp]] ''[[Modern Masquerades]]'' (1975) (producer and guest instrumentalist)\n* Fireballet ''Night on Bald Mountain'' (1975) (producer and guest instrumentalist)\n* [[Ian Lloyd (musician)|Ian Lloyd]] ''Ian Lloyd'' (1976) (guest instrumentalist)\n* [[Steve Taylor]] ''[[On the Fritz]]'' (1985) (co-producer and guest instrumentalist)\n* Jesse Taylor Is Dead ''Jesse Taylor Is Dead'' (1996) (guest instrumentalist)\n* Various Artists ''To Cry You a Song: A Collection of Tull Tales'' (1996) ([[Jethro Tull (band)|Jethro Tull]] tribute album) (guest instrumentalist)\n* Nari Matsuura ''Pianist'' (1997) (co-producer)\n* The Wallace/Trainor Conspiracy'' Take A Train'' (1998) (guest instrumentalist)\n* Park Stickney ''Action Harp Play Set'' (2000) (producer and guest instrumentalist)\n* Waking in the Blue ''Isn't It Pretty to Think So'' (2003) (guest instrumentalist)\n* [[Ian Wallace (drummer)|Ian Wallace]] ''Happiness With Minimal Side Effects'' (2003) (guest instrumentalist)\n* Unu ''Pangaea'' (2004) (guest instrumentalist)\n* [[John Wetton|Wetton]]/[[Geoffrey Downes|Downes]] ''[[Icon (Wetton and Downes album)|Icon]]'' (2006) (guest instrumentalist)\n* [[Jakko Jakszyk]] ''The Bruised Romantic Glee Club'' (2006) (guest instrumentalist)\n* [[Judy Dyble]] ''[[Talking With Strangers]]'' (2009) (guest instrumentalist)\n* [[Vince Martell]] ''Endless High'' (2009) (guest instrumentalist)\n* Third International ''Beautiful Accident'' (2010) (guest instrumentalist)\n* [[Asia (band)|Asia]] ''Spirit of the Night: Live''  (2011) (guest instrumentalist)\n\n===As soundtrack composer===\n* ''Success Stories with Bruce Jenner'' (1987) (Nationally Syndicated CBS Television Show)\n* ''[[Wachenr\u00f6der]]'' (1998) ([[Sega Saturn]] [[video game]])\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n* [http://www.leninimports.com/kingcrimson_bio.html King Crimson Biography]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20110428181026/http://www.gramy.com/eloadok/ianmcdonald_eng.html Gramy Records \u2013 Ian McDonald]\n\n==External links==\n* [https://sociallysparkednews.com/every-day-fathers-day-rock-icon-ian-mcdonald/ Every Day Is Father's Day For Rock Icon Ian McDonald]\n* [https://parade.com/577633/nancyberk/dads-who-literally-rock-ian-and-maxwell-mcdonald-share-the-stage/ Dad Who Literally Rock: Ian And Maxwell McDonald Share The Stage]\n* [http://wwdbam.com/episodes/thats-show-biz-052317/ Chuck Darrow Radio Interview With Ian McDonald, 23 May 2017]\n* [http://www.rbeatz.com/podcasts/legends-land-in-honey-west/ Legends Land In Honey West]\n* [http://www.billboard.com/articles/columns/rock/7785154/ian-mcdonald-dementia-honey-west-exclusive Ian McDonald Dementia Honey West Exclusive]\n* [http://www.vintagerock.com/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=1309:the-ian-mcdonald-interview&catid=3:interviews&Itemid=4 The Ian McDonald Interview (2012)]\n* [http://frogandpeachtheatre.org/ The Official Frog and Peach Theatre Company Website]\n* [http://thethirdinternational.com/ The Official Third International Website]\n* [http://www.elephant-talk.com/wiki/Interview_with_Ian_McDonald_in_Big_Bang_Magazine Interview with Ian McDonald in Big Bang Magazine]\n* [http://www.artist-shop.com/irc/mcdon2.htm The Artist Shop IRC Chat with Ian McDonald on Wednesday, 27 October 1999]\n* [http://www.artist-shop.com/irc/mcdonald.htm The Artist Shop/Talk City chat with King Crimson founding member Ian McDonald on Sunday, 3 May 1998]\n\n{{King Crimson}}\n{{Foreigner}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:McDonald, Ian}}\n[[Category:1946 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:English rock saxophonists]]\n[[Category:British male saxophonists]]\n[[Category:English multi-instrumentalists]]\n[[Category:King Crimson members]]\n[[Category:Foreigner (band) members]]\n[[Category:People from Osterley]]\n[[Category:English session musicians]]\n[[Category:Centipede (band) members]]\n[[Category:21st-century saxophonists]]\n[[Category:21st Century Schizoid Band members]]\n", "text_old": "{{distinguish|text=Iain Matthew McDonald (another English musician born June 1946), professionally known as [[Iain Matthews]]}}\n{{EngvarB|date=August 2014}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=August 2014}}\n{{one source|date=November 2011}}\n{{Infobox musical artist <!-- See Wikipedia:WikiProject_Musicians -->\n| name                = Ian McDonald \n| image               = Ian McDonald (2009).jpg\n| caption             = McDonald in 2009\n| image_size          = \n| background          = non_vocal_instrumentalist \n| birth_name          = \n| alias               = \n| birth_date          = {{Birth date and age|df=yes|1946|6|25}}\n| birth_place         = [[Osterley]], [[Middlesex]], [[England]]\n| origin              = [[Chiswick]], Middlesex, England\n| instrument          = Saxophone, flute, keyboards, guitar <!--- If you think an instrument should be listed, a discussion to reach consensus is needed first per: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Template:Infobox_musical_artist#instrument--->\n| genre               = [[Rock music|Rock]], [[progressive rock]], [[jazz fusion]], [[hard rock]]\n| occupation          = {{hlist|Musician|producer|songwriter}}\n| years_active        = 1968\u2013present \n| label               = \n| associated_acts     = [[King Crimson]]<br />[[Foreigner (band)|Foreigner]]<br/>[[Spooky Tooth]] \n| website             = [http://www.allmusic.com/artist/ian-mcdonald-p103833/biography/ allmusic.com/ian mcdonald] \n}}\n\n'''Ian McDonald''' (born 25 June 1946 from [[Osterley]], [[Middlesex]]) is an English [[multi-instrumentalist|multi-instrumental]] musician, best known as a founding member of [[progressive rock]] band [[King Crimson]], formed in 1969, and of the [[hard rock]] band [[Foreigner (band)|Foreigner]] in 1976. He is well known as a rock [[session musician]], predominantly as a saxophonist. He also plays keyboards, flute, [[vibraphone]] and guitar.\n\n==Biography==\nBorn in [[Osterley]], [[Middlesex]], McDonald served five years in the [[British Army]] as a bandsman. His music talent ranged from [[European classical music|classical]] orchestra to dance bands to [[rock and roll|rock]]. In 1969, he was in [[King Crimson]]'s initial line up, which recorded their first album ''[[In the Court of the Crimson King]]''. McDonald and drummer [[Michael Giles]] departed and formed a spin-off group that released one album titled ''[[McDonald and Giles]]''. He reappeared in King Crimson in 1974 and intended to rejoin the band as a full member but did not get the opportunity to do so given Fripp's decision to split the band.\n\nHe became a founding member of the band [[Foreigner (band)|Foreigner]] in 1976, for whom he played guitar as well as his woodwinds and keyboards.<ref name=\"NME Rock 'N' Roll Years\">{{cite book\n| first= John\n| last= Tobler\n| year= 1992\n| title= NME Rock 'N' Roll Years\n| edition= 1st\n| publisher= Reed International Books Ltd \n| location= London\n| page= 318\n| id= CN 5585}}</ref> He has been a session musician and appeared in the recording of the hit single \"[[Get It On (T. Rex song)|Get It On (Bang a Gong)]]\" by [[T. Rex (band)|T. Rex]], and recordings by Linda Lewis, Christine Harwood amongst others. He also has some production credits to his name, including albums by [[Fruupp]], Darryl Way's Wolf and Fireballet. In 1999, he released a solo album, ''Drivers Eyes''.\n\nIn 1997, the release of the King Crimson four CD set ''[[Epitaph (King Crimson album)|Epitaph]]'', consisting of rare live recordings of the 1969 version of King Crimson, renewed interest in the early Crimson material. Out of that interest, the [[21st Century Schizoid Band]] was formed in 2002 and several tours and live albums have followed. The band included former King Crimson members Michael Giles (drums and percussion), [[Peter Giles (musician)|Peter Giles]] (bass), McDonald (sax, flute, keyboards), [[Mel Collins]] (alto/tenor sax, flute, keyboards) and also [[Jakko Jakszyk]], who later joined King Crimson, on guitar and lead vocals. After the first tour Michael Giles was replaced with another former King Crimson drummer [[Ian Wallace (drummer)|Ian Wallace]], who has since died.\n\nMcDonald has contributed saxophone and flute to several tracks on [[Judy Dyble]]'s 2009 release, [[Talking With Strangers]]. The album sees McDonald reunited with former [[King Crimson]] bandmate [[Robert Fripp]] on the 20-minute \"Harpsong\".\n\nOn 28 July 2009, McDonald made a guest appearance with [[Asia (band)|Asia]] during their opening set for [[Yes (band)|Yes]] at the [[Tower Theater (Upper Darby, Pennsylvania)|Tower Theater]] in [[Upper Darby Township, Delaware County, Pennsylvania|Upper Darby]], Pennsylvania, just outside of [[Philadelphia]]. McDonald played flute, clarinet, saxophone and sang backing vocals for \"In the Court of the Crimson King\" and also returned for the encore to sing backing vocals for \"Heat of the Moment\". His guest appearance on \"In the Court of the Crimson King\" is featured as a bonus track on Asia's 2011 DVD release, \"Spirit of the Night: Live\".\n\nOn 14 May 2010 (Sherman Theatre, Stroudsburg, Pennsylvania) and 15 May 2010 (Trump Taj Mahal Casino Resort, Atlantic City, New Jersey), Ian made guest appearances during \"An Intimate Evening with Keith Emerson and Greg Lake\". Played flute and shared lead vocals/vocal harmonies with Greg Lake on \"I Talk to the Wind\" while playing solo flute on \"Lucky Man\". For these two songs, it was \"Emerson, Lake & McDonald\".\n\nIn 2010, Ian provided alto sax, flute and percussion textures to ''Beautiful Accident'', the debut album by progressive blues band, Third International. One track, \"Penitentiary\" was co-written by Ian with Third International frontman, Andrew Pearson.\n\nIn 2011, McDonald began working with long-time neighbour Lynnea Benson and her husband Ted Zurkowski, directors of New York City's Frog and Peach Theatre Company, which specialises in off-Broadway productions and readings of Shakespearean plays. In collaboration with Zurkowski, McDonald composed and performed guitar and piano music to accompany select Frog and Peach Shakespearean productions and readings: ''Julius Caesar'', ''Two Gentleman of Verona'', ''Hamlet'', ''A Midsummer Nights Dream'', ''King Lear'', ''The Taming of the Shrew'' and ''Measure for Measure''. In addition, Ian became involved with Zurkowski' band, Honey West, the self-described \"US/UK Indie Rock Country Fusion Invasion\" band where he is providing lead guitar, flute, sax, keyboards and background vocals to their current NYC live performances and to their second album, \"Bad Old World,\" released in May 2017.\n\n==Discography==\n\n===With Giles, Giles and Fripp===\n* ''[[The Cheerful Insanity of Giles, Giles and Fripp]]'' (1968) (1992 CD reissue has bonus track, \"Under The Sky,\" which Ian McDonald  played acoustic guitar/flute, sang vocals and co-wrote with Peter Sinfield)\n* ''The Brondesbury Tapes'' (1968 demo recordings, released 2001) (Ian McDonald contributed clarinet, flute, guitar, saxophone and vocals)\n* ''Metamorphosis'' (2001) (Edited in vinyl only)\n\n===With King Crimson===\n* ''[[In the Court of the Crimson King]]'' (#28 US, #5 UK) (1969)\n* ''[[Red (King Crimson album)|Red]]'' (#66 US, #45 UK)  (1974) (Ian McDonald played alto saxophone as a guest instrumentalist)\n* ''[[A Young Person's Guide to King Crimson]]'' (1976)\n* ''[[The Compact King Crimson]]'' (1986)\n* ''[[Heartbeat: The Abbreviated King Crimson]]'' (1991)\n* ''[[Frame by Frame: The Essential King Crimson]]'' (1991)\n* ''[[Sleepless: The Concise King Crimson]]'' (1993)\n* ''[[Epitaph (King Crimson album)|Epitaph]]'' (1969 live recording) (1997) \n* ''[[Live at the Marquee (King Crimson album)|Live at the Marquee]]'' (1969 live recording) (1998)\n* ''[[Cirkus: The Young Persons' Guide to King Crimson Live]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[The Beginners' Guide to the King Crimson Collectors' Club]]'' (2000)\n* ''[[King Crimson Live in Hyde Park, London|Live in Hyde Park]]'' (1969 live recording) (2000)\n* ''[[Live at Fillmore East (King Crimson album)|Live at Fillmore East]]'' (1969 live recording) (2004)\n* ''[[The 21st Century Guide to King Crimson - Volume One - 1969\u20131974]]'' (2004)\n* ''[[The Condensed 21st Century Guide to King Crimson]]'' (2006)\n* ''40th Anniversary Tour Box'' (2008)\n* ''[[The Elements of King Crimson]]'' (2014)\n\nAdditionally, McDonald is credited as co-composer of \"Cat Food\" and \"The Devil's Triangle\" from ''[[In the Wake of Poseidon]]'', even though he didn't play on the album.\n\n===With McDonald and Giles===\n* ''[[McDonald and Giles]]'' (1971)\n\n===With Foreigner===\n* ''[[Foreigner (Foreigner album)|Foreigner]]'' (#4 US) (1977)\n* ''[[Double Vision (Foreigner album)|Double Vision]]'' (#3 US, #32 UK) (1978)\n* ''[[Head Games (album)|Head Games]]'' (#5 US) (1979)\n* ''[[Records (album)|Records]]'' (#10 US, #58 UK) (1982)\n* ''[[The Very Best ... and Beyond]]'' (#123 US, #19 UK) (1992)\n* ''[[Classic Hits Live/Best of Live|Classic Hits Live/Best Of Live]]'' (1993)\n* ''JukeBox Heroes: The Best Of'' (1994)\n* ''The Best of Ballads\u2013 I Want to Know What Love Is'' (1998)\n* ''The Platinum Collection'' (1999)\n* ''Hot Blooded And Other Hits'' (2000)\n* ''Jukebox Heroes: The Foreigner Anthology'' (2000)\n* ''[[Complete Greatest Hits (Foreigner album)|Complete Greatest Hits]]'' (#80 US) (2002)\n* ''The Definitive'' (#33 UK) (2002)\n* ''Hot Blooded And Other Hits'' (2004)\n* ''The Essentials'' (2005)\n* ''[[The Definitive Collection (Foreigner album)|The Definitive Collection]]'' (2006)\n* ''The Very Best of Toto & Foreigner'' (2007)\n* ''[[No End in Sight: The Very Best of Foreigner]]'' (#132 US) (2008)\n* ''[[Can't Slow Down (Foreigner album)|Can't Slow Down]]'' (#29 US) (2009)\n* ''The Complete Atlantic Studio Albums 1977-1991'' (2014)\n\n===With Ian Lloyd===\n* ''Ian Lloyd'' (1976) \n* ''3WC (Third Wave Civilization)'' (1980) (co-producer for one song, \"Trouble\")\n\n===With Steve Hackett===\n* ''[[Genesis Revisited]]'' (1997)\n* ''[[The Tokyo Tapes]]'' (1998)\n* ''[[Darktown (album)|Darktown]]'' (1999)\n* ''[[To Watch the Storms|To Watch The Storms]]'' (2003)\n\n===With John Wetton===\n* ''Hazy Monet Live In New York City May 27, 1997'' (1999)\n* ''[[Welcome to Heaven (album)|Welcome to Heaven]]'' / ''[[Sinister (album)|Sinister]]'' (2000)\n\n===Solo album===\n* ''Drivers Eyes'' (1999)\n\n===With 21st Century Schizoid Band===\n* ''[[Official Bootleg V.1]]'' (2002)\n* ''[[Live in Japan (21st Century Schizoid Band album)|Live in Japan]]'' (2003)\n* ''[[Live in Japan (21st Century Schizoid Band album)|Live in Japan]]'' (2003) (DVD)\n* ''[[Live in Italy (21st Century Schizoid Band album)|Live in Italy]]'' (2003)\n* ''Pictures of a City \u2013 Live in New York'' (2006)\n\n===With Honey West===\n* ''Bad Old World'' (released on 19 May 2017)\n\n===As producer or guest instrumentalist===\n* Christine Harwood ''Nice To Meet Miss Christine'' (1970) (guest instrumentalist)\n* [[Centipede (band)|Centipede]] ''[[Septober Energy]]'' (1971) (guest instrumentalist)\n* [[Linda Lewis]] ''[[Say No More (Linda Lewis album)|Say No More]]'' (1971) (guest instrumentalist)\n* [[T. Rex (band)|T. Rex]] ''[[Electric Warrior]]'' (#32 US, #1 UK) (1971) (guest instrumentalist)\n* [[Silverhead]] ''Sixteen and Savaged'' (1973) (guest instrumentalist)\n* [[Herbie Mann]] ''[[London Underground (album)|London Underground]]'' (1973) (guest instrumentalist)\n* Darryl Way's Wolf ''Canis Lupus'' (1973) (producer and guest instrumentalist)\n* [[Keith Christmas]] ''Brighter Day'' (1974) (guest instrumentalist)\n* [[Fruupp]] ''[[Modern Masquerades]]'' (1975) (producer and guest instrumentalist)\n* Fireballet ''Night on Bald Mountain'' (1975) (producer and guest instrumentalist)\n* [[Ian Lloyd (musician)|Ian Lloyd]] ''Ian Lloyd'' (1976) (guest instrumentalist)\n* [[Steve Taylor]] ''[[On the Fritz]]'' (1985) (co-producer and guest instrumentalist)\n* Jesse Taylor Is Dead ''Jesse Taylor Is Dead'' (1996) (guest instrumentalist)\n* Various Artists ''To Cry You a Song: A Collection of Tull Tales'' (1996) ([[Jethro Tull (band)|Jethro Tull]] tribute album) (guest instrumentalist)\n* Nari Matsuura ''Pianist'' (1997) (co-producer)\n* The Wallace/Trainor Conspiracy'' Take A Train'' (1998) (guest instrumentalist)\n* Park Stickney ''Action Harp Play Set'' (2000) (producer and guest instru