enter\" | 3\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | -3\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 0\n|- ALIGN=\"center\"\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | [[2008 NFL season|2008]]\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | [[Tennessee Titans|TEN]]\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 16\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 242\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 415\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 58.3\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 2,676\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 12\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 7\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 80.2\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 25\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 49\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 0\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" \n| ALIGN=\"center\" | [[2009 NFL season|2009]]\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | [[Tennessee Titans|TEN]]\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 7\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 119\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 216\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 55.1\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 1,225\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 6\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 8\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 65.5\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 11\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 15\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 1\n|- ALIGN=\"center\"\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | [[2010 NFL season|2010]]\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | [[Tennessee Titans|TEN]]\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 10\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 160\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 278\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 57.6\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 1,823\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 14\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 8\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 82.2\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 10\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 1\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 0\n|- ALIGN=\"center\"\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | [[2011 NFL season|2011]]\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | [[Indianapolis Colts|IND]]\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 3\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 48\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 98\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 49.0\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 481\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 2\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 1\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 65.9\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 2\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | -1\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 0\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! colspan=\"2\" | NFL totals\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | 198\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | 3,487\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | 6,261\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | 55.7\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | 40,922\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | 208\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | 196\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | '''73.8'''\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | 374\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | 686\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | 10\n|}\n\n===Playoffs===\n{| BORDER=\"0\" CELLPADDING=\"3\" CELLSPACING=\"0\" ID=\"Table3\"\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! ALIGN=\"center\" colspan=\"3\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" | &nbsp;\n! ALIGN=\"center\" rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" | &nbsp;\n! ALIGN=\"center\" colspan=\"7\" | Passing\n! ALIGN=\"center\" rowspan=\"99\" bgcolor=\"#ffffff\" | &nbsp;\n! ALIGN=\"center\" colspan=\"3\" | Rushing\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | Season\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | Team\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | League\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | GP\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | Comp\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | Att\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | Pct\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | Yds\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | TD\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | INT\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | Att\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | Yds\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | TD\n|- ALIGN=\"center\"\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | [[NFL playoffs, 1996-97|1996]]\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | CAR\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | NFL\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 2\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 31\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 59\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 52.5\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 315\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 3\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 3\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 7\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 4\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 0\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | [[NFL playoffs, 2000-01|2000]]\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | NYG\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | NFL\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 3\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 56\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 98\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 57.1\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 622\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 5\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 6\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 14\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 26\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 0\n|- ALIGN=\"center\"\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | [[NFL playoffs, 2002-03|2002]]\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | NYG\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | NFL\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 1\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 29\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 43\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 67.4\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 342\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 4\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 1\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 0\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 0\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 0\n|- ALIGN=\"center\"  bgcolor=\"#f0f0f0\"\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | [[NFL playoffs, 2008-09|2008]]\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | TEN\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | NFL\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 1\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 29\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 42\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 61.9\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 281\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 0\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 1\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 1\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 0\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 0\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" bgcolor=\"#e0e0e0\"\n! colspan=\"3\" | Playoff totals\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | 7\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | 145\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | 242\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | 59.7\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | 1,560\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | 12\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | 11\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | 22\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | 30\n! ALIGN=\"center\" | 0\n|}\n\n==Major League Baseball Draft==\n\nCollins was drafted by the [[Detroit Tigers]] in the 26th round of the 1990 MLB draft, but opted to attend Penn State. Detroit selected him in the 60th round of the 1991 amateur draft, but he did not sign with the club. He was again selected in the 48th round of the 1994 amateur draft by the Toronto Blue Jays but again did not sign.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kerry Collins \u2013 BR Bullpen|url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/bullpen/Kerry_Collins|website=baseball-reference.com|accessdate=June 12, 2014}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n\n===Battles with alcoholism===\nBefore the 1997 season got underway, Collins's private battle with [[alcoholism]] started to make public headlines.  In a highly publicized incident, on the last night of [[Carolina Panthers]] training camp in 1997, Collins used the racial slur \"[[nigger]]\" in reference to [[African-American|black]] teammate [[Muhsin Muhammad]] while in a drunken state at a bar in [[Spartanburg, South Carolina]]. Supposedly, Collins also inadvertently slurred offensive lineman [[Norberto Garrido]], who is of [[Hispanic]] descent. It was widely rumored that Garrido punched Collins in the eye as a result, although this was later proven false.<ref name=\"Panthers' Collins Finds Himself Tangled Up in Racial Barbs\">{{cite news | title = Panthers' Collins Finds Himself Tangled Up in Racial Barbs | first = Mike | last = Freeman | url = https://www.nytimes.com/1997/08/24/sports/panthers-collins-finds-himself-tangled-up-in-racial-barbs.html | newspaper = New York Times | date = August 24, 1997 | accessdate = October 3, 2009}}</ref>\n\nOn November 2, 1998, Collins was arrested for drunk driving in [[Charlotte, North Carolina]].<ref>{{cite news | title = Collins' DWI Case On Hold | url = https://www.cbsnews.com/news/collins-dwi-case-on-hold/ | website = CBS News | date = February 15, 1999 | accessdate = December 20, 2019}}</ref> He finished the 1998 season in New Orleans and signed with the [[New York Giants]] as a free agent on February 19, 1999.<ref>{{cite news | title = Giants Sign QB Kerry Collins | url = https://www.cbsnews.com/news/giants-sign-qb-kerry-collins/ | website = CBS News | date = February 19, 1999 | accessdate = December 20, 2019}}</ref>  Not long before signing with New York, Collins decided to seek treatment for his alcoholism. He entered a rehabilitation clinic in [[Topeka, Kansas]].<ref>{{cite news | title = Uncorked: Kerry Collins Couldn't Release His Bottled Up Talent Until He Let Go of Alcohol | first = Mark | last = Gaughan | url = https://buffalonews.com/2001/01/26/uncorked-kerry-collins-couldnt-release-his-bottled-up-talent-until-he-let-go-of-alcohol/ | newspaper = The Buffalo News | date = January 26, 2001 | accessdate = December 20, 2019}}</ref>\n[[File:FEMA - 44079 - Tennessee Titans helping residents in Tennessee.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Collins in [[Nashville]] helping clean out homes after floods damaged the city]]\nWhile a member of the New York Giants, Collins remained in therapy for four years. As a member of the [[Tennessee Titans]], he readdressed the 1997 racial slur incident, explaining that \"The guys were talking to each other that way, and I was trying to be funny and thought I could do it, too. I was so upset by it. It was bad judgment. I could have been labeled a racist for the rest of my career. I had to live with the way I used that word with a teammate. Extremely poor judgment. I was na\u00efve to think I could use that word in any context.\"<ref name=\"Young's mentor is right next to him, if only he'd reach out\">{{Cite news |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story?id=09000d5d80b1c033&template=with-video&confirm=true |title=Young's mentor is right next to him, if only he'd reach out |last=George |first=Thomas |date=September 25, 2008 |access-date=September 25, 2008 |publisher=NFL.com}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[List of NCAA major college football yearly passing leaders]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n*Reed, Steve (January 27, 2001). [http://www.gazettearchives.com/panthers2001/_article/00000335.htm Once a lost soul, Collins turns career, life around] ''The Gaston Gazette''\n*Gay, Nancy (October 3, 2004). [http://www.sfgate.com/cgi-bin/article.cgi?file=/c/a/2004/10/03/RAIDERS.TMP Collins appreciates second chances] ''San Francisco Chronicle''\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category}}\n* [http://www.titansonline.com/team/roster/Kerry-Collins/5aab2a78-008b-4d1c-bfc1-7831afc1a00d Tennessee Titans bio]\n* {{espn nfl|id=734|name=Kerry Collins}}\n\n{{Navboxes|title=Kerry Collins|list1=\n{{Penn State Nittany Lions quarterback navbox}}\n{{1994 NCAA Division I-A College Football Consensus All-Americans}}\n{{Davey O'Brien Award}}\n{{Maxwell Award Winners}}\n{{Chicago Tribune Silver Football navbox}}\n{{NFL Quarterbacks with a Perfect Passer Rating}}\n{{1995 NFL Draft}}\n{{Panthers1995DraftPicks}}\n{{PanthersFirstPick}}\n{{1995 Carolina Panthers}}\n{{Carolina Panthers starting quarterback navbox}}\n{{New Orleans Saints starting quarterback navbox}}\n{{New York Giants starting quarterback navbox}}\n{{Oakland Raiders starting quarterback navbox}}\n{{Tennessee Titans starting quarterback navbox}}\n{{Indianapolis Colts starting quarterback navbox}}\n}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Collins, Kerry}}\n[[Category:1972 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:American football quarterbacks]]\n[[Category:Carolina Panthers players]]\n[[Category:Indianapolis Colts players]]\n[[Category:New Orleans Saints players]]\n[[Category:New York Giants players]]\n[[Category:Oakland Raiders players]]\n[[Category:Penn State Nittany Lions football players]]\n[[Category:Tennessee Titans players]]\n[[Category:All-American college football players]]\n[[Category:Maxwell Award winners]]\n[[Category:People from Berks County, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:People from Lebanon, Pennsylvania]]\n[[Category:Players of American football from Pennsylvania]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American football quarterback}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox NFL biography\n|name=Kerry Collins\n|image_size=250\n|image=Kerry-Collins-TitansvsPackers-Nov-2-08.jpg\n|alt=\n|caption=Collins with the Tennessee Titans in 2008\n|number=12, 13, 5\n|position=[[Quarterback]]\n|birth_date={{Birth date and age|1972|12|30|mf=y}}\n|birth_place=[[Lebanon, Pennsylvania]]\n\n|height_ft=6\n|height_in=5\n|weight_lbs=247\n|high_school=[[Wilson High School (Pennsylvania)|Wilson]]<br/>([[West Lawn, Pennsylvania]])\n|college=[[Penn State Nittany Lions football|Penn State]]\n|draftyear=1995\n|draftround=1\n|draftpick=5\n|pastteams=\n* [[Carolina Panthers]] ({{NFL Year|1995}}\u2013{{NFL Year|1998}})\n* [[New Orleans Saints]] ({{NFL Year|1998}})\n* [[New York Giants]] ({{NFL Year|1999}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2003}})\n* [[Oakland Raiders]] ({{NFL Year|2004}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2005}})\n* [[Tennessee Titans]] ({{NFL Year|2006}}\u2013{{NFL Year|2010}})\n* [[Indianapolis Colts]] ({{NFL Year|2011}})\n|highlights=\n* 2\u00d7 [[Pro Bowl]] ([[1997 Pro Bowl|1996]], [[2009 Pro Bowl|2008]])\n* [[Maxwell Award]] (1994)\n* [[Davey O'Brien Award]] (1994)\n* [[Heisman Trophy]] finalist ([[1994 NCAA Division I-A football season#Heisman Trophy voting|1994]])\n* [[Big Ten Conference football individual honors#Offensive Player of the Year|Big Ten Offensive Player of the Year]] (1994)\n* Consensus [[College Football All-America Team|All-American]] ([[1994 College Football All-America Team|1994]])\n|statlabel1=[[Touchdown|TD]]\u2013[[Interception|INT]]\n|statvalue1=208\u2013196\n|statlabel2=Passing yards\n|statvalue2=40,922\n|statlabel3=Completion percentage\n|statvalue3=55.7%\n|statlabel4=[[Passer rating]]\n|statvalue4=73.8\n|nfl=COL620367\n|pfr=CollKe00\n|CollegeHOF = 2421\n}}\n'''Kerry Michael Collins''' (born December 30, 1972) is a former [[American football]] [[quarterback]] who played 17 seasons in the [[National Football League]] (NFL).  He played [[college football]] for [[Penn State University]] and earned [[All-American]] honors.  He was drafted by the [[Carolina Panthers]] with the fifth overall pick of the [[1995 NFL Draft]], the first choice in the franchise's history.\n\nHe also played for the [[New Orleans Saints]], [[New York Giants]], [[Oakland Raiders]], [[Tennessee Titans]], and [[Indianapolis Colts]]. He defeated every NFL team except the [[Miami Dolphins]] during his career, and threw for over 200 touchdowns. He led the [[New York Giants]] to an appearance in [[Super Bowl XXXV]], where they lost to the [[Baltimore Ravens]] by a score of 34\u20137. He was inducted into the [[College Football Hall of Fame]] in 2018.\n\n==Early years==\nCollins was born in [[Lebanon, Pennsylvania]].  He attended [[Lebanon High School (Pennsylvania)|Lebanon High School]], until 1987, when he transferred to [[Wilson High School (Spring Township, Pennsylvania)|Wilson High School]] in [[West Lawn, Pennsylvania]], and played [[high school football|football]], [[basketball]], and [[baseball]] for the Wilson Bulldogs.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://lancasteronline.com/sports/football/college/penn-state-qb-and-lebanon-native-kerry-collins-makes-college/article_5b5ebb52-f48c-11e7-8e0f-073962c32d53.html |title=Penn State QB and Lebanon native Kerry Collins makes college football hall of fame |last=Gross |first=Mike |website=LancasterOnline |language=en |access-date=2019-06-27}}</ref>\n\n==College career==\nCollins attended [[Pennsylvania State University]], where he played for coach [[Joe Paterno]]'s [[Penn State Nittany Lions football]] team from 1991 to 1994.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.sports-reference.com/cfb/players/kerry-collins-1.html |title=Kerry Collins College Stats |website=College Football at Sports-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=2019-06-27}}</ref> As a senior quarterback in 1994, he was recognized as a consensus first-team [[All-America]]n, having received first-team honors from the Associated Press, United Press International, ''The Football News'', the Football Writers Association of America, the Walter Camp Foundation and ''The Sporting News''. Collins also captured two of college football's major postseason prizes \u2014 the [[Maxwell Award]], presented to the nation's outstanding player, and the [[Davey O'Brien Award]], which goes to the nation's top quarterback.  Collins finished fourth in the [[Heisman Trophy]] balloting that year.  In addition, he was chosen UPI Back-of-the-Year and garnered Player-of-the-Year honors from ABC-TV/Chevrolet and the [[Big Ten Conference]]. Collins made a serious run at the NCAA season passing efficiency record, falling just four points short (172.8), the fourth-highest figure in NCAA annals. He broke Penn State season records for total offense (2,660), completions (176), passing yardage (2,679), completion percentage (66.7), yards per attempt (10.15) and passing efficiency (172.86). He had 14 consecutive completions at [[Minnesota Golden Gophers football|Minnesota]], another Penn State record. Collins was the [[linchpin]] of an explosive offense that shattered 14 school records and led the nation in scoring (47.8 ppg.) and total offense (520.2 ypg.). With 5,304 career passing yards, Collins ranks third in Penn State annals and is one of only three quarterbacks to top 5,000 yards through the air. With Collins at quarterback, the [[1994 Penn State Nittany Lions football team|1994 Nittany Lions]] completed an undefeated season, the fifth under coach Joe Paterno, capped by a [[1995 Rose Bowl|Rose Bowl]] win over [[Pac-10 Conference|Pac-10]] Champion [[Oregon Ducks football|Oregon]]. His team was voted #1 by the [[New York Times]], although they were voted #2 behind undefeated [[Nebraska Cornhuskers football|Nebraska]] in the traditional polls ([[AP Poll]] and [[Coaches' Poll]]) used to determine [[NCAA Division I-A national football champions|Division 1-A champions]] prior to the [[Bowl Championship Series|BCS]] era. In 2018, he was inducted into the [[College Football Hall of Fame]].\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! Season !! Comp !! Att !! Percent !! Yards !! TD !! INT !! W !! L\n|-\n| 1991 || 3 || 6 || 50.0% || 95 || 1 || 1 || 0 || 0\n|-\n| 1992 || 64 || 137 || 46.7% || 925  || 4 || 2 || 2 || 3\n|-\n| 1993 || 127 || 250 || 50.8% || 1,605  || 13 || 11 || 7 || 2\n|-\n| 1994 || 176 || 264 || 66.7% || 2,679  || 21 || 7 || 12 || 0\n|-\n| Total || 370 || 657 || 56.3% || 5,304  || 39 || 21 || 21 || 5\n|}\n\n==Professional career==\n\nCollins presently ranks 16th all-time in [[List of National Football League passing yardage leaders|NFL career passing yardage]] and 11th all-time in [[List of National Football League passing completions leaders|NFL career passing completions]]. He was less successful in terms of wins and losses, and finished with a career total of 81 regular season wins (winning percentage of .450) and three playoff wins (winning percentage of .429).  His lone Super Bowl appearance was for the New York Giants in their loss to the Baltimore Ravens in [[Super Bowl XXXV]].  He played for a large number of professional teams, and is regarded as a [[journeyman quarterback]]. In his career, he beat 31 NFL teams; the only team he never beat was the [[Miami Dolphins]], against whom he is 0-5.\n\n===Carolina Panthers===\nCollins was selected as the [[Carolina Panthers]]' first round pick (fifth overall) in the [[1995 NFL Draft]]. <ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.pro-football-reference.com/years/1995/draft.htm |title=1995 NFL Draft Listing |website=Pro-Football-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=2019-06-27}}</ref>He was the first player ever chosen by the Panthers in the annual college draft, though other players\u2014some [[free agents]], as well as players from the [[expansion draft]]\u2014had previously signed with the team. In his three seasons with the Panthers, he threw for 7,295 yards, 39 touchdowns, and 49 interceptions. His completion percentage was 52.6% and his [[quarterback rating]] was 65.6. In his second season, he led the Panthers to the [[NFC Championship]] Game.\n\nCollins threw 21 interceptions during the 1997 season and the Panthers finished 7\u20139, just one season after advancing to the NFC Championship.\n\nCarolina started the 1998 season with Collins as its starting quarterback. After an 0\u20134 start, Collins walked into head coach [[Dom Capers]]' office and, as Collins later put it, \"told Coach Capers my heart's not in it, I'm not happy, and I don't feel like I can play right now.\"<ref>{{cite news| url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/vault/article/magazine/MAG1014353/index.htm | work=CNN | title=Video | date=October 19, 1998 | accessdate=May 7, 2010}}</ref> He asked to be traded, but was instead placed on waivers by Carolina during the 1998 season and subsequently signed with the [[New Orleans Saints]] to finish the season with seven more starts but only two wins.\n\nCollins would later say that he did not intend to quit the Panthers, only to sit out for a few weeks. However, Capers interpreted his request as quitting on the team and he was released. He later admitted that much of his erratic behavior was due to his struggles with alcoholism. After being arrested for drunk driving later that year, he was ordered by the NFL to seek treatment for alcohol abuse.<ref>{{cite news|last1=King|first1=Peter|authorlink=Peter King (sportswriter)|title=Renewed and revitalized at 28, Collins finally comes clean|url=http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/inside_game/peter_king/news/2001/01/22/king_collins/|accessdate=October 23, 2014|work=[[Sports Illustrated]]|date=January 22, 2001|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20010501174807/http://sportsillustrated.cnn.com/inside_game/peter_king/news/2001/01/22/king_collins/|archivedate=May 1, 2001}}</ref>\n\n====Franchise records====\nCollins held or shared four Panthers franchise records {{as of|2017}}:\n* Passing touchdowns, rookie game (3; with [[Cam Newton]] x2)\n* Interceptions, season (21 in 1997), rookie season (19; with [[Chris Weinke]]), rookie game (4 on 1995-11-12 @STL and 1995-11-26 @NOR; with [[Chris Weinke]] and [[Cam Newton]])\n\n===New York Giants===\nCollins started the 1999 season as the Giants' second-string quarterback behind [[Kent Graham]], but claimed the starting job in Week 11 as Graham struggled with a 5\u20134 record. In the 2000 season, Collins led the Giants to [[Super Bowl XXXV]], where they lost to the [[Baltimore Ravens]]. His performance in his lone Super Bowl appearance is among the worst in [[NFL]] history. During the 2001 season, Collins set a single-season NFL record with 23 fumbles,<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/history/randf/records/indiv/fumbles |title=NFL Records |website=www.nfl.com |access-date=2019-06-27}}</ref> a record tied in 2002 by then-Minnesota Vikings quarterback [[Daunte Culpepper]]. In 2002, Collins set the Giants single season franchise passing record with 4,073 yards; the record was broken by [[Eli Manning]] in 2011. After five seasons, 68 starts and 16,875 yards, Collins was released by the Giants in 2004.<ref name=\"part ways Giants\">{{cite web|last=Best|first=Neil|title=Collins, Giants ready to part ways|url=http://buffalonews.com/editorial/20040427/1053500.asp|work=Newsday|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040501031746/http://buffalonews.com/editorial/20040427/1053500.asp|archivedate=May 1, 2004|date=April 27, 2004}}</ref>  The team had already signed former league MVP [[Kurt Warner]] and traded for 2004's #1 draft pick, Eli Manning.\n\n{{As of|2018}}, Kerry Collins held at least 7 Giants franchise records, including:\n* Most Passing Yards (playoff game): 381 (2001-01-14 MIN)\n* Most Passing TDs (playoff game): 5 (2001-01-14 MIN)\n* Most Intercepted (playoff season): 6 (2000)\n* Best Passer Rating (game): 158.3 (2002-12-22 @IND)\n* Most Pass Yds/Game (playoff career): 240.0\n* Most Pass Yds/Game (playoff season): 342.0 (2002)\n* Most 300+ yard passing games (playoffs): 2 (tied with [[Eli Manning]])\n\n===Oakland Raiders===\nAfter his release from the Giants, Collins signed a three-year, $16.82 million contract with the [[Oakland Raiders]]. Collins began the 2004 season as the team's backup to [[Rich Gannon]], but took over the starting role when Gannon suffered a neck injury in the third week of the regular season. Collins was the team's starting quarterback for the 2005 season, subsequent to Gannon's retirement.<ref>{{cite news|title=Gannon's career nears end |first=Phil |last=Barber |url=http://www.pressdemocrat.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=/20050729/NEWS/507290360/1010/SPORTS |newspaper=The Press Democrat |date=July 29, 2005 |accessdate=October 3, 2009 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20071205133421/http://www1.pressdemocrat.com/apps/pbcs.dll/article?AID=%2F20050729%2FNEWS%2F507290360%2F1010%2FSPORTS |archivedate=December 5, 2007 }}</ref>\n\nThe 2005 season started off well for Collins, but he was benched after a 34\u201310 Week 12 loss to the [[San Diego Chargers]].  He was replaced by [[Marques Tuiasosopo]]. After Tuiasosopo's 26\u201310 loss at the Jets in Week 13, Collins regained his starting job in Week 14 against the [[Cleveland Browns]] (a 9\u20137 loss at home). After two seasons and a 7\u201321 record with the Raiders, Collins was cut on March 10, 2006 in what was at least partially a move designed to free space with the salary cap.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/nfl/news/story?id=2363183 |title=Raiders cut Collins, saving $9.2 million on cap |date=2006-03-11 |website=ESPN.com |language=en |access-date=2019-06-27}}</ref>\n\n===Tennessee Titans===\nOn August 28, 2006, Collins agreed to a one-year contract with the [[Tennessee Titans]]. After three games, all losses for the Titans, Collins had completed fewer than half his passes, and had thrown one touchdown and six interceptions. [[Vince Young]], who played extensively as a substitute in the second game, started the fourth through sixth games while Collins saw no playing time in any of them. On March 5, 2007, he re-signed with the Titans.\n[[File:Manning Collins Pro Bowl.jpg|thumb|left|200px|Collins (right) and [[Peyton Manning]] at the [[2009 Pro Bowl]].]]\nAfter Young was injured against Jacksonville on September 7, 2008, Collins finished the game and was named the Titans starting quarterback for the rest of 2008 later that week. On September 21, 2008, Collins became the 15th player in NFL history to pass for more than 35,000 yards. Coming into the game against the [[Houston Texans]], Collins needed only 90 yards to eclipse the mark. On his ninth completion of 13 attempts, Collins completed a 17-yard pass to [[Justin McCareins]] to give him 107 yards on the day and 35,017 yards for his career.\n\nThe Titans finished the 2008 regular season with a record of 13\u20133, top seed in the playoffs, and a first round bye. In the divisional round they lost to the Baltimore Ravens 13\u201310. A last minute field goal by [[Matt Stover]] won the game for the Ravens.  Collins indicated after the season that he would like to play in 2009, but only as a starter.<ref>[http://blogs.nfl.com/2009/01/12/collins-i-feel-like-im-a-starter-in-this-league/ Collins: I feel like I'm a starter in this league] NFL.com, January 13, 2009</ref> Collins replaced Jets quarterback [[Brett Favre]] in the 2009 Pro Bowl, after first alternate [[Philip Rivers]] pulled out. He re-signed with the Titans on February 27, 2009. His new contract was worth $15 million, with $8.5 million guaranteed over two years.<ref name=\"resigns2009\">{{Cite web |url=http://www.nfl.com/news/story?id=09000d5d80efa6d0&template=with-video-with-comments&confirm=true |title=Titans re-sign Collins, agree to two-year deal with QB |publisher=National Football League |url-status=dead |access-date=February 27, 2009 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20090302064236/http://www.nfl.com/news/story?id=09000d5d80efa6d0&template=with-video-with-comments&confirm=true |archive-date=March 2, 2009 }}</ref>\n\n[[File:Kerry Collins and Matt Schaub.jpg|thumb|Collins (left) and [[Matt Schaub]].]]\n\nCollins returned as the team's starting quarterback for the beginning of the 2009 season. In week six the Titans were defeated by the [[New England Patriots]] 59\u20130. After that loss and a 0\u20136 record on the season, coach [[Jeff Fisher]] replaced Collins as starting quarterback with Vince Young, three days before the November 1, 2009 game against the Jacksonville Jaguars. Fisher stated that he was against this decision, saying that the problems with the team were unrelated to quarterback play, but he made the substitution after being urged by Titans owner Bud Adams to do so.<ref>{{cite news|last=Wyatt|first=Jim|title=Second chance: Titans move to Vince Young as starting QB|url=https://www.usatoday.com/sports/football/nfl/titans/2009-10-29-vince-young-kerry-collins_N.htm|publisher=USA Today|accessdate=August 9, 2010 | date=October 30, 2009}}</ref> The Titans won five straight games with Young as quarterback, and later finished the season 8\u20138.<ref>{{cite web|last=Walker|first=Teresa|title=Young, Titans win 1st of \u201909, beat Jaguars 30\u201313|url=https://sports.yahoo.com/nfl/recap;_ylt=AmfFRvCSJAvRt2hkxSorv.FDubYF?gid=20091101010|publisher=Yahoo Sports}}</ref>\n\nCollins officially announced his retirement from the NFL on July 7, 2011.<ref name=\"retirement\">{{cite news |author=Florio, Mike |title=Kerry Collins retires |url=http://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2011/07/07/kerry-collins-retires/ |work=[[profootballtalk.com]] |date=July 7, 2011 |accessdate=July 7, 2011}}</ref>\n\n===Indianapolis Colts===\nOn August 24, 2011, Collins decided to forgo his retirement plans and agreed with the [[Indianapolis Colts]] on a contract deal.<ref>{{cite web | last=Aziz | first=Andrew | title=Colts sign Kerry Collins | url=http://everything-colts.com/kerrycollinssigned.htm/ | website=everything-colts.com | date=August 24, 2011 | accessdate=August 24, 2011 | url-status=dead | archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131004220842/http://everything-colts.com/kerrycollinssigned.htm/ | archivedate=October 4, 2013 }}</ref> The contract was worth one-year and $4 million.<ref>{{cite web | url=https://www.spotrac.com/nfl/indianapolis-colts/kerry-collins-2875/cash-earnings/ | title=Kerry Collins: Career Earnings | website=spotrac.com | accessdate=January 4, 2019}}</ref>  Collins was signed as insurance for [[Peyton Manning]], who was recovering from offseason neck surgery. The Colts named Collins the starter for week one, ending Manning's streak of 227 consecutive starts (208 regular season plus 19 playoff games) and making Collins the first quarterback other than Manning to start a regular-season game for the Colts since [[Jim Harbaugh]] in week 17 of the [[1997 NFL season]].<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.nfl.com/player/jimharbaugh/2501019/gamelogs?season=1997 | title=Jim Harbaugh Game Logs: 1997 | website=NFL.com | accessdate=January 4, 2019}}</ref>  On October 25, 2011, the Colts placed Collins on injured reserve due to a concussion, ending his season.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://profootballtalk.nbcsports.com/2011/10/25/colts-send-kerry-collins-to-injured-reserve/ |title=Colts send Kerry Collins to injured reserve |last=Florio |first=Mike |date=2011-10-25 |website=ProFootballTalk |language=en |access-date=2019-06-27}}</ref>\n\nOn March 8, the Colts officially released Collins from their active roster.\n\nAfter his release, Collins did not re-sign with any team and would retire from professional football.  His 40,922 career passing yards [[List of National Football League passing yardage leaders|ranks 19th all-time]] at present, and his 3,487 completions [[List of National Football League passing completions leaders|ranks 16th all-time]] at present.\n\n==Awards==\n*Won the 1994 [[Maxwell Award]] (Nation's top college player)\n*Won the 1994 [[Davey O'Brien Award]] (Nation's top college quarterback)\n*Selected to the NFL [[1997 Pro Bowl|Pro Bowl]] following the 1996 season.\n*Selected to the NFL [[2009 Pro Bowl|Pro Bowl]] following the 2008 season.\n\n==Career statistics==\n\n===Regular season===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n! rowspan=2 | Year !! rowspan=2 | Team !! rowspan=2 | {{tooltip|GP|Games played}} !! colspan=7 | Passing !! colspan=3 | Rushing \n|-\n! {{tooltip|Cmp|Passes completed}} !! {{tooltip|Att|Passes attempted}} !! {{tooltip|Pct|Completion percentage}} !! {{tooltip|Yds|Passing yards}} !! {{tooltip|TD|Passing touchdowns}} !! {{tooltip|Int|Interceptions}} !! {{tooltip|Rtg|Passer rating}} !! {{tooltip|Att|Rushing attempts}} !! {{tooltip|Yds|Rushing yards}} !! {{tooltip|TD|Rushing touchdowns}}\n|- ALIGN=\"center\" \n| [[1995 NFL season|1995]] || [[Carolina Panthers|CAR]]\n| 15 || 214 || 432 || 49.5 || 2,717 || 14 || 19 || 61.9 || 42 || 74 || 3\n|- \n| ALIGN=\"center\" | [[1996 NFL season|1996]]\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | [[Carolina Panthers|CAR]]\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 13\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 204\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 364\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 56.0\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 2,454\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 14\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 9\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 79.4\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 32\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 38\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | 0\n|- ALIGN=\"center\"\n| ALIGN=\"center\" | [[1997 NFL season|1997]]\n| ALIGN=\"ce